<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Politics     11-01 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Politics,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Governing Party Reports on Donations from Pinball Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party said Thursday that it and 52 of
its members received more than $800,000 in donations from the
pinball industry, at the center of Japan's latest scandal over
alleged influence-buying efforts.
   Donations by the industry, known as pachinko, have been the
subject of two days of debate in Parliament this week.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party first took up published
allegations that legislators of the opposition Socialist Party used
their influence to fight efforts to tighten regulations on the
industry after receiving such donations.
   Police say the industry is a major tax-evader.
   Questions also were raised as to whether such donations violate
laws against political donations by foreigners and may have
security implications.
   Many pachinko parlor owners are Korean residents of Japan, and
an estimated 30 percent have links to Communist North Korea.
   The Socialist Party maintains close ties with the North. The
government recognizes only North Korea's capitalist rival, South
Korea.
   The pro-North Korean residents association denied making any
political donations in Japan.
   Seiji Ozawa, the Liberal Democrats' secretary-general, has
reported 52 party members received a total of $553,000 from an
association of pachinko parlor operators, said a party spokesman on
condition of anonymity.
   Ozawa also said the party itself received about $278,000 from
the association from 1972 to 1989, the spokesman added.
   Ozawa said former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita received
$12,500, former Prime Minister Takeo Fukuda received just under
$7,000 and former Chief Cabinet Secretary Masaru Gotoda $34,700.
   Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu and seven other Cabinet members
accepted $34,500 from pinball parlor owners, Ozawa said. He said he
did not include them in his list because they already publicly
announced receipt of these donations.
   The Socialists said earlier their investigation showed that
party members had received $56,000 in donations from the pinball
industry.
   Socialist Secretary-General Tsuro Yamaguchi said party officials
``found no trace of wrongdoing'' in the case.
   The Socialists urged disclosure of pinball industry donations to
the Liberal Democrats.
   The governing party was shaken earlier by sex and money
scandals. The scandals along with an unpopular sales tax led, in
elections in July, to the party's losing its majority in
Parliament's upper house for the first time in its 34-year history.
Party support has been recovering in recent public opinion polls,
however.
   In one scandal, the Recruit Co., an information and publishing
conglomerate, was accused of trying to buy influence among
prominent politicians and bureaucrats with donations and cut-price
stock sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
