<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Radio 1stLd-Writethru   11-01 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Radio, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0726,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>President To Give Occasional Radio Interviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS graf on broadcast times _ up to the participants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will begin giving occasional
interviews to radio reporters, the White House said Wednesday.
   Marlin Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, said Bush intends
to give the radio interviews on Friday afternoons. It will be ``not
every week, but occasionally,'' he added.
   The interviews will be with radio reporters who regularly cover
the White House, Fitzwater said.
   Bush has given numerous one-on-one interviews with newspapers in
his first 10 months in office, but had not made a habit of granting
radio interviews.
   Former President Reagan, a one-time broadcaster, broadcast
weekly Saturday radio talks, but Bush never copied that practice.
   Fitzwater said the interviews would be with individual radio
correspondents and ``will be exclusive to the radio receiving the
interview, just as any other interview.''
   He said the first one is not scheduled, but Bush did give an
interview Wednesday to Hal Bruno for the ABC radio network.
   Broadcast times for the interviews would be up to the outlets
participating, Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
