<FIRST>u w AM-Radiation-EPA 2ndLd-Writethru   11-01 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radiation-EPA, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0787,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Tightens Controls on Radioactive Releases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf: ``Under the,'' to remove extraneous material</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency tightened
controls Wednesday on radioactive releases from hospitals, nuclear
power plants and other facilities, although officials said in many
cases the tougher standards already are being met.
   The new regulations were issued 10 years after the federal Clean
Air Act called on the agency to establish emission standards for
radioactive byproducts. Such releases already are controlled by the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   William Rosenberg, the EPA's assistant adminstrator for air and
radiation, said the long delay in the regulations reflects the
difficulties the agency faces in reducing hazardous releases under
current federal air quality laws.
   He said some changes would shorten the process by years, such as
the proposal by President Bush to no longer require the EPA to make
risk assessment for each type of release and, instead, establish
broader requirements for industries to use the ``best available''
pollution control technology.
   So far the EPA has only established regulations for eight of the
hundreds of toxic or carcinogenic chemicals released into the air
by industry and other sources.
   The new regulations on radionuclide emissions cover nearly 7,000
facilities _ most of then hospitals, laboratories, research
facilities, atomic power plants, and uranium mines or processing
plants _ where atomic materials are used causing radioactive
byproducts to be released into the air.
   Under the new standards, the EPA aims at reducing the lifetime
risk of cancer faced by the ``most exposed'' individuals to one in
10,000. These are people who live 70 years adjacent to the
installations in question.
   Many facilities such as nuclear power plants and hospitals
already meet such stanards but some do not, the agency said.
   Richard Guimond, director of the EPA's office of radiation,
estimated that currently as many as 10,000 people may live in areas
where they are exposed to a higher than 1-in-10,000 risk level.
Under the new regulations that number would be cut to fewer than
1,000 people.
   Some environmentalists have argued the EPA should use a risk
level of 1 in 1 million even for those living close to such
facilities, but Rosenberg said such a standard would be
counterproductive since it likely would cause significant
restrictions in the use of radioactive therapy that is aimed at
saving lives.
   Guimond said the regulations likely would require no changes,
other than perhaps in record keeping, at most of the facilities _
especially hospitals, power plants and medical laboratories _
because they already meet the tighter risk standards.
   But other facilities have risk levels _ as much as 6 in 10,000
at some phosphorous plants, for example _ that will require tighter
controls on emissions to meet the new standard, he said.
   According to the EPA, tigher controls to curb radioactive
releases likely will be required at:
   _Seven of the country's 15 underground uranium mines at a cost
to the industry of $400,000 a year. As many as five of the mines
may choose instead to shut down, officials said.
   _A number of Energy Department sites where excessive radon is
released from radioactive wastes, some dating back to the early
days of the nuclear program in the 1940s and 1950s.
   _Some of the country's five operating elemental phosphorous
plants where health risks to nearby residents exceed EPA standards.
A phosphorous plant in Pocatello, Idaho likely will have to install
a $2.4 million scrubber to reduce emissions because radioactive
pollution there poses an estimated cancer risk 12 times as greater
as the 1-in-10,000 standard allows, according to the EPA.
</TEXT>
