<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Shooting     11-01 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Shooting,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Good Samaritan' in Quake Not So Good, Police Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake-South Of Market, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man depicted as a good Samaritan after
the San Francisco earthquake actually stole traffic flares from
legitimate volunteers and provoked his own shooting death, a police
official said Wednesday.
   Some news reports wrongly portrayed DeSoto Barker, a 24-year-old
former Mississippian, as a volunteer who helped police direct
traffic but was shot to death by a passing motorist upset by the
chaos, said police Inspector Michael Byrne of San Francisco.
   ``This is not a good Samaritan case,'' Byrne said in a telephone
interview.
   The Salvation Army gave the initial favorable account of
Barker's actions. But several witnesses have given a much different
version of the events leading to his death within an hour of the
Oct. 17 quake, Byrne said.
   The inspector said Barker and others apparently stole flares
from police and legitimate volunteers directing traffic on a
highway a few blocks from his home.
   Witnesses said that at one point, Barker used flares to stop
traffic so he could cross a busy street to his home, Byrne said.
   ``As he was crossing the street, he caused a motorcycle to
swerve out of his way,'' the inspector said. A neighbor,
28-year-old William Carter, criticized Barker.
   After calling each other names, ``Mr. Carter challenged Mr.
Barker to fight,'' Byrne said. Witnesses said Barker threatened to
kill Carter as he headed home.
   Barker returned five minutes later and Carter, fearing that
Barker would hurt him because Barker had been armed with a gun,
shot him, Byrne said.
   About two hours later, Carter surrendered to police. He has been
charged with murder, Byrne said.
   Barker's mother and other family members live in Jonestown in
northwest Mississippi. His body was returned there last week with
the help of the Salvation Army.
</TEXT>
