<FIRST>r i PM-WalesaAide     11-01 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walesa Aide,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Appoints Walesa Aide A Minister of State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski has
appointed an aide to Solidarity leader Lech Walesa to serve as a
minister of state responsible for contacts with parliament.
   Piotr Nowina-Konopka, an economist and head of the Solidarity
press bureau in the Baltic port of Gdansk, confirmed by telephone
Wednesday that he had accepted Jaruzelski's offer.
   Under the constitution, the president has the right to appoint
ministers of state who report to him.
   Jaruzelski also named Jozef Koziol, a member of the Peasant
Party, which forms part of the Solidarity-led coalition in
parliament, to be a minister of state, the agency reported.
   After his election to the new powerful post of president on July
19, Jaruzelski said he wanted to create a staff composed of a broad
range of political views in Poland.
   But until now, the top posts in his chancellery have gone to
Communist Party members. Jozef Czyrek, a former foreign minister
and current member of the party's Politburo, is responsbile for
foreign affairs in the presidential chancellery.
</TEXT>
