<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 2359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Asbestos     11-01 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Asbestos,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Job Exposure to Form of Asbestos Triples Death Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatively brief on-the-job exposure to a highly
toxic form of asbestos appears to dramatically increase the risk of
death from asbestos-related illnesses, according to a study
published today.
   The researchers studied 33 men who had worked in 1953 at a paper
factory that made cigarette filters containing crocidolite fibers,
a form of asbestos. Twenty-eight had died, triple the expected
death rate.
   The increased mortality was almost entirely attributable to 18
deaths from three asbestos-associated diseases _ lung cancer,
malignant mesothelioma and asbestosis. The men had worked in the
factory a median of under two years.
   Work exposure to other forms of asbestos also has been linked
with lung diseases, but crocidolite is thought to be especially
hazardous.
   The researchers said doctors should be alert to the appearance
of asbestos-related diseases from unusual sources of industrial
exposure.
   ``These results emphasize that intense, localized occupatonal
exposures to asbestos may have effects decades after the exposures
cease and that such effects may remain unrecognized and
unreported,'' they wrote in the New England Journal of Medicine.
   They said it is unclear whether smoking cigarettes with the
asbestos-laden filters increased the risk of disease.
   The study was conducted by James A. Talcott of Dana-Farber
Cancer Institute in Boston.
</TEXT>
