<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     11-01 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC's `Roseanne' First, But World Series Lag</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's World Series coverage fell in the
ratings like a Texas League fly ball but the network could take
comfort that ``Roseanne'' was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey.
   NBC was first in the ratings for last week and ABC was a close
second.
   The last two games of the earthquake-delayed World Series fared
poorly, considering that the first two games helped put ABC in
first place two weeks ago and ended NBC's record 68-week winning
streak.
   The third game between the San Francisco Giants and the Oakland
Athletics was 18th. The fourth game on Saturday, in which the A's
wrapped up the series in four straight, was 29th.
   The second game, played before the Oct. 17 earthquake delayed
the series, was 16th and the first game tied for 18th place.
Although even those ratings were off from previous years, they
still helped ABC take first place for the week.
   ABC had better luck with its football coverage. The Monday night
game between the Chicago Bears and the Cleveland Browns finished in
ninth place.
   First-place NBC's average in the Nielsen survey was 14.9, to
ABC's 14.2 and CBS' 13.0. A rating point is the percentage of the
nation's 92.1 million homes with televisions.
   Here are last week's top 10 prime-time shows: ABC's
``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's ``Cheers,'' CBS' ``60
Minutes,'' NBC's ``A Different World,'' CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,''
ABC's ``The Wonder Years,'' NBC's ``Golden Girls,'' ABC's Monday
Night Football and NBC's ``In the Heat of the Night.''
   The 27th anniversary celebration of Johnny Carson's tenure as
host of ``The Tonight Show'' was 15th.
   Fox Broadcasting Co's highest-ranked show was ``Married ... With
Children,'' in 39th place.
   ``The ABC Evening News'' was the highest-rated news show last
week. The ratings: ABC 10.3, CBS 10.0 and NBC 9.6.
   The lowest-rated network show was CBS' ``Wolf.''
   Here are the bottom five network shows: ABC's Saturday World
Series preview, CBS' ``Saturday Night with Connie Chung,'' ABC's
``Ghostbusters'' Halloween special, CBS' ``Tour of Duty'' and CBS'
``Wolf.''
