<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-01 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher in Tokyo, Stocks Recover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged against the Japanese yen on
Wednesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange recovered
morning losses to inch higher.
   The dollar closed at 143.08 yen, up 0.93 yen from Tuesday's
close of 142.15-yen close. It started at 142.80 yen and ranged
between 142.77 yen and 143.15 yen.
   Despite earlier losses of 95.5 points, the Nikkei Stock Average
of 225 selected issues rebounded in the afternoon to gain 14.99
points, or 0.04 percent, ending the day at 35,564.43. The Nikkei
gained 132.00 points Tuesday.
   Dealers said the index began to recover as individual investors
bought a range of issues in the afternoon session.
   Most market players were reluctant to make major moves ahead of
the U.S jobless rate report for October, scheduled for Friday, they
said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar was higher in Tokyo following
similar upward trends on overseas markets, traders said.
   ``Although the 142.50-yen line was a turning point for many
Japanese investors, the dollar jumped over the line overnight, and
they just let it go,'' said Yuji Nakao, a trader with Chemical Bank
in Tokyo.
   Comments Tuesday by David Mulford, U.S. Treasury Undersecretary
for International Affairs, that the dollar has shown ``modest
adjustment'' since the last meeting of seven major industrialized
nations in September also prompted dollar-buying, Nakao said.
   ``Investors saw his comments as an indication that the U.S.
central bank will no longer intervene aggressively in the market at
the current exchange rate,'' he said.
   But responding to a question from a member of the House Banking
Subcommittee, Mulford also said, ``Intervention can send signals to
the market, and that's important.''
   Nakao said the dollar-yen rate could be stuck at the current
level for a while.
   ``The U.S. economic fundamentals don't seem very good _ the
trade deficit increased last month, and the interest rate gaps
between the United States and other major industrial nations are
narrowing, although demand for the U.S. currency is still great,''
he said.
</TEXT>
