<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneBookRecycling     11-01 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Book Recycling,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recyclers Aim for Ringing Success With Old Telephone Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort involving schoolchildren and
corporations, about 120,000 old telephone directories are being
saved from Tulsa's trash-to-energy plant to be recycled into tissue
and other paper products.
   It's called Project ReDirectory, and it culminates Saturday with
the Directory Games, a kind of novelty Olympics at LaFortune
Stadium.
   ``I don't think anyone estimated the enthusiasm in this
project,'' said Wayne Campbell, spokesman for Southwestern Bell
Telephone Co. and chairman of the effort. ``This is raising
everyone's consciousness of recycling. After this is over, it's
still going to do something good for Tulsa.''
   Mayor Rodger Randle has endorsed the project and is having old
telephone directories stored in the City Hall basement, where they
will be available for schools or civic groups.
   Dozens of Tulsa's major companies are gathering their phone
books for the project, which coincides with distribution of the new
directories.
   Collection points have been set up in stores and all 31 fire
stations in the city for the four-week effort, Campbell said.
   Groups from at least a dozen schools also are collecting
telephone books. The school that arrives at the games Saturday with
the most books wins $300. The games will feature book-stacking
contests, book-balancing races, a book-throwing event and other
contests involving directories. The entry fee is one used telephone
book per person.
   Cash prizes also are provided for civic groups and individuals
who bring in the most books.
   ``They're really out hustling to get books. We're going to make
120,000. It's going to happen,'' Campbell said.
   That would represent about one-fourth of the books distributed
last year.
   Telephone directories can't be recycled as easily as newspapers
because of the glue used in the binding and the Yellow Pages
content, Campbell said.
   Directories that once brought up to $60 a ton to recyclers now
bring only about $5 a ton, he said.
   ``It's not a project anymore that can be done by Boy Scouts and
Girl Scouts. It's not a money-maker ... The bottom has dropped out
of the paper market,'' he said.
   Fort Howard Paper Co. in Muskogee has agreed to accept the books
for recycling, Campbell said.
   Until now, Campbell said, the telephone company's ``best
market'' for surplus directories was to bundle them aboard a
freighter destined for Taiwan, where the directories were made into
insulation.
   A similar recycling effort was tried last year in Tucson, Ariz.,
Campbell said. A civic group in Seattle also has gathered telephone
directories for recycling with limited success, he said.
   If the Tulsa project is as successful as sponsors hope,
Southwestern Bell will plan to make the same effort in Oklahoma
City next year when new directories are distributed there, he said.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
