<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ExxonSpill     11-01 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Spill,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say Alaska Cleanup Plan Lets Exxon Off the Hook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists say the government's plan
for assessing damages to natural resources from the Alaska oil
spill could save Exxon millions of dollars in recovery costs.
   The country's major environmental organizations said Tuesday the
plan doesn't give enough time to judge the long-term damage,
wrongly allows Exxon a part in assessing some harm, and puts too
much emphasis on direct economic costs without examining damage to
Alaska's overall ecosystem.
   ``If this draft is any indication, (President Bush) is preparing
to let Exxon off the hook,'' said Jay Hair, president of the 5.8
million-member National Wildlife Federation.
   Interior Department spokesman Bob Walker said the plan may yet
be revised and officials putting the procedures together will take
into account the criticism and changes suggested by the
environmental groups.
   ``If they (the environmentalists) have suggestions we'll be glad
to consider them,'' said Walker.
   The Interior Department drew up the plan in August and gave
interested parties until the end of October to comment. The plan
outlines procedures that federal trustees intend to use in
determining what Exxon will have to do to restore Alaska's
environment.
   The proposed plan, which will be used by the federal trustees
overseeing the damage assessment, does not set a dollar value on
possible damages, but does establish broad outlines for how damages
are to be determined.
   But environmentalists said in formal comments to the proposed
plan that it could limit the government's ability to recover all
natural resource losses.
   The environmentalists objected most strongly to a Feb. 28, 1990
deadline for the completion of environmental damage studies, saying
many long-term damages from the spill cannot be determined by then.
   The deadline is less than a year after the Exxon Valdez tanker
ran aground in Alaska's Prince William Sound, spilling more than 10
million gallons of oil. Hundreds of miles of Alaska shoreline have
been polluted and many birds and wildlife have been killed by the
oil.
   ``Oil will not disappear in a year,'' the environmental groups
said in a joint statement. They said such a deadline will ``result
in the serious underestimation of damages and inadequate recovery
from Exxon.''
   They also charged that the plan ignores the ``big picture'' and
gives too little attention to damage caused to Alaska's total
ecosystem, focusing instead on damages to resources that have
direct economic value to humans _ such as damage to the salmon and
herring fisheries.
   The environmentalists said the government should undertake a
multi-year study to determine long-term effects from the oil, which
continues to pollute hundreds of miles of Alaska shoreline.
   The critics also objected to the proposed plan's failure to
specifically exclude Exxon Corp., from taking part in making damage
assessments.
   ``Given the potential liability faced by Exxon, the company has
every incentive to minimize the damages and should not be relied on
to conduct any part of the damage assessment,'' said the
environmental organizations.
   The groups that sent a letter to Bush protesting the assessment
plan were:
   The Natural Resources Defense Council, National Wildlife
Federation, Wilderness Society, National Audubon Society,
Environmental Defense Fund, Defenders of Wildlife, the Izaak Walton
League of America, Sierra Club, National Parks &amp; Conservation
Association, Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund, Center for Marine
Conservation, Trustees for Alaska, and a coalition of the
Environmental Policy Institute, Friends of the Earth and Oceanic
Society.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-LincolnS&amp;L     11-01 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unusual Audit Conditions Set on Lincoln S&amp;L Regulators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top thrift regulators in Washington placed
unusual restrictions on an audit of Lincoln Savings and Loan
Association conducted after the rejection of an earlier
examination's conclusions, a field examiner says.
   David W. Riley, an examiner who helped last year with the second
audit of Lincoln and its holding company, American Continental
Corp., said he was not allowed to see the first report prepared by
thrift agency officials in San Francisco in 1987.
   He and his colleagues also were not permitted to see original
documents _ only copies _ he said, adding that they were told to
deal with only one Lincoln official and stay away from other top
officers, and were denied access to Lincoln's corporate
headquarters.
   ``These instructions were unusual,'' Riley said, adding that he
also was discouraged from criticizing Lincoln's high salaries.
   The examiners, sent from offices around the country to
scrutinize the operations of the Irvine, Calif.,-based Lincoln,
offered that assessment in sworn testimony Tuesday to the House
Banking Committee.
   The panel is investigating the failure of Lincoln, which was
controlled by Phoenix, Ariz., millionaire Charles H. Keating Jr.,
and is expected to become the nation's biggest thrift collapse at a
cost to the government of up to $2 billion.
   The committee is focusing on why M. Danny Wall, director of the
Office of Thrift Supervision, rejected a 1987 recommendation to
close Lincoln from his agency's San Francisco office, instead
ordering a second examination that delayed government seizure of
Lincoln until April 1989. Wall's office formerly was known as the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   Kevin O'Connell, the thrift agency supervisory agent in charge
of Lincoln, disputed Riley's complaints, saying in a telephone
interview, ``Certainly it was an unusual exam ... But the end
product was we found significant insider abuse and far more losses
than the previous exam had found ... and we were the ones who
finally seized the institution.''
   Also at Tuesday's hearing, California state savings and loan
examiner Richard E. Newsom testified that three months ago he
referred to the FBI documents showing that Keating contributed
$850,000 to three voter registration drives after he was solicited
by Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.
   The contributions have been previously reported but were not
known to be the subject of an FBI probe. They included $400,000 to
the Center for Participation in Democracy, which was run by
Cranston's son, Kim Cranston, and $325,000 for the Forum Institute,
which in 1987 gave $550,000 to a group headed by Kim Cranston
called The Organizing Institute.
   In March, Newsom also referred to the FBI a document identifying
a top aide to Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., as a principal in RA
Homes Inc., which failed to pay back a $30 million loan from
Lincoln.
   Cranston and DeConcini were two of the five senators who met
with federal regulators on Lincoln's behalf in April 1987. All five
have received campaign contributions from Keating, although
DeConcini and Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., have returned
theirs.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House panel,
said after the hearing that no decision has been made about whether
to subpoena the senators or ask them to testify. Gonzalez said
Cranston and Riegle have offered to appear before the committee.
The others are Sens. John Glenn, D-Ohio, and John McCain, R-Ariz.
   Keating's attorney, Leonard Bickwit, said Keating will appear
before the House panel as scheduled on Nov. 7, but he would not say
if the S&amp;L executive will respond to questions.
   He said allegations made against Keating Tuesday were
``groundless'' and complained that the hearings had become ``shrill
and unreasonable.''
   Meanwhile, two officials of the Seattle district of Wall's
agency testified that last year a top thrift agency official,
regulation director Darrel Dochow, urged them to consider approving
the purchase of a small ailing S&amp;L in Oregon by Lincoln.
   Patricia A. McJoynt, senior vice president of the agency's
Seattle office, said Keating acknowledged he sought the acquisition
so he could move his headquarters to Oregon and escape the
regulatory jurisdiction of the San Francisco office, which a year
earlier had recommended that Lincoln be closed.
</TEXT>
