<FIRST>r w PM-FarmPrices     11-01 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Prices,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices for Raw Farm Products Rebound</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prices farmers get for raw products are
picking up this fall, according to Agriculture Department price
watchers.
   Preliminary figures reported Tuesday showed the farm price index
rising 0.7 percent from September to October. In September, USDA
reported the monthly index dropped 0.7 percent.
   The preliminary figures for October also left the index 0.7
percent above the year-ago level.
   Higher prices for hogs, milk, lettuce and tomatoes were mostly
responsible for the increase from the September average, the
department's Agricultural Statistics Board said. Lower prices were
reported for broilers, soybeans, cattle and corn.
   ``Prices for hogs, milk and oranges were major contributors to
the increase over a year ago, but lower prices for soybeans, corn
and broilers were partially offsetting,'' the report said.
   Meanwhile, prices paid by farmers to meet expenses _ a figure
computed only every three months _ was unchanged from July but
averaged 2.9 percent more than in Oct. 1988.
   ``Compared to July, prices were up for feeder livestock but down
for feed and gasoline,'' the report said.
   A survey made twice a year showed prices farmers pay for
building and fencing material and machinery were up generally from
last spring. Fertilizer prices, however, were down from the April
survey.
   Department economists say net cash income of farmers _ gross
cash income minus cash expenses _ is expected to decline from last
year's record of $59.9 billion to a range of $52 billion to $57
billion.
   Economists say the cash income decline this year is expected to
stem from farmers' larger cash expenses as they boost plantings,
and also because of lower federal subsidies.
   USDA economists expect consumer food prices to rise about 6
percent this year, following a 4.1 percent increase in 1988. No
forecast has yet been issued by the department for 1990, but some
in the agency believe next year's increase will be less than 6
percent.
</TEXT>
