<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-IncaCrops     11-01 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inca Crops,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Research Council Pushes `Lost' Crops of Incas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's National Research Council is
telling the world where to find the ``lost'' treasures of the Incas
_ not gold, but 31 different crops that could enrich diets here and
in many other countries.
   For example, few people outside Peru and Bolivia have heard of
ahipa, a white tuber the council says is succulent, flavorful and
crisp as an apple, even when cooked. With a Bolivian variety coming
in purple or magenta stripes, it can adorn a salad while adding
flavor.
   Nearly 500 years ago, the Inca empire spread over 2,500 miles
from what is now southern Colombia to central Chile.
   But it was conquered for its gold and silver by a small band of
Spaniards under Francisco Pizarro, who executed the last Inca
ruler, Atahualpa, despite a huge ransom paid in precious metals.
   But while conquerors were searching for gold and other
treasures, the Incas were growing some 70 crops _ more than in
Europe and Asia combined.
   More than 30 of the crops still being grown are described in
``Lost Crops of the Incas,'' a 427-page volume published by the
council earlier this month.
   The potato is the one crop from the Andes mountain region that
spread quickly through the rest of the world because, the study
says, it was convenient in the silver mines and on the galleons
that carried silver to Spain.
   The Spaniards considered Inca crops inferior and insisted
European foods like carrots and barley be grown instead. But
Peruvians in remote areas still cultivate their own plants today.
   The panel found Ahipa, which has been grown in Denmark, a likely
candidate for wider modern consumption because it is small, tasty
and adaptable.
   The plant thrives even in short periods of daylight. Unlike
other root crops, it has bacteria in the root that help fertilize
it so it can grow in otherwise unfavorable areas.
   Ahipa resembles jicama, which is already sold in many
supermarkets and is popular with people who look for specialty
vegetables. The authors of the report think ahipa could be grown in
the United States and parts of Europe, Japan, Australia and New
Zealand.
   Many of the other plants could also tickle the America taste.
There's a bean that pops like popcorn, a kind of potato with a
buttery taste and another that's slightly acid so that it wouldn't
need sour cream when baked.
   There are at least five more varieties of potatoes unknown
outside the region.
   ``Some are golden yellow inside, a number have a decidedly nutty
taste, and almost all are more concentrated in nutrients than the
common potato,'' the study said.
   The hardy oca has become popular in New Zealand. It looks like a
stubby, wrinkled carrot in a variety of shades of pink, red and
yellow. The book's authors think it has a future in highland areas
and it's being tried in Nepal.
   An international conference three years ago proposed that the
seed called tarwi or chocho in Latin America be rebaptized with the
more romantic name of ``Andean lupin'' because of its brilliant
blue blossoms. It contains more protein than peas and beans, and 20
percent of the oil. Researchers are working on it in Britain, East
and West Germany, Poland and the Soviet Union.
   Some have created ``sweet'' varieties that get rid of most of
its natural bitterness so the seeds need little or no washing.
   The authors are optimistic Inca foods can win acceptance.
   ``The English refused to eat potatoes for two centuries, in part
because the Irish ate them,'' they said. ``Northern European
ignored tomatoes even longer, in part because Italians ate them and
even today in the United States, collard greens are unacceptable to
many people who consider them `poor folks food.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0035 </DOCNO>
