<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Probe     11-01 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Probe,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel to Pick Up HUD Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel will continue the investigation
of multi-billion scandals at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development now that a House committee is stymied by the refusal of
former top officials to testify.
   ``Our goal is to make sure our housing program doesn't get
sacked again,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., who was named
chairman of the special investigations subcommittee of the Senate
Banking Committee.
   ``Working with our colleagues in the House, we'll establish
causes for the breakdown at HUD and propose corrective
legislation,'' he said.
   Sen. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., chairman of the Banking Committee,
announced the new panel Tuesday and named Graham as chairman.
   Graham said no decision was made on whether the panel would seek
testimony from former HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce Jr., who has
refused to testify before a House investigative panel by invoking
constitutional guarantees against self-incrimination, or three
former aides who have also refused to testify.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the Government Operations
employment and housing subcommittee, said last week after Pierce's
second refusal to testify that his panel was about to wrap up the
hearings it began last spring.
   The subcommittee conducted a long series of hearings on
influence-peddling, fraud and mismanagement that HUD Secretary Jack
Kemp acknowledged he found at the department.
   Graham presided over a hearing Tuesday by the Senate Banking
Committee on HUD in which a pair of former Reagan White House
officials denied they exerted any influence for projects seeking
HUD grants.
   A third witness, William M. Diefenderfer III, deputy director of
the Office of Management and Budget, acknowledged ``a massive
failure of collective oversight responsibilities, which includes
OMB,'' was responsible for the HUD scandals.
   The cost of the scandals has been estimated at $2 billion to $6
billion or more.
   ``There was a particular responsibility on the Reagan
administration because they had given such a high visibility to the
elimination of waste, fraud and abuse _ that had become almost a
litany,'' Graham said.
   ``The cliche of `waste, fraud and abuse' was just that _ it was
a banner with no substance,'' he said.
   Richard H. Davis, former associate director for Cabinet affairs
at the Reagan White House, and Assistant Attorney General Carol
Crawford, who during the Reagan administration was associate
director for economics and governments at OMB, also testified.
   Davis, who was the White House liaison to HUD, said he talked
daily with Pierce's executive assistant Deborah Gore Dean, who has
cited her Fifth Amendment rights in refusing to testify before
Congress. But Davis said he only passed along correspondence or
calls the White House received from political figures or others
``with no value judgment.''
   ``I can't recall an instance where I was advocating a particular
project with Miss Dean,'' Davis said.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who has come under scrutiny in the
HUD investigations because of his active role in securing HUD
grants, offered a spirited defense of such congressional efforts in
a statement before the committee.
   He said legitimate efforts by members of Congress on behalf of
prospective HUD projects were tarnished by revelations of big fees
paid to consultants to obtain HUD grants. ``Sometimes my blood
boils when I see activities of us in the Senate lumped with'' the
HUD scandal, D'Amato said.
   Also named to the new panel, besides Graham, were: Republican
Sens. Connie Mack of Florida and Christopher Bond of Missouri; and
Democratic Sens. Richard C. Shelby of Alabama and Richard Bryan of
Nevada.
</TEXT>
