<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     11-01 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Condemns Ortega Intention to End Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has condemned Nicaraguan President
Daniel Ortega's Saturday announcement that he will cancel the
19-month cease-fire in the war with the Contras.
   A strongly worded resolution, approved 95-0 Tuesday, demands
Ortega renew his commitment to the cease-fire and conduct elections
scheduled for Feb. 25 in a free, fair and open manner.
   It expresses concern that Ortega's cancellation of the
cease-fire ``could be a prelude to a Sandinista effort to cancel or
postpone the elections.''
   ``Even Ortega's strongest apologists in Congress are having a
hard time coming up with excuses for this one,'' said Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas, referring to the declaration
made by Ortega that he would end the cease-fire because of alleged
violations by the Contras.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Bush Receives Bills Raising FHA Loan Limits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has sent President Bush a bill that
enables home buyers to obtain government-insured mortgages for more
expensive homes.
   Acting Tuesday on a voice vote and with no debate, the House in
a matter of moments gave final legislative approval to a spending
bill that included the mortgage provision.
   The measure boosts from $101,250 to $124,875 the cap on
mortgages that can be insured by the Federal Housing Administration
in most of the country's high-cost housing markets.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America estimated that the
higher cap, which will last one year, would allow 100,000
additional families to buy homes with FHA-backed loans.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Poindexter's Attorney Objects to Iran-Contra Prosecutors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for former National Security
Adviser John Poindexter contends that two newly hired Iran-Contra
prosecutors should be disqualified from handling the criminal case
against his client because they could have seen his televised
congressional testimony.
   During a federal court hearing Tuesday, attorney Richard Beckler
said independent counsel Lawrence Walsh violated his office's own
procedures by hiring Dan Webb in September to head the prosecution
team against Poindexter.
   Another member of the Poindexter prosecution team, Howard Pearl,
a longtime colleague of Webb, was hired a few weeks ago.
   At the hearing, Webb disclosed that he plans to call 46
witnesses in the government's case, including former National
Security Council aide Oliver North, who in May was convicted of
three felonies in the Iran-Contra scandal.
   Poindexter is charged with conspiracy, two counts of obstructing
Congress and two counts of making false statements. The alleged
crimes occurred in connection with North's secret resupply
operation to the Nicaraguan Contras and in regard to a shipment of
Hawk missiles to Iran in 1985 assisted by the CIA.
</TEXT>
