<FIRST>r a PM-KahaneSpeech 1stLd-Writethru a0442 11-01 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kahane Speech, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0442,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Allows University to Cancel Israeli Extrimist's Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Kahane planning to defy judge's
ruling and give speech; DELETES `BRF' designation in slug. Pick up 5th
graf pvs: `In a...'; Appearance expected around 3 p.m. EST, lead prospects
doubtful.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge allowed the University of Southern
California to cancel a speech by Rabbi Meir Kahane for security
reasons, but a spokesman for the Israeli extremist said he would
speak anyway.
   ``What I see here appears to be a bona fide concern for students
and the speaker,'' Superior Court Judge Kurt Lewin said Tuesday in
rejecting a request for a temporary restraining order against the
cancellation.
   Undeterred, Kahane planned to go ahead with today's speech, said
Ira Braverman, Los Angeles coordinator of Kach International, an
affiliate of Kahane's Kach party.
   ``The rabbi is coming regardless,'' Braverman said. ``Rabbi
Kahane will come to exercise his free speech.''
   The judge scheduled a Nov. 22 hearing on a request for a
preliminary injunction against the university. He also said The
Jewish Overview group, which was sponsoring Kahane's appearance,
could ask at the hearing for damages in the amount of Kahane's
round-trip plane fare from Israel.
   In a statement with the court, Provost Cornelius Pings said he
canceled the event Monday because Jewish and Muslim student groups
had planned demonstrations.
   USC attorney Christian Markey Jr. said the university was
willing to reschedule the event.
   Kahane's Kach party advocates expulsion of Arabs from Israel.
The Brooklyn-born rabbi founded the Jewish Defense League in New
York to mount armed responses to anti-Semitic acts.
</TEXT>
