<HEAD>Winter Moves into Plains; Indian Summer Leaves Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   November brought wintry weather to much of the country today,
with snow in the Rockies and the Plains states and a chill in the
Northeast, which had enjoyed a prolonged Indian summer.
   Snow was falling this morning from the Dakotas through Colorado,
and was forecast for today across the Great Basin and as far south
as New Mexico. Cold and strong gusts were expected in Oklahoma and
the Texas Panhandle.
   An area of strong arctic high pressure over northwest Canada was
expected to drop into the midwest Thursday and Friday, bringing
snow to Iowa, Wisconsin and possibly farther east. By Thursday, low
temperatures in the upper Midwest will fall to the teens, and highs
will reach only into the 20s and 30s.
   In the Northeast, which had enjoyed more than a week of fair and
warm weather, the forecast called for temperatures to slide into
the 50s and 60s, with rain that doused New York Tuesday moving into
New England today.
   Partly sunny skies were forecast for Virginia, Maryland and
Delaware.
   Tuesday's high temperature for the nation was 87 degrees at
Miami.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EST today:
   _East: Albany, N.Y. rain; Atlanta 50 fair; Boston 63 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 61 fair; Chattanooga 43 fair; Cincinnati 33 fair;
Cleveland 40 fair; Detroit 41 cloudy; Hatteras 65 fair;
Jacksonville 64 foggy; Key West 74 fair; Knoxville 47 partly
cloudy; Macon 52 fair; Miami 70 fair; New York 61 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 57 fair; Pittsburgh 41 cloudy; Tampa 66 foggy;
Washington, D.C. 57 fair.
   _Central: Birmingham fair; Bismarck 27 snow; Chicago 37 fair;
Denver 23 snow; Des Moines 38 fair; Indianapolis 32 fair; Kansas
City 39 fair; Little Rock 43 fair; Louisville 36 fair; Memphis 43
fair; Nashville 39 fair; New Orleans 57 cloudy; North Platte 30
