<FIRST>r i PM-CheapGizmo     11-01 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheap Gizmo,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Wants Auctioned Submarine Communications Device Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A communications device lost by a
U.S. submarine and sold at a wreckage sale for $50 turned out to be
worth a lot more, and the Americans want it back, newspapers
reported today.
   But Mogens Soerensen, the 41-year-old electrical engineer who
bought the device at the auction, has turned down a $500 offer from
the U.S. Embassy.
   The device is a paravane, which submerged submarines release
towards the surface to receive long-frequency radio messages.
   ``The components alone in the paravane are worth more (than
$500. I can't say how much I want for it. My professional interest
in the paravane can't be measured in money,'' Soerensen was quoted
as saying in the Jylland-Posten newpaper.
   Estimates of the paravane's value range from $30,000 to $800,000.
   The device, which looks like an inverted dingy with three fins
at the bow, washed ashore on Denmark's west coast last summer. It
came from an American nuclear-power submarine on patrol in the the
Atlantic, according to reports.
   Local police notified Danish naval authorities, who failed to
react to news of the find, and it was put up for auction in the
town of Hjoerring.
   The U.S. embassy is negotiating with the Danish government for
its return, the newspaper said.
   A few years ago Soerensen bought a Soviet paravane from a
fisherman who caught the receiver in his net, but Danish military
intelligence seized it.
   Soerensen, who heads an electronics workshop connected with
Denmark's state fisheries and marine research institute, has hidden
his latest acquisition until it can be sold to the highest bidder,
the newspaper B.T. said.
</TEXT>
