<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major foreign
currencies in quiet European trading today with some West German
markets and all Italian markets closed for the All Soul's Holiday.
Gold prices were lower.
   Dealers said foreign exchange markets were waiting for Friday's
release of new U.S. employment figures for confirmation that the
economy is slowing down.
   ``There isn't any clear trend,'' said a trader at a large
Frankfurt bank.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.93 yen to a closing 143.08 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 143.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8420 West German marks, up from 1.8410
   _1.6175 Swiss francs, up from 1.6142
   _6.2510 French francs, up from 6.2445
   _2.0837 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0730
   _1,350.50 Italian lire, up from 1,349.75
   _$1.1745 Canadian, up from $1.1742
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5770 to buy one pound compared with $1.5775 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $373.70 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $377.75. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $373.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $373.95 compared with $375 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.92 to close at a bid $373.87.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.18 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $5.21.
