<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Refugees     11-01 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Refugees,0274</SECOND>
<UNK>Former Norwegian Foreign Minister Prime Candidate To Fill Refugee
Post</UNK>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Norwegian Foreign Minister Thorvald
Stoltenberg has emerged as the prime candidate to fill the post of
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar consulted with
the chairmen of the U.N.'s regional groups on Monday and Tuesday
and Stoltenberg has emerged as the only candidate for the post,
officials said, requesting anonymity.
   The high commissioner for refugees is responsible for more than
12 million refugees worldwide, including 5 million Afghan refugees
in Iran and Pakistan, more than 1 million in the Horn of Africa; a
million in southern Africa, and several hundred thousand in
southeast Asia and Central America.
   The former high commissioner, Jean-Pierre Hocke, resigned last
week. The United Nations is investigating Hocke's handling of an
educational fund for refugees.
   Hocke, of Switzerland, has admitted using the funds to upgrade
airplane flights, but denied that he misused U.N. funds.
   Denmark played a key role in Hocke's downfall by questioning his
use of the educational fund and on Monday Danish Foreign Minister
Uffe Elle-Jensen conveyed the Nordic nation's support for
Stoltenberg.
   Officials said Stoltenberg is likely to also receive the
endorsement of the European Community next week.
   The General Assembly chooses a high commissioner nominated by
the secretary-general, but in practice the leading candidate is
promoted by a major contributor to the refugee agency.
   The U.S. State Department was Hocke's main proponent.
   Stoltenberg, 58, was Norway's defense minister from 1974-1976,
and was appointed again in 1979. He has also served as foreign
minister, in 1959.
</TEXT>
