<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Train-CarCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0500 11-01 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train-Car Collision, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Die When Train Crushes Car</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with victims' relationship, apparent cause
of accident; No pickup. Shcelelia is cq in 7th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALERA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A freight train crushed a car that may have
tried to beat it across the tracks, killing all five people in the
auto, including three children.
   ``It was completely demolished. It was almost like it was real
silent,'' said Nancy Utter, a reporter for KTEN-TV in Sherman,
Texas, who happened on the scene moments after the collision
Tuesday night. ``The only thing that appeared to be showing life
was a baby in an infant seat. His arms and legs were moving.''
   Sheriff B.J. Moore and Highway Patrol dispatcher Shaun Houghston
said the car was dragged a quarter-mile by the 83-car Union Pacific
train. The crossing lights were working and the crossing arms were
down when the accident occurred, the Highway Patrol reported.
   ``I guess it tried to beat the train or didn't see it,'' Moore
said.
   Julia Turnbull, 21, of Bells, Texas; her sister-in-law Dawn
Barnett, 24, of Calera, and her children Michael, 6, and Shcelelia,
5, died at the scene, authorities said.
   Ms. Turnbull's son Darwin, 1, died at Southeastern Oklahoma
Medical Center in Durant, officials said.
   Ms. Utter said lights from the railroad crossing were flashing
when she and a half-dozen other cars pulled up to help.
   ``People were yelling to get help for the people trapped,'' Ms.
Utter said.
   Calera is about 90 miles south of Oklahoma City and just north
of the Texas line.
</TEXT>
