<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CigaretteVideo     11-01 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cigarette Video,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>RJR Sends Ads Through the Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINDY ROBERTS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. has mailed
smokers videotapes to get its message on TV screens despite the
two-decade-long ban on cigarette commercials.
   The nation's second-largest cigarette maker says the 78-second
videotape commercial about its low-tar Now cigarette is targeted at
smokers of Carlton, made by American Brands in Reidsville.
   Reynolds says the videotapes do not violate Congress' intent
when it banned cigarette commercials.
   ``We're not forcing anyone to watch it. If someone is not
interested, they could simply throw it away,'' said Reynolds
spokeswoman Maura Payne.
   ``The fact is there are roughly 48 million Americans who choose
to smoke, and they have a right to know about the products,'' Ms.
Payne said Tuesday. ``We would defend our right to give customers
access to information about our brand.''
   Ms. Payne would not say how many tapes were involved in the
August mailing or how much the effort cost.
   In the commercial, an announcer compares the two low-tar brands
and suggests that Now smokers are inhaling less tar than Carlton
smokers. The tape is labeled as an advertisement and includes the
surgeon general's warning that smoking is harmful.
   Ms. Payne said the company was encouraged by a 1988 test in
which it mailed videotapes to smokers. The mailing lists come from
smokers' use of coupons and calls to a toll-free number that
provides information on smokers' rights, Ms. Payne said.
   Among those who contend the videotapes violate Congress' intent
are Phil Wilbur, director of the Health Advocacy Resource Center in
Washington, and David Hudgins, spokesman for the North Carolina
group Greensboro to Alleviate Smoking Pollution.
   ``I'm opposed to any type of cigarette advertising,'' Hudgins
said. He said that he was concerned that the videos not be mailed
at random, but that he was not questioning smokers' rights to watch
the commercials in the privacy of their own homes.
   ``I hate to be on their side, but I do believe in certain civil
rights,'' he said.
   Reynolds holds about a third of the domestic cigarette market,
second only to Philip Morris. Its Now brand has a 2.65 percent
market share, and Carlton 4.68 percent, according to the Maxwell
Consumer Report.
</TEXT>
