<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Judge-Homosexuals     11-01 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge-Homosexuals,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Official Recommends No Sanctions for Judge's Anti-Gay Comments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 1st and 7th grafs may be offensive to some
readers.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay activists reacted angrily to a report
recommending a judge be cleared of bias and misconduct charges for
calling two murder victims ``queers.''
   Special Master Robert R. Murray on Tuesday said State District
Judge Jack Hampton was wrong to comment publicly on a pending case
but that Hampton ``would be impartial in any case that came before
him.''
   ``This is like saying, `Yes, he was a bigot but he won't be one
in the future,''' said William Waybourn, president of the Dallas
Gay Alliance, which has urged Hampton's removal.
   Murray's findings will be reviewed by the State Commission on
Judicial Conduct, which could impose sanctions or begin a process
to remove Hampton from the bench.
   But Murray's report probably will ``weigh heavily'' with
commission members, said executive director Robert Flowers.
   The judge's comments came in a 1988 interview about the murder
trial of Richard Lee Bednarski, 18, sentenced by Hampton the
previous month to 30 years in prison for shooting two men in a
park. Bednarski could have received life in prison.
   ``These homosexuals by running around on weekends picking up
teen-age boys, they're asking for trouble. They really are,''
Hampton said in the interview with the Dallas Times Herald. ``I
don't much care for queers cruising the streets picking up teen-age
boys.''
   Hampton added, ``I put prostitutes and gays at about the same
level. ... And I'd be hard put to give somebody life for killing a
prostitute.''
   In his report, Murray said the statements did not reflect a bias
against homosexuals and did not discredit the judiciary.
   ``Judge Hampton has a reputation for fairness and impartiality
and has never exhibited bias or prejudice toward any group, class
or individual,'' the report said.
   The only thing Hampton did wrong, Murray said, was comment on a
case still pending because of Bednarski's efforts to get a new
trial.
   David Bryan of the Texas Human Rights Foundation, which
instigated the complaint against Hampton, asked, ``How can the
master find that Hampton made all of these comments and that
Hampton would be impartial in all of these cases?''
   Hampton would not comment on Murray's report.
   ``I'm not talking to any reporters any more,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
