<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     11-01 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Groups Demand Inquiry Into Deaths of Activists</HEAD>
<HEAD>By GREG MYRE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid groups said
today 11 activists have been killed in unsolved cases this year and
demanded a public judicial investigation.
   In Pretoria, Walter Sisulu and three other recently freed
leaders of the outlawed African National Congress today visited a
courtroom during sentencing proceedings against three white ANC
members convicted of terrorism.
   At a Johannesburg news conference today, seven anti-apartheid
groups said they supported calls for a probe of what they called
the unexplained deaths of 11 activists this year.
   ``Until the police produce evidence to the contrary, the
suspicion will continue in the minds of South Africans that death
squads with alleged police links are carrying out these
assassinations,'' said Judith Hardin of the Black Sash civil rights
organization.
   Such suspicions were heightened when a former security policeman
on Death Row said last month he was part of a police death squad.
   The Black Sash, a group made up of white women, said there have
been 61 unsolved killings of activists since 1977. The Human Rights
Commission documented 11 such deaths this year.
   In the Pretoria courtroom, the three whites embraced the ANC
leaders during a short adjournment at Pretoria Regional Court after
the presiding magistrate ordered defendants Iain Robertson and
Damian de Lange to remove neckties of green, gold and black _ the
ANC's colors. The third defendant is Susan Westcott.
   ``Greetings, comrade leaders!'' Robertson shouted upon seeing
the four men in the courtroom.
   In addition to Sisulu, 77, the visiting ANC delegation included
Ahmed Kathrada, 60; Elias Motsoaledi, 65, and Andrew Mhlangeni, 63.
The four were released unconditionally Oct. 15 after spending 26
years in prison for planning an anti-government sabotage campaign.
   The three whites pleaded guilty in June to terrorism charges and
face life in prison. Sentencing is expected within the next few
days after completion of arguments on whether the judge should
consider any mitigating circumstances.
   A senior police commander, Maj. Gen. Herman Stadler, testified
today that the ANC had recently adopted a more pragmatic approach
but remained committed to the use of violence.
   De Lange, Robertson and Ms. Westcott were arrested at a
farmhouse outside Johannesburg in May 1988. Police seized a cache
of Soviet-made weapons that included assault rifles, hand grenades,
and a SAM-7 heat-seeking missle.
   Terrorism can carry the death penalty, but the magistrate ruled
it out by conducting the trial without two lay assistants whose
presence is required when capital punishment at stake.
</TEXT>
