<DOCNO> AP891101-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Krenz     11-01 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Krenz,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Krenz Calls Protests `Good Sign,' Says No Quarrels With Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS9, MOS16</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German leader Egon Krenz said the widespread
protests in his country are ``a very good sign'' of public support
for the reforms he discussed today with President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Krenz, who said he and Gorbachev reached ``total agreement on
all questions that we discussed,'' said many of the hundreds of
thousands of pro-democracy demonstrators in East Germany's streets
were showing their support for ``the renovation of socialism.
   ``In this sense I consider this a very good sign,'' Krenz told a
Moscow news conference during his first visit since succeeding
hard-line leader Erich Honecker last month.
   Despite some negative aspects about the protests, ``the main
fact of these demonstrations is to show the goal of improving life
in East Germany,'' he said.
   Krenz's remarks, notably more positive toward the protests than
previous statements, indicated the government will tolerate
continued activism.
   Speaking forcefully in his hoarse, powerful voice and smiling
often, Krenz described an intense meeting with Gorbachev at which
the time flew by unnoticed as they discussed Soviet reforms and
their possible applications in East Germany.
   Krenz said his government's aim is to ``further strengthen
socialism in our country and start reform in all aspects of our
society.''
   He ruled out the idea of tearing down the Berlin Wall as well as
the possibility of reunification of the two Germanys.
   But he said his government plans ``to create expansive
opportunities for each citizen of East Germany to obtain a visa and
passport to go to any country in the world.''
   He said the plans for broader travel rights would be discussed
by the government, the public and Parliament.
   Krenz assumed power as the government struggled to grapple with
the exodus of tens of thousands of East Germans to West Germany and
growing public unrest at home.
</TEXT>
