<SECOND>PM-Devil's Night, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Devil's Night Fires Apparently Checked on Halloween</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with final arrest total; PICKS
UP 15th graf, `The Detroit ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three nights of curfews and 399 arrests helped
control Halloween night fires, authorities said today as they
tallied destruction from the annual arson spree known as Devil's
Night.
   Police rounded up 65 youngsters on the last night of the 6
p.m.-to-6 a.m. curfew, down from 165 on Monday and 169 on Sunday,
said spokesman Sgt. Christopher Buck. The arrests included at least
four arson suspects, he said.
   Detroit had only one confirmed arson fire on Halloween, compared
with Monday night's dozens of blazes in homes, trash bins and
garages. The Monday fires left at least five families homeless, but
no injuries were reported.
   Tracey Bryant said her home was gutted Tuesday evening.
   ``I thought it was just a cheap little joke,'' Bryant said.
``Just like an April Fool's joke. ... A stupid little joke.''
   Elsewhere, Halloween found scores of youths rampaging through
New York City, committing robberies on the streets and in
businesses and injuring at least five people, police said.
   Sixty-seven people were arrested and charged with taking part in
Tuesday's terror sprees, which began in the morning, New York
police said.
   ``Halloween was te excuse for random violence,'' said Officer
Jimmy Lee.
   ``This day every year brings out the worst,'' said Capt. Stephen
P. Davis.
   In Detroit, about 30,000 volunteers joined the battle against
Devil's Night arson this year and police were allowed to detain
minors caught on the streets without a parent.
   Most of those detained were released to their parents after
paying a $50 fine, said Robert Berg, a spokesman for Mayor Coleman
A. Young.
   City officials said the number of Devil's Night fires would not
be released until later in the day.
   The Detroit Fire Fighters Association said, however, about 285
blazes were reported Monday. If true, the number would approach
that of 1984, when 297 fires were reported on Oct. 30.
   Last year, 229 Devil's Night blazes raged, and so far this year
the number is higher, City Councilman Mel Ravitz said Tuesday.
   ``We've got to find a way to either re-educate or incarcerate
those who engage in this sport,'' he said.
   Also, 157 fires were fought in Flint on Monday, including 25
house fires, said Officer Joe Florida.
   Detroit's Devil's Night tradition began about 10 years ago with
pranks such as ringing doorbells and soaping windows. The practice
of starting fires was first acknowledged in 1983.
   The number of blazes apparently peaked in 1984, when
firefighters battled 808 fires during the last three days of
October. The number of fires has declined steadily.
</TEXT>
