<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan     11-01 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Rockets Hit Capital, Boy Killed; Plane Crashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three guerrilla rockets hit the
capital today and killed an 8-year-old boy, the government said.
Supplies began arriving in the city after government troops
dislodged rebels blocking a key highway.
   Trucks carrying flour and gasoline entered Kabul for the first
time in 11 days, a day after Soviet-backed troops cleared blockades
by U.S.-backed guerrilla forces.
   Soldiers with knowledge of the Salang Highway said two weeks'
worth of steady traffic was backed up on the road and waiting to
come to the capital.
   Most of the trucks today were privately owned vehicles. The
govermnment recently has ended its monopoly on the transportation
and sale of fuel and sugar because of shortages. Now it is relying
on private truckers to feed its people and supply them with fuel
for the winter.
   The rocket attacks came after the government had said it was
intensifying efforts to clear guerrillas from the mountains
surrounding Kabul.
   On Tuesday, reporters were shown a captured guerrilla hideout 15
miles south of the city. Tuesday night, government troops fired
dozens of rockets at the Paghman Mountains to the west, another
guerrilla stronghold.
   Since June, rocket attacks on the city have killed about 400
people and wounded 900. The government blamed the guerrillas, who
deny rocketing civilian targets and say the government is killing
its own people.
   At the United Nations, the General Assembly was expected to
approve an unprecedented resolution today calling on Afghanistan's
Communist government and the guerrillas to open negotiations on
forming a coalition government.
   The U.N. resolution called for a government of national
reconciliation that is non-aligned and Islamic. Passage of the
resolution in the General Assembly is a formality, since the Soviet
and Pakistani delegations worked out mutually acceptable language
weeks ago.
   The General Assembly had never before ordered the combatants in
the 10-year-old civil war to open peace talks, nor has it specified
the ideological or religious orientation of the resulting
government of national reconciliation.
   Under a U.N.-mediated plan, Moscow completed the withdrawal of
more than 100,000 Red Army troops on Feb. 15, more than nine years
after the first Soviet forces rolled into the country to back the
Marxist government.
   The rebels control most of the countryside but have made little
military or diplomatic progress since the Soviet withdrawal ended.
</TEXT>
