<FIRST>u i PM-Iran-US     11-01 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-US,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Passes Law Legalizing Arrests of Americans Overseas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iranian government today passed a law
allowing it to arrest Americans anywhere in the world as it
prepared for an anti-U.S. rally that officials said will include
the burning of 160 American flags.
   The new law, passed by Parliament on Tuesday, was approved by
the Council of Guardians. It gives the Iranian government the right
to arrest Americans who act against its interests anywhere in the
world and bring them to the Islamic Republic for trial by Islamic
courts.
   The Parliament members who introduced the measure said it
mirrors a similar power the U.S. government granted itself to bring
terrorists to the United States for trial.
   ``You who scream about human rights and talk about terrorism,
are yourselves innately terrorists and criminals who have taken
security away from the people of the world,'' parliament speaker
Mahdi Karrubi said on a Tehran radio broadcast monitored in Nicosia.
   The new law precedes celebrations Saturday marking the 10th
anniversary of the takeover of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran by
Iranian militants.
   As part of the celebrations, protesters will burn 160 flags
before the sprawling compound of the former embassy in downtown
Tehran, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   The 160 flags will honor 16 Kuwaiti Shiite Moslems beheaded in
Saudi Arabia for planting bombs in Mecca during the annual Moslem
pilgrimage earlier this year that killed one pilgrim and wounded 16
others.
   Iran has rebutted televised confessions by those convicted that
Tehran trained them and supplied the explosives for their mission.
The Iranians have turned the beheadings into a cause celebre,
denouncing it as a ``U.S. plot.''
   An Iranian newspaper suggested that the former captain of the
American warship Vincennes be the first person brought to trial in
Iran under the new anti-American law.
   The radical daily, Abrar, said Capt. Will Rogers II, commander
of the Navy warship when it shot down an Iran Air passenger jet
over the Persian Gulf, could be brought to trial in Iran under the
measure.
   The Vincennes shot down the plane during fighting in the gulf in
July 1988, killing all 290 people on board. The Navy said the crew
mistook the ascending passenger plane for an attacking F-14 fighter
jet.
   The new law empowers the Iranian president to take all
``necessary steps for capture and prosecution of Americans, as well
as their direct and indirect elements who have been prosecuted in
Iranian courts,'' the radio said.
   It added that citizens of countries which cooperate directly or
indirectly with America in abducting Iranian citizens, or conspire
against their lives or property of the Islamic Republic, will be
tried in Iranian courts according to Islamic principles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
