<FIRST>r a PM-NoTownMeetings 1stLd-Writethru a0434 11-01 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-No Town Meetings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0434,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plymouth, Mass., Considers Ending Town Meetings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD how often town meetings are held,
how much government participants are paid. PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `The
reformers ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some activists say the town meeting is no
longer serving the 50,000 residents of Plymouth, where America's
first such governmental gathering took place 3{ centuries ago.
   The group Government for the People wants a salaried town
manager and a 13-member town council, whose members might receive a
stipend, to replace the five selectmen and 104 town meeting
representatives.
   The selectmen, who get a $2,000 annual stipend, meet once a
week; town meetings, whose participants are volunteers, are held
once a year unless something extraordinary comes up.
   The reformers submitted a petition Monday asking that the
proposal be put before voters in April. They needed 2,900
signatures to get the measure on the ballot. They collected 3,608
and are preparing for the campaign.
   The group says Plymouth has grown too big to be governed by
part-time public servants.
   ``They just can't be responsive to the needs on a daily basis,''
said William Nolan, a former selectman and co-leader of Government
for the People.
   ``The council would be more responsive because they're elected
by geographic area. And town meeting, which has been a real
tradition in this town, is just not working.''
   Town meetings have governed Plymouth since around 1636, said
Grace Karbott, who heads the Plymouth library's reference
department and is a town meeting representative.
   Last year, voters rejected the reform proposal by 55 percent to
45 percent. Adocates of the change said voters were confused by
disputes over the ballot.
   Opponents argued that the town council, led by a manager
considerably more powerful than the executive secretary who is now
the town's top employee, would be a far less democratic form of
government.
   Selectmen proposed to amend the current charter, which was
established in 1973, when the town meeting was altered from an open
forum to one for representatives.
   ``The board of selectmen can continue to run the town,'' said
David Malaguti, a nine-year board member. ``Before we scrap the
charter, the one we have deserves modification.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
