<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Education     11-01 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>RJR Nabisco Targets $30 Million for Education Risk Takers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The RJR Nabisco Foundation announced today a
$30 million fund to support ``risk-taking'' education programs in
elementary and secondary schools.
   ``The biggest risk in education today is not taking one,'' said
Nabisco Chairman Louis Gerstner. ``Timid, fine-tuning approaches
are not up to the task of revitalizing an education system that is
failing our young people and jeopardizing the future of our nation.
   ``Our goal is to nurture risk-taking, not reward entrenched
conventional wisdom,'' he said.
   Over five years, the program, titled ``Next Century Schools,''
will make three-year grants of from $100,000 to $250,000 a year to
teachers, principals and community groups ``with bold and
innovative ideas and strategies,'' said Gerstner.
   Fifteen grants will be made this spring for fall start-up and
applications will be accepted nationwide. But, North Carolina will
receive preference the first year because it is the home of three
of RJR Nabisco's four operating companies.
   In the second and third years, the program will make grants to a
much larger number of schools in urban, suburban and rural
districts throughout the United States, officials said.
   Criteria for awarding grants include: prospects for improving
student performance; a commitment to reform shared by parents,
teachers and the community as a whole; and a plan for sustaining
and expanding the program once it proves successful.
   With Gerstner as chairman, a 17-member board will determine how
the grants will be distributed. Board members include former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, now president of the University of
Tennessee; Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton; National Education
Association President Keith Geiger; New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean;
former Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin, now a visiting fellow at the
Urban Institute; and American Federation of Teachers President
Albert Shanker.
</TEXT>
