<FIRST>r i BC-Nicaragua-Chronology     11-01 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nicaragua-Chronology,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Developments in the Nicaragua Truce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events related
to the 19-month cease-fire that was canceled Wednesday by
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 3, 1988 _ U.S. military aid to the Contras runs out as the
Sandinistas grapple with the worst economic crisis since their 1979
revolution.
   March 21, 1988 _ The Contras and the Sandinistas meet
face-to-face for the first time on Nicaraguan territory, signing an
accord in the border outpost of Sapoa, agreeing to a 60-day truce
and further talks. An unofficial truce goes into effect.
   April 1, 1988 _ The truce officially begins.
   July 1, 1988 _ The Sandinista government unilaterally renews the
truce for 30 days, setting a pattern that holds until Nov. 1, 1989,
despite scattered clashes. Contra leaders say they consider the
truce indefinite in any case.
   September 1988 _ Talks to turn the Sapoa agreement into a
lasting peace collapse. With U.S. non-lethal aid continuing, 12,000
Contra troops move out of Nicaragua into Honduran camps. Contra
field commanders say they consider the truce only a pause and
continue military training.
   Feb. 14, 1989 _ Ortega and the other Central American presidents
agree at a summit in El Salvador to devise a plan for disbanding
the rebels holed up in Honduran base camps. In exchange, Nicaragua
promises free and fair elections in 1990.
   April 18, 1989 _ President Bush signs a $49 million non-lethal
aid package for the Contras that runs through February 1990.
   Aug. 7, 1989 _ An agreement to disband and relocate the Contras
by Dec. 8 is signed at a Central American summit in Tela, Honduras.
U.S. officials note that the disbandment is voluntary and say the
Contra army should be kept in place as a guarantee of fair
elections.
   Aug. 26, 1989 _ Contra army commander Israel Galeano says his
men will ignore both the Tela accords and U.S. advice, moving their
troops back into Nicaragua to await the elections.
   Sept. 17, 1989 _ Nicaraguan Defense Minister Humberto Ortega
says the Sandinista army will not undertake offensive operations
but will act to prevent the Contras from occupying new territory.
   Oct. 22, 1989 _ The Sandinistas accuse the Contras of killing 18
peasants who were returning from military training. The Contras say
they are not launching attacks, only defending themselves.
   Oct. 27, 1989 _ Ortega, in an Jose, Costa Rica, to help
celebrate 100 years of Costa Rican peace and democracy, says the
Oct. 22 attack was the ``drop of water that made the glass spill
over'' and announces the cease-fire will end.
   Oct. 28, 1989 _ Ortega, under fire from other leaders, says a
final decision has yet to be made.
   Oct. 30 _ The Sandinistas say that another Contra attack has
killed four civilians and wounded five others.
   Nov. 1 _ After postponing a final decision for several days,
Ortega ends the 19-month-old truce, citing continued rebel attacks,
and threatens to cancel the Feb. 25, 1990 elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-ThomasNomination 1stLd-Writethru a0463 11-01 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thomas Nomination, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0463,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 12 grafs new to update with comments from civil rights activist,
picks up 8th graf pvs, Thomas has one.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Bar Association's decision to
give a key federal court nominee only a ``qualified'' rating could
bolster opposition to the nomination, a civil rights attorney said
today.
   The ABA's ``qualified'' rating given federal appellate court
nominee Clarence Thomas ``will stimulate some concern'' about the
nomination, said William Taylor, a Washington civil rights attorney.
   Thomas's seven-year tenure as chairman of the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission has drawn criticism from lawmakers and civil
rights groups who say he has undermined enforcement of age
discrimination laws.
   The ABA rating ``lends some credence to the concerns that some
of the advocacy groups have been voicing,'' said Taylor, an
official of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights.
   The group successfully lobbied last summer against the
nomination of William Lucas to head the Justice Department's civil
rights division.
   Taylor said the coalition of civil rights groups has not taken a
formal position on the nomination, even though some organizations
already have expressed opposition individually.
   ``Now that the nomination has been made, the sentiment of the
various groups will crystallize,'' Taylor said.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel on Tuesday played down
the rating of Thomas as ``qualified'' instead of ``well qualified''
to sit on the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for Washington, a court
that takes on many of the nation's most heavily spotlighted cases.
   ``Anyone who is qualified is by definition an appropriate
nominee,'' Runkel said.
   But Thomas' supporters expressed anger about the rating.
   ``I know him to be an absolutely first-rate lawyer lawyer and
beyond that I know him to be a first-rate human being,'' Sen. John
Danforth, R-Mo., for whom Thomas once worked, said Tuesday.
   ``I am concerned about what I fear might happen to my friend
Clarence Thomas when he comes before the Senate Judiciary Committee
in his hearings,'' Danforth said on the Senate floor.
   Thomas ``has one thing going against him and that is that he is
a black lawyer of fairly conservative political and judicial
philosophy,'' Danforth said.
   ``The interest groups that did a job on William Lucas in the
Senate Judiciary Committee are going to be mobilizing again to do a
job on Clarence Thomas,'' Danforth said.
   The nomination of Lucas, a black Republican, to head of the
civil rights division of the Justice Department died in committee
this year because of concerns over his qualifications and
commitment to civil rights.
   On Tuesday, the Alliance for Justice and 21 other civil rights
groups wrote Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph R. Biden
Jr., D-Del., to urge a careful investigation of Thomas' record at
EEOC.
   ``It is his actions as head of the EEOC which suggest that he
lacks the commitment to equal justice, the qualifications and the
judicial temperament for a lifetime appointment to one of the
nation's most important courts,'' said the letter.
   The ABA report card on Thomas also revived the debate over the
group's role in screening judicial candidates, which conservatives
say is heavily skewed by the panel's alleged liberal bias.
   ``The ABA has no legitimate role in judicial selection,'' said
Patrick McGuigan, senior scholar at the Free Congress Foundation's
Center for law and Democracy. ``The fact they gave a man like
Clarence Thomas a `qualified' instead of a `well qualified' is just
further evidence.''
   McGuigan noted ``roughly half'' of federal judicial nominees
have received the ``qualified'' rating from the 15-member ABA panel.
   According to the ABA's judicial screening handbook, a
``qualified'' rating means that the nominee meets minimum
qualifications for satisfactory performance as a judge.
   To be rated ``well qualified,'' a nominee ``must have the
committee's strong affirmative endorsement ... and be regarded as
one of the best available for the vacancy from the standpoint of
integrity, competence and temperament,'' the handbook said.
   ``The evaluation of qualified indicates that it appears the
prospective nominee would be able to perform satisfactorily as a
federal judge with respect to integrity, competence and
temperament,'' according to the handbook.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
