<FIRST>r a PM-MagazineSuit     11-01 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Magazine Suit,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Playboy, Waldenbooks Sue Group Protesting Adult Magazines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of retailing and publishing giants has sued
a religious organization, accusing it of using racketeering and
extortion to suppress the sale of adult magazines.
   Playboy and Waldenbooks were among those who filed the
racketeering suit against the Florida chapter of the American
Family Association.
   ``What they're doing goes far beyond rights of free speech,''
said Robert O'Donnell, Playboy Publishing Group's vice president of
retail marketing and sales. ``They're going beyond legal bounds.''
   AFA has picketed and threatened to boycott stores that carried
the targeted magazines. The publishing interests decided to sue
after the association distributed a letter in September to store
operators and corporate officers.
   The letter told the stores they were violating Florida's
obscenity statute by selling adult magazines and promised to name
those stores as violators and demand enforcement.
   The plaintiffs said the statute applies only to publishers, and
that the AFA was using the letter to harass retailers and their
customers. The AFA acknowledged in a news release that was included
in the lawsuit that the pornography statute applies only to
publishers.
   AFA has ``maliciously persisted in a pattern of racketeering
activity intended to coerce plaintiffs ... and others from
purchasing, selling or distributing magazines denominated sexually
explicit by them,'' the suit said.
   The suit said one major chain and about 1,400 convenience stores
``have acceded to defendants' extortion and ceased distributing
various publications.''
   The suit demands an end to interference, as well as triple
damages. No figures were given.
   A call to the association's state headquarters in Tampa reached
a recording saying only that a Wednesday news conference at which
the group planned to name alleged violators of the obscenity law
had been canceled. A home number for Florida leader David Caton was
unlisted.
   Forrest Ann Daniels, a spokeswoman at the association's national
office in Tupelo, Miss., said any comment would have to come from
the Florida chapter.
   For years, the AFA has campaigned against the sale of magazines
such as Penthouse and Playboy. The association, which has also
backed boycotts of TV programs it considers offensive, most
recently persuaded Matchbox to cancel sale of a Freddy Krueger
doll, based on the ghoulish killer in ``Nightmare on Elm Street''
movies.
   Americans for Consitutional Freedom, an anti-censorship group
formed by publishing trade associations, supported the lawsuit to
uphold what it called constitutionally protected publications.
   ``These types simply don't believe in freedom of choice,'' said
Oren Teicher, the group's executive director. ``If they dislike a
TV show or a magazine, they want to drive it out of the market.
That's un-American, and we're going to stop them.''
</TEXT>
