<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0523 11-01 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0523,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Condemns Oretega Action as ``Deplorable''.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 15 grafs new with latest White House reaction, picks up
6th graf pvs, The Sandinista.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration today condemned as
``deplorable'' Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega's suspension of
the cease-fire with the Contras, but steered clear of calling for
renewing military aid to the anti-Sandinista rebels.
   ``We don't want to go that route. We want to get free elections.
We want the Tela agreement to be carried out,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said at a briefing.
   ``We just don't think it's helpful to speculate on actions
beyond that,'' Fitzwater said.
   Ortega today ended the 19-month-old cease-fire and threatened at
a news conference in Managua to cancel elections scheduled next
year. He accused Bush of ``supporting terrorism in Nicaragua.''
   ``His deplorable action, which was foreshadowed during the Costa
Rican celebration of democracy, is an affront to the hemisphere and
the democratic traditions we hold so important,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said it demonstrated that the Nicaraguan government
``continues to swim against the tide'' of democracy in the region.
   It is ``obvious that (Ortega) is afraid of the ballot box,''
Fitzwater said.
   ``It's important that the world understand our emphasis is on
the elections and the democratic processes in Nicaragua, so we
continue to push for that,'' said Fitzwater. ``If Mr. Ortega wants
to pursue a military conflict, if he wants to re-open war, if he
wants to resume the killing again, that is his business.''
   ``Our purpose is to try to get the peace process back on
track,'' said Fitzwater. He said President Bush has been in contact
with other leaders in the hemisphere. He declined to name them.
   Pressed on whether the administration might consider asking
Congress anew to re-arm the rebels, Fitzwater said, ``We are
evaluating the entire situation, but we do not think it's
appropriate to speculate on military assistance.''
   He said the United States has no advice now for the Contras on
how they should conduct themselves.
   Vice President Dan Quayle, meeting separately with Afghan
resistance leaders, was also asked by reporters if the
administration had advised the Contras not to fight. ``We have made
our position very clear on the matter that we support the
cease-fire. ... '' Quayle said. ``We do not want violence. We want
peace.''
   ``Over the past decade, our hemisphere has witnessed a
tremendous growth of democracy. Unfortunately, the Nicaraguan
government continues to swim against the tide,'' Fitzwater said.
``The Sandinista unwillingness to negotiate with the Democratic
opposition, its military harrassment in the country, and now its
unilateral breaking of the cease-fire confirm President Ortega's
desire to maintain power at all costs and at the expense of the
wishes of the Nicaraguan people.
   ``One can only assume that his actions are being taken to thwart
the democratic opposition as the elections draw near. It is obvious
that he's afraid of the ballot box,'' Fitzwater said.
   When Bush was asked Tuesday about the possibility of renewed
military aid to the Contras, he told a news conference, ``I would
re-evaluate this situation in a minute if the cease-fire is
broken.''
   The Sandinista leader shocked a meeting of Western hemisphere
leaders in San Jose, Costa Rica, last Friday with his announcement
that he planned to call off the 19-month cease-fire because of
``savage attacks'' inside Nicaragua by the Contra rebels.
   A unanimous U.S. Senate on Tuesday condemned Ortega's plan to
end the cease-fire.
   A strongly worded resolution, approved 95-0, demanded that
Ortega renew his commitment to the cease-fire and conduct elections
scheduled for Feb. 25 in a free, fair and open manner.
   It expressed concern that Ortega's cancellation of the
cease-fire ``could be a prelude to a Sandinista effort to cancel or
postpone the elections.''
   ``Even Ortega's strongest apologists in Congress are having a
hard time coming up with excuses for this one,'' said Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas, referring to the declaration
made by Ortega that he would end the cease-fire because of alleged
violations by the Contras.
</TEXT>
