<DOCNO> AP891101-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-NuclearWaste     11-01 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Waste,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Recommends Building One Interim Dump For Nuclear Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government should build one
central site to store radioactive waste from nuclear power plants
until a permanent dump is ready to operate early in the 21st
century, a panel told Congress today.
   The recommendation by a congressionally ordered study group is
expected to revive a national debate over whether a temporary
storage site is necessary and safe, as well as where it would be
situated and who would pay the bill.
   The panel, which studied the issue for 18 months, recommended
that Congress authorize the construction of a temporary waste dump
capable of holding 5,000 metric tons of uranium, the fuel that
nuclear reactors use to make electricity.
   It said this would be enough to satisfy the nuclear utilities'
storage needs until the year 2006. The capital cost of the facility
was put at $500 million to $600 million.
   The panel said only those nuclear utilities that used the dump
should pay for its construction and operation.
   The Energy Department in 1987 proposed building as soon as
possible a temporary storage facility near Oak Ridge, Tenn. Later
that year, however, Congress annulled the proposal and created the
review commission to report on the need for interim storage.
   The panel is known as the Monitored Retreivable Storage Review
Commission.
   Tennessee is opposed to being the site of an interim waste dump.
The review commission did not recommend a specific site for the
dump but said it expected the siting question to be a major public
issue.
   About 20,000 metric tons of spent, or used, nuclear fuel have
accumulated at nuclear plants around the country since the start of
commercial nuclear power in the 1960s.
   Even if no more nuclear reactors were built in this country,
spent fuel from existing reactors is projected to reach 87,000 tons
by the time their licenses expire.
   Congress in 1987 ordered the Energy Department to study the
feasibility of building a permanent dump for the nuclear wastes at
Yucca Mountain in Nevada, but a series of technical and political
problems have delayed that project. The department still says the
permanent dump could open as soon as 2003, but the storage review
commission said it believed further delays were likely.
   In light of the Yucca Mountain delays, the panel recommended
building a Federal Emergency Storage facility capable of holding up
to 2,000 metric tons of uranium. Its purpose would be as a ``safety
net'' of storage capacity for emergency purposes such as an
accident at a nuclear power plant. The panel said it should be paid
for by all utilities that operate nuclear reactors.
   The 1987 law, known as the Nuclear Waste Policy Amendments Act,
also authorized the construction of an interim storage facility but
said construction could not start until a license had been issued
for the permanent dump.
   The linkage was designed to avoid the possibility _ often cited
by critics of the interim facility _ that continuing delays in
building the permanent dump could, in effect, mean waste at the
temporary site would stay there indefinitely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
