<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 4thLd-Writethru a0554 11-01 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0554,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Assassinated in West Beirut; Shiite Group Claims Responsibility</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The 16 ...,' to CORRECT date of executions to
Sept. 21, sted Sept. 24; picks up 9th: A Lebanese...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   conform
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a Saudi Arabian embassy
employee in Moslem west Beirut today and the Iran-backed Islamic
Jihad, which holds at least two Americans hostage, claimed
responsibility for the assassination.
   The group said in a statement that it killed Mohammed Ali
Marzouqi, 42, the personnel officer at the Saudi embassy in
Damascus, Syria, to avenge the recent execution in Saudi Arabia of
16 Shiite Moslems convicted of terrorism.
   The typewritten statement in Arabic was accompanied by a picture
of American hostage Terry Anderson to prove its authenticity. They
were delivered to the offices of a Western news agency in Moslem
west Beirut.
   Police said Marzouqi was visiting the Moslem sector of the
Lebanese capital when he was killed.
   Islamic Jihad is among the pro-Iran Shiite Moslem groups in
Lebanon believed to be holding eight Americans hostage. Anderson,
chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, was
captured in Beirut on March 16, 1985, and is the longest-held
Western hostage.
   The Islamic Jihad statement said: ``A few weeks ago, the rulers
of Saudi Arabia, the servants of the devil, committed a massacre
against 16 Moslem pilgrims.''
   Marzouki, it added, was ``one of the most senior Saudi security
officers in Lebanon. His activities were not hidden from the eyes
of the Mujahedeen.'' Mujahedeen is Arabic for holy warriors.
   The 16 convicted terrorists were beheaded on Sept. 21. They were
all Shiite Moslem Kuwaitis convicted of bomb attacks in the holy
city of Mecca in July in which one Pakistani pilgrim was killed and
16 wounded.
   A Lebanese police spokesman said Marzouqi was climbing into a
grey embassy limousine in the Tallet Khayyat district at 9:30 a.m.,
when three gunmen opened up with submachine guns equipped with
silencers.
   ``Death was instantaneous,'' a police spokesman said.
   Marzouqi's driver, a Syrian, suffered a gunshot wound in the
hand, said the spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations.
   Marzouqi was a frequent visitor to Beirut because he was in
charge of the affairs of the Lebanese employees of the Saudi
Embassy in Beirut, closed down since it was ransacked and burned by
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem zealots in 1985.
   His assassination was preceded by a flurry of anonymous calls to
Western news agencies in recent weeks in which men claiming to
speak for pro-Iranian factions vowed to undermine a peace accord
worked out in Taif, Saudi Arabia.
   The Arab League-sponsored accord, aimed at ending Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war, was approved Oct. 22 by Lebanon's aging
parliamentary deputies.
   Because of the civil war, which has largely pitted Christian
against Moslem militias, the country has not held parliamentary
elections since 1972.
   Iran has openly rejected the peace accord, claiming it asserts
Christian hegemony over the Moslem majority in Lebanon.
   Police said a security committee in charge of overseeing a
cease-fire brokered by the Arab League was called to an emergency
meeting to discuss Marzouqi's assassination.
   Saudi embassy employees around the world have been the target of
assassins over the past year.
   On Oct. 16, Abdelrahman Shrewi, an embassy employee in Ankara,
Turkey lost his legs in a car bomb blast. Another Saudi diplomat
was killed there in an earlier attack.
   The Saudi prayer leader in a Brussels, Belgium mosque was
assassinated in March, and an Egyptian driver working in the Saudi
Embassy there was found murdered in June. An officer of the Saudi
Embassy in Thailand was killed in Bangkok in January.
   Pro-Iranian groups in Beirut claimed responsiblity for the
assassinations.
   Also today, a newspaper quoted Christian army commander Gen.
Michel Aoun as threatening to dissolve parliament to block the
election of a new president and saying he will punish the deputies
who approved the Taif accord.
   In an interview with the conservative Ad-Diyar newspaper, Aoun
said the deputies acted outside the Constitution when they approved
the accord.
   Aoun has rejected the peace plan, which was welcomed by most
Christian groups, because it did not include a specific timetable
for the withdrawal of 40,000 Syrian troops deployed in Lebanon
since 1976.
   The Syrian troops arrived under an Arab League peacekeeping
mandate but later sided with Moslem militias against the Christians.
</TEXT>
