<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     11-01 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Envoy Meets Officials on Iran-Iraq Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Nations envoy met President Saddam
Hussein and senior officials Wednesday at the start of a new round
of shuttle diplomacy to try to get the deadlocked Iran-Iraq peace
talks moving.
   Jan Eliasson delivered a letter from U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar during the meeting, which Foreign Minister
Tariq Aziz also attended.
   The official Iraqi news agency quoted the Iraqi president as
telling Eliasson that Iraq is eager for peace while ``there is
nothing in Iran's record which testifies it is sincere in
accepting'' peace.
   The news agency earlier quoted Eliasson as saying on arrival
that his mission is aimed at ``encouraging the two countries to end
the no-war, no-peace situation.''
   He is expected to spend three weeks shuttling between Baghdad
and Tehran.
   Security Council Resolution 58 outlines a peace plan for the
eight-year war, but both sides have only accepted the cease-fire
that went into effect in August 1988. Peace talks that started with
the cease-fire stalled immediately.
   The issues that continue to hamper progress include exchange of
the 100,000 prisoners of war each side holds, withdrawel of troops
to borders both sides will agree on and control over the Shatt
Al-Arab waterway that forms the southern border between the two
countries.
</TEXT>
