<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-AIDS     11-01 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-AIDS,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Discovers First AIDS Virus Carrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first person to contract the AIDS virus in
China has been identified in Beijing, an official said Wednesday.
   The man was a former shop assistant in a Beijing food store who
had long been sexually promiscuous and had homosexual relations
with foreigners, said Cao Qing, vice director of the Department of
Epidemic Prevention in the Public Health Ministry.
   The man was detained for committing homosexual acts, a crime in
China, but left the country before it was confirmed he had the AIDS
virus, Cao said in an interview, declining to give the man's name
or whereabouts.
   ``This, in regard to our country of 1.1 billion people, is a
very dangerous signal,'' the Science and Technology Daily quoted
Cao as saying about the victim.
   One Chinese man died from the disease after contracting the
virus in the United States. Four people in Hangzhou _ one a
hemophiliac who later died from what the Chinese said were
unrelated causes _ tested positive for the AIDS virus after
transfusions with imported blood.
   But China says that none of the previous 25 cases of AIDS
infection, mostly involving foreigners, originated on the mainland.
   Despite the near non-existence of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome in China, authorities have raised a nationwide alarm about
the disase.
   All foreigners taking up residence in China must show proof that
they are AIDS-free and earlier this year legislation took effect
that gives health officials the right to test any Chinese deemed at
risk of contracting the killer disease.
   Imports of blood products have been banned and Chinese returning
from more than a year abroad must be tested for AIDS.
   The official press, television, movies and streetside billboards
have also linked AIDS to Western liberalism now being condemned by
China's conservative leaders, with the message going out that those
attracted to decadent Western ways run the risk of AIDS infection.
   A positive test for the AIDS virus detects the presence of AIDS
antibodies, meaning the person has been exposed to the virus. Those
carrying the virus could later develop AIDS.
   AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread
most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by
drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant
women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
