<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-10Years-Glance     11-01 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-10 Years-Glance,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Profile of Iran Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-10 Years-Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Iran:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LAND: Strategically situated between the Soviet Union and the
oil-rich Persian Gulf, Iran is slightly larger than Alaska. It is
ringed by mountains, and its center is largely desert covering an
area the size of France.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PEOPLE: Most of Iran's 50 million people adhere to the Shiite
branch of Islam. Ethnic Persians make up the majority, but Iran has
significant minorities of Kurds, Arabs, Turkomans and Baluchis. Two
million Iranians were displaced by the 1980-88 war with Iraq.
Another 2 million have fled abroad since the 1979 revolution.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ECONOMY: Long a leading oil producer, Iran has estimated
reserves of 100 billion barrels. The conflict with Iraq drove
revenues down from a prewar $18 billion a year in 1979 to as low as
$6 billion in recent years. Iran also has the world's
second-biggest natural gas deposits.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY: The Qajar dynasty, last in a succession of Persian
monarchies, was overthrown by military leader Reza Khan in 1925.
His son, the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, ascended the throne
in 1941 and was toppled in 1979 in an Islamic revolution that
dramatically altered the geopolitical map of the oil-rich Gulf
region.
   The seizure of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran by Iranian militants
in November 1979 led to a break in U.S. relations. Iraq invaded
Iran on Sept. 22, 1980. After initial defeats, the Iranians pushed
the Iraqis out. They later seized chunks of Iraq, but lost them in
a string of 1988 defeats and were forced to accept a United Nations
cease-fire that ended one of the century's longest conflicts.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POLITICAL STRUCTURE: As an Islamic republic, Iran's national
life closely follows guidelines set down in the Koran. It has an
elected parliament, or Majlis, but ultimate decision-making rests
in the hands of the small group of clerics. Hashemi Rafsanjani was
elected president in July. The post of prime minister has been
scrapped. Iran's supreme religious leader is Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, an ex-president who succeeded Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, the revolutionary patriarch who died last June 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FactoryOrders     11-01 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Orders,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Orders Keep Overall Factory Orders from Falling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods remained flat last month, but would have fallen had it not
been for the second largest increase in defense orders in history,
the government reported Wednesday.
   Analysts viewed the report as another sign of weakness in the
manufacturing sector, which will produce in continued sluggishness
in the overall economy in the months ahead.
   The Commerce Department said orders for both durable and
non-durable manufactured goods totaled a seasonally adjusted $236.7
billion in September. That included a 59.6 percent gain in defense
orders, to $12.7 billion, the largest advance in that category
since a record 68.3 percent advance in June 1988.
   Without the defense factor, orders actually declined 2.1
percent, the department said.
   ``It continues to show sluggishness in the manufacturing
sector,'' economist David Berson of the Federal National Mortgage
Association said of the report. ``I think we'll see it pretty flat
for a while.''
   Berson pointed to the second consecutive drop in non-defense
capital goods as an indication of things to come.
   Those orders, a barometer of business investment plans, were off
5.2 percent after dropping 10.4 percent in August.
   The economy, particularly the manufacturing and housing sectors,
have been hit hardest by high interest rates as the Federal Reserve
tightened credit in its attempt to slow inflation.
   Underlining that, the Commerce Department also reported
Wednesday that construction spending was unchanged in September
after a 1.5 percent spurt in August. But it, too, was propped up by
a 4.3 percent increase in public construction.
   Factory inventories posted their first decline since February
1987, but that was a fractional 0.1 percent fall to $371.2 billion.
If inventories increase without a corresponding gain in new orders,
it could signal production cutbacks in the future as factories
attempt to get rid of goods on shelves and backlots.
   Shipments of manufactured goods fell 1.6 percent to $234.4
billion.
   Orders for durable goods _ big-ticket items expected to last
more than three years _ rose 0.2 percent to $127 billion, boosted
by a 7.2 percent increase in electrical machinery to $20.8 billion.
   Primary metals orders were up 0.9 percent to $11.4 billion.
   But non-electrical machinery orders, including computers, were
off 0.7 percent to $22.5 billion.
   Transportation equipment orders, on the other hand, fell 4.7
percent to $34.8 billion as declines in autos and non-military
aircraft more than offset gains in military aircraft orders.
   Without the drop in transportation, total orders would have
risen 0.8 percent.
   Orders for non-durable goods were down 0.3 percent to $109.7
billion, led by a decline in food products.
   Total orders for the first nine months were 7.5 percent over
those of the same period a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-Namibia 3rdLd-Writethru   11-01 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Namibia, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0600,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa Alleges Guerrilla Incursion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 9th, `If it ...' with U.N. reaction;
picks up 10th pvs: SWAPO maintained ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today said it put
troops on alert because hundreds of Namibian guerrillas reportedly
crossed into Namibia from Angola in the past week.
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha said his country is prepared to act
even if it delays next week's U.N.-supervised elections that are a
step toward Namibian independence from South Africa, its southern
neighbor.
   Guerrilla leaders accused Botha of trying to sabotage the
election by making false allegations.
   Botha told a news conference that Foreign Affairs personnel
intercepted messages from U.N. soldiers referring to the
infiltration from Angola of more than 600 guerrillas of the
South-West Africa People's Organization between Oct. 23 and Oct. 31.
   SWAPO's secretary-general, Andimba Toivo ja Toivo, denied
Botha's assertion, saying it was ``'a concoction by the South
African government in a bid to sabotage the election.''
   ``It is well-known that the South African government sends it
own troops dressed in other armies' clothing when it wishes to
fabricate an offensive maneuver,'' Toivo said.
   Eddie Amkongo, a guerrilla spokesman in Windhoek, Namibia,
challenged Botha to prove his ``naive and childish remarks.''
   ``If it can be proved that Mr. Botha is spreading lies, days
before the people of Namibia are about to exercise their democratic
rights, SWAPO would have no choice but to assume that South Africa
has a hidden agenda.''
   But Francois Giuliani, the chief U.N. spokesman, told reporters
in New York: ``We are not aware of any such action along the
Namibian border ... This is the first we have heard of it.''
   Giuliani, responding to a question at a daily news briefing,
said Botha had telephoned the U.N. chief at 8:30 a.m. EDT ``to
inform the secretary-general of his allegations.''
Undersecretary-General Marrack Goulding, in charge of U.N.
peacekeeping operations, also was informed, he said.
   SWAPO maintained bases in Angola during its 23-year bush war
against South African rule, but is not supposed to have armed
personnel in Namibia during the transitional period. Under the U.N.
plan, South Africa also withdrew its troops from the territory.
   SWAPO is favored to get the most votes in a five-day election
starting next Tuesday for seats in an assembly that will draft a
constitution for Namibia.
   After a Cabinet meeting, Botha said he met with ambassadors of
the United States, Britain, Canada, West Germany and other Western
countries, urging them to do whatever they can ``to end this now.''
   ``The messages made it clear that SWAPO warned (United Nations)
patrols they they shouldn't interfere or they would be shot,''
Botha said. ``The tendency of (U.N. peacekeeping troops) is that
they are wishing to evacuate, to run.''
   He said the U.N. peacekeeping force is ``certainly not doing its
job, it is frightened to do it where SWAPO is involved.''
   ``Unless this is resolved within days, the South African
government is reserving the right to take whatever steps would be
required to ensure that all parties comply with their
obligations,'' Botha said. ``The South African security forces have
been put on alert.''
   Botha said military units in Walvis Bay, a South African enclave
on Namibia's coast, had been included in the alert.
   If South Africa was forced to act, Botha said, the election
definitely would be delayed.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia, a former German colony, since
1915. In December, South Africa signed accords with Angola and Cuba
agreeing to cooperate with a U.N. plan for Namibia's transition to
independence as Cuba withdraws its 50,000 troops from Angola.
</TEXT>
