<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AlcoholTesting     11-01 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alcohol Testing,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Department Proposal Would Add Alcohol Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department intends to draw
up rules that could include random testing for alcohol abuse among
workers in the transportation industry.
   Following the pattern of drug-testing rules, the department says
in a notice in Thursday's Federal Register that it is considering
several steps to combat alcohol abuse. The department asks for
public comments on alcohol problems in the transportation industry
to be submitted by Jan. 31.
   ``We ought to find ways of dealing with alcohol-impaired
operators in a safety environment,'' Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner said in an interview earlier this week. On Tuesday,
he discussed proposals for rules on alcohol-abuse testing with
trucking groups meeting in Chicago.
   Tests for alcohol abuse were not included in the Transportation
Department's drug-testing rules, which take effect in December.
Portions of the rules covering highway transportation workers _
opposed by many truckers _ have been stopped by a court injunction.
   Separately, Congress is working on legislation that would
require drug testing in the transportation industry. A Senate
measure would add alcohol testing.
   Among options being considered by the department are requiring
pre-employment, periodic, reasonable-cause, post-accident and
random alcohol testing of transportation employees in jobs where
public safety is at stake.
   Another proposal would set up programs to identify alcohol
abusers and persuade them to enter rehabilitation programs, ``with
the understanding that the identified abusers could retain their
jobs after successful rehabilitation.''
   A third proposal would establish assistance programs to educate
employees and employers on the dangers of alcohol abuse and how to
detect it on the job.
   The Federal Aviation, Highway and Railroad administrations
already have rules that prohibit drinking on the job and set a far
tougher standard for blood alcohol content among commercial
operators than the levels used by police departments to determine
intoxication.
</TEXT>
