<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ConstructionSpending     11-01 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Spending,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Stagnant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending after surging ahead in
August was unchanged last month, the government said Wednesday in
another report reflecting continued weakness in that segment of the
economy.
   The Commerce Department said residential, non-residential and
government construction spending totaled a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of $415.6 billion in September after jumping 1.5
percent in August following declines of 1.8 percent in July and 0.8
percent in June.
   Spending had spurted in August because of a strong 5.3 percent
increase in government building and a 2.9 percent gain in
non-residential construction.
   But economist David Berson of the Federal National Mortgage
Association said that pace of spending is unsustainable because of
government budget problems and a glut of vacant office buildings.
   The construction industry has been among the sectors of the
economy hardest hit by the Federal Reserve's campaign to keep
inflation in check.
   But the Fed has been easing its grip on the economy and analysts
have been looking for a slight pickup in construction spending as
interest rates fall.
   Fixed-rate mortgages declined from a peak of 11.22 percent in
March to 10.16 percent at the end of September, according to the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Private construction was off 1.2 percent last month to an annual
rate of $327.6 billion, reflecting declines in both residential and
non-residential building.
   Residential building, which accounts for nearly half of
construction spending, fell 0.9 percent to a $191.9 billion rate.
That included a drop of 1.1 percent in single-family construction
to $111.5 billion and a 2.2 percent decline in apartment building
to $22.7 billion.
   Non-residential construction, such as factories and office
buildings that represent about 20 percent of construction spending,
fell 2.6 percent to $99.1 billion at an annual rate.
   The volatile government projects category, representing another
20 percent of construction spending, was up 4.3 percent to $88
billion.
   The total construction spending figure for the first nine months
was up 1 percent from the same period of 1988.
</TEXT>
