<FIRST>u w PM-ExchangeChairman 2ndLd-Writethru a0522 11-01 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exchange Chairman, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0522,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYSE Chairman Says He Could Support Authority to Suspend Program
Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Phelan remarks; picks up pvs graf 3: ``A
lot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the New York Stock Exchange
said today he could support giving the federal government authority
to suspend program trading during times of wild swings in stock
prices.
   Chairman John J. Phelan Jr. testified before a House Commerce
subcommittee, which is considering legislation to permit the
Securities and Exchange Commission to suspend trading that is
controlled by computer program.
   ``We have to sit down with the commission to see how they feel
about such emergency powers,'' Phelan told reporters after
testifying in a closed session of the subcommittee.
   Phelan said he will take up the issue when he meets Thursday
with the board of governors of the New York exchange.
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the Commerce
subcommittee on telecommunications and finance, said disruptions
associated with broad swings in stock prices leave the impression
with many potential investors that the stock market has become
``the playground of a few privileged firms.''
   ``The bottom line is that we are messing with the golden goose _
capital formation,'' Markey said.
   Phelan said in an earlier interview with The Washington Post
that if broad price swings are left unchecked, ``it is going to
destroy the markets as a capital-raising mechanism, much less as a
place where people can invest intelligently.''
   ``A lot of people think it is a New York Stock Exchange issue,''
he said. ``It is a national issue _ liquidity in all markets and
volatility in all markets.''
   ``It affects individual investors because they get frightened to
death of this volatility that is there, and we don't blame them,''
Phelan said.
   Phelan's remarks came as he was preparing to testify today to
the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on telecommunications
and finance and meet Thursday with the exchange's board of
governors.
   The closed-door hearing on Capitol Hill was to examine the
causes of the Oct. 13 market plunge that saw the Dow Jones
industrial average plunged more than 190 points.
   Considerable criticism has been focused on the practice of
massive buying and selling triggered by computer programs that have
caused stock prices to move quickly and dramatically. Phelan
offered no specifics on what if anything should be done about the
program trading.
</TEXT>
