<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Nigeria-Rights     11-01 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Nigeria-Rights,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 2,000 Freed From Nigerian Jails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two weeks after a human rights group filed
suit against the military government in connection with dozens of
prison deaths, more than 2,000 inmates have been freed, the Justice
Ministry said Wednesday.
   The ministry also said a committee would be set up to facilitate
the release of detainees and inmates.
   The statement provided no details on who would be released. In
the past, the government has freed those awaiting trial or
convicted of minor crimes. In some cases, prisoners have waited
years to go to trial.
   The Civil Liberties Organization, a Nigerian group that has
pressed for human rights in the West African nation, alleged last
month that 78 inmates died in one prison this year because of
malnutrition, lack of medical care and inhuman conditions.
   The organization demanded $1 million in compensation for the
relatives of the dead prisoners.
   Hundreds of deaths have been reported in Nigerian prisons
recently.
   Amnesty International reported this year that jail cells and
prisons had ``grossly deficient sanitation and overcrowding,'' and
a large number of prisoners died from disease and medical neglect.
</TEXT>
