<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-DeathPenalty     11-01 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Death Penalty,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Case: Should Sympathy Be Factor in Death Penalty?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sympathy should not be a factor when a jury
decides whether a convicted murderer deserves the death penalty, a
lawyer for Oklahoma told the Supreme Court on Wednesday.
   ``We think that sympathy is among a catalogue of things that
could improperly influence the sentence,'' Oklahoma Assistant
Attorney General Robert Nance told the justices.
   Nance urged the court to reinstate the overturned death sentence
of Robyn Leroy Parks, convicted of the 1977 killing of Abdullah
Ibrahim, an Oklahoma City gas station attendant.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, while upholding Parks'
conviction, threw out his death sentence last year.
   The judge at Parks' sentencing trial told jurors, among other
things, ``You must avoid any influence of sympathy, sentiment,
passion, prejudice or other arbitrary factor when imposing
sentence.''
   The appeals court said that instruction ``undermines the jury's
consideration of mitigating evidence'' _ factors suggesting life
imprisonment rather than death as the appropriate punishment.
   Nance argued Wednesday that the appeals court was mistaken.
``This instruction ... did not construct any additional barriers to
the consideration of mitigating evidence,'' he said.
   But Vivian Berger, a New York City lawyer appointed by the
justices to represent Parks, contended that jurors could be mislead
by the anti-sympathy instruction.
   ``We have to look at this through the eyes of lay jurors,'' she
said. ``This instruction interferes with the full consideration of
mitigating evidence.''
   At Parks' sentencing trial, jurors were told about eight
mitigating factors _ most of them based on Parks' troubled
childhood.
   But Ms. Berger said jurors could have mistakenly thought that
along with avoiding any sympathy they must also avoid considering
mitigating factors presented by Parks.
   Parks ``does not assert any constitutional right to a
sympathetic jury, only a right to a sentencer not precluded from
considering any mitigating factor,'' Ms. Berger said.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia
voiced skepticism over the potential for juror confusion.
   Many of the court's questions, however, centered on whether a
decision favoring Parks could be applied retroactively to other
death row inmates across the country. Several justices said they
doubted such a ruling would have to be applied retroactively.
   That question was not among those presented by Oklahoma's
appeal, and its discussion during the oral argument session may _
or may not _ indicate at least five votes among the nine justices
to uphold Parks' victory in the appeals court.
   The justices in 1987 upheld a California murderer's death
sentence even though jurors in that case were told they should not
be swayed by ``mere sympathy.''
   The justices, by a 5-4 vote, said in the California case that a
reasonable juror would ``understand the instruction not to rely on
`mere sympathy' as a directive to ignore only the sort of sympathy
that would be totally divorced from the (mitigating) evidence.''
   The court is expected to announce its decision in Parks' case by
July.
   The case is Saffle vs. Parks, 88-1264.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
