<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Poland     11-01 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Poland,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomatic Ties Established, Seoul to Loan Warsaw $450 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea and Poland established
diplomatic relations Wednesday, and Seoul announced $450 million in
loans to the financially strapped government in Warsaw.
   Poland is the second East Bloc nation to establish ties with the
conservative Seoul government.
   The accord was signed in Seoul by South Korean Foreign Minister
Choi Ho-joong and Polish Undersecretary of State Jan Majewski.
   South Korea said it hoped the opening of relations with Warsaw
would lead to establishing ties with other socialist nations and
help ease tensions on the divided Korean peninsula.
   ``The opening of Korea-Polish diplomatic relations is expected
to have a favorable effect on efforts to establish similar
relations with other socialist countries,'' South Korea's Foreign
Ministry said.
   The agreement calls for South Korea to provide $450 million in
loans to Poland in the next five years. Also signed were trade and
investment guarantee agreements to promote mutual trade and
investment.
   President Roh Tae-woo wants to establish ties with communist
nations to reduce support for rival communist North Korea and
increase international acceptance of his own government.
   Roh hopes North Korea will pose less of a threat to regional
stability if its communist allies develop friendly relations with
Seoul and discourage any aggressive moves by the government in
Pyongyang.
   The breakthrough with Poland raised hopes among South Korean
officials that the Soviet Union may broaden ties with Seoul. The
Soviet Chamber of Commerce has established a trade office in Seoul,
but South Korea has pressed for more formal ties.
   The Korean peninsula was divided at the end of World War II.
Communist nations until recently shunned South Korea because of
their ties to North Korea.
   The daily Dong-A Ilbo newspaper said Poland originally requested
$1 billion in aid, but Korean officials said they could not afford
it. South Korea agreed to loan Hungary $120 million when it
established relations in February.
   South Korea expects to export textiles, machinery, electric and
electronic items to Poland. The 1988 bilaterial trade between the
two countries amounted to $42 million, nearly double the year
before.
</TEXT>
