<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan     11-01 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto Survives No-Confidence Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto
defeated the first no-confidence motion in Pakistan's 42-year
history Wednesday. Her opponents in Parliament claimed the vote was
rigged.
   The combined opposition mustered 107 votes in the 237-seat
National Assembly, 12 short of a majority.
   ``I have no rancor nor any ill will against those who have moved
the no-trust motion against me,'' she said after Speaker Meraj
Khalid read the tally.
   Khalid called it ``a historical moment for the country.''
   Ghulam Mustafa Jatoi, leader of the opposition sominated by the
center-right Islamic Democratic Alliance, said, ``We will bow to
the decision of the house.''
   He said at a news conference, however, that 22 members of Ms.
Bhutto's left-leaning Pakistan People's Party were confined to her
office to keep them from voting against her.
   A spokesman for the prime minister called that ``absolute
nonsense.''
   Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning party has 111 seats in the assembly
and governs with the aid of smaller parties and independents.
   She said after the vote: ``This is a time for reflection by the
government. We are exploring the possibility of negotiating with
the more moderate elements of our opposition.''
   Her supporters rose to applaud as the 36-year-old prime minister
entered the chamber before the debate wearing the colors of the
Pakistani flag _ a loose native dress of green and a white scarf.
She expects her second child by the end of the year.
   Members were given military escorts to the Parliament building,
which was surrounded by soldiers and police. Opposition legislators
had requested the special security to ensure them access to the
session.
   Authorities banned processions in Islamabad and some other
cities to prevent clashes between supporterw and opponents of the
government.
   Police in Karachi, Pakistan's largest city, said young men set a
bus ablaze and fired shots into the air, but no one was injured.
They said it was not clear whether the disturbances were related to
events in the capital.
   In Lahore, a northeastern city where no ban was imposed,
supporters of Ms. Bhutto's party chanted slogans and set off
fireworks in celebration of her victory. No violence was reported.
   Opponents accuse Ms. Bhutto's government of corruption and say
she has not pursued economic reforms they deem necessary.
   She has denied the corruption charges, but said Wednesday:
``What mistakes we've made, we've made. We're not angels.''
   The opposition put the no-confidence motion forward after a
small party of Indian immigrants who had supported the government
changed sides Oct. 23.
   Pakistan's first free elections in 11 years were held in
November 1988, three months after the death in a plane crash of
President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   Gen. Zia overthrew Ms. Bhutto's father, Prime Minister Zulfikar
Ali Bhutto, in 1977. Bhutto subsequently was convicted of plotting
to murder a political foe, who was not killed, and was hanged in
1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
