<FIRST>u a PM-DC-10CrashHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0505 11-01 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash Hearing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0505,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Metallurgist: Another Fan Disk May Have Had Flaw</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with testimony from metallurgist; EDITS to
tighten. CORRECTS first name of Nall to Joseph, sted James. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators may have found a flaw in
an engine fan made from the same batch of titanium as the DC-10
disk suspected of causing a jet crash that killed 112 people, a
metallurgist testified today.
   James Wildey II, chief metallurgist for the National
Transportation Safety Board, said, however, there was no evidence
the disk pulled from another plane could have caused an accident
similar to the July 19 crash, which 184 people survived.
   Wildey testified on the second day of a hearing on the crash of
the United Airlines jet at Sioux Gateway Airport. Investigators say
the rear engine disintegrated in fight, severing the jet's
hydraulic lines and making the plane nearly impossible to control.
   Wildey said a hairline crack in the rear engine fan disk of the
plane existed before the crash and was visible to the naked eye
after the accident. But he said it is too early to say whether the
crack could have been detected before the crash.
   Wildey made no conclusion on how long the crack had been on the
General Electric Co. engine.
   After the crash, GE pulled out of service six other engine disks
made from the same source of titanium. Wildey said preliminary
tests show a possible flaw in one of the disks but that he could
not conclude it might have led to similar engine failure.
   ``There was no evidence of any type of fatigue or crack,'' he
said, although he did not otherwise describe the possible flaw.
   NTSB investigators also said they had not concluded that the
crack was responsible for the crash. Joseph Nall, the NTSB member
in charge of the Sioux City hearing, said no final decision on the
cause will be issued for months.
   Wildey said in his report that two cracks were found in the
United jet's disk but that only one _ a hairline crack _ existed
before the engine exploded in flight.
   Wildey's report is based on testing of the fan disk, found in
two pieces in corn fields near Alta, about 80 miles east of the
airport, where the airplane cartwheeled and burst into flames as
pilots tried to make an emergency landing.
   Last week, a Federal Aviation Administration official said tests
on the disk indicated that the crack was caused by a flaw in the
metal that probably was present when the disk was built 18 years
ago.
   United spokesman Rob Doughty said Tuesday that it was too early
to pinpoint the cause of the engine explosion. He said experts have
only had 12 days to study the disk, and ``a full analysis takes two
months.''
   Phillip Battaglia, an engineering test pilot from McDonnell
Douglas, which made the DC-10, testified Tuesday that the company
had not anticipated an explosion severing all three hydraulic lines
and did not have instructions on how a pilot should deal with the
problem.
   He said that it was unlikely any instructions could help a pilot
safely land such a crippled plane.
   ``It's my opinion that this is not a trainable maneuver,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
