<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Saints     11-01 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Saints,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>World War I Doctor, Religious Order Founder Declared Saints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medic who treated Italian soldiers in
World War I trenches and an Italian priest who founded a religious
order were declared saints of the Roman Catholic church Wednesday
by Pope John Paul II.
   The pope conducted the canonization ceremony on the steps of
Saint Peter's Basilica before an All Saints' Day crowd of 30,000
people.
   John Paul described the two men as ``sensitive to the suffering,
caring toward the abandoned, participants in the anguish and
afflications of their brothers.''
   Elevated to sainthood were Riccardo Pampuri, a medic who served
on the frontline in northern Italy in World War I and later became
a physician and member of a religious order, and Gaspare Bertoni,
who founded the Stigmatine Fathers in the 19th century.
   Pampuri died in 1930 at the age of 32 from tuberculosis
contracted in the war; Bertoni died in 1853.
</TEXT>
