<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-OathofOffice     11-01 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oath of Office,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Amendment Would Delete Public Disavowal of Bribery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters get to decide Tuesday whether taking
the oath of office in Texas is undignified.
   Proposition 7 would eliminate the century-old section of the
oath to which an officeholder must swear publicly that he or she
didn't bribe anyone to get the job.
   If the proposed state constitutional amendment passes,
officeholders still would swear to faithfully execute their duties
and preserve, protect and defend the constitutions and laws of the
United States and Texas.
   And they would be required to sign a written oath denying that
any bribery took place.
   But public disavowals of bribery would be out.
   Opponents said during the legislative debate that the oath, as
it stands, is no problem. They also said such amendments clutter
the ballot and detract from more important issues.
   Secretary of State George Bayoud said he didn't find taking the
oath undignified.
   ``I kind of like it,'' Bayoud said. ``During my swearing in,
there were people from around the state here and they said they
liked it.''
   The bribery provision was added to the 1876 Texas Constitution
as a reaction to corruption during Reconstruction.
   Backers of the change say it is an outdated remnant of another
time. And it's not as if the constitutional oath were sacrosanct.
It has been changed before.
   Until approval of a 1938 amendment, officeholders were required
to swear that they hadn't participated in a duel.
</TEXT>
