<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Hot-TubKilling     11-01 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hot-Tub Killing,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murder Complaint Issued For Arrest of Former Temple Professor in
England</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDIA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Temple University professor has been
charged with killing his wife in their hot tub, but prosecutors say
they will have to bring him back from England to face charges.
   Delaware County District Attorney William Ryan Jr. announced
Tuesday that a complaint had been issued seeking the arrest in
England of Charles Bagley, who is accused of murdering his wife
March 26.
   Ryan said Bagley, a British citizen, left his home in Radnor
Township last June and returned to England with his two children
while an investigation was under way into the death of his wife,
Yvonne. Bagley resigned as a professor of finance at Temple after
his wife's death.
   Bagley claimed she was electrocuted accidentally in a whirlpool
bathtub in their home.
   The county medical examiner ruled Mrs. Bagley's death a homicide
from asphyxiation and multiple blunt injuries.
   Ryan said that after Bagley is arrested in England he will seek,
through the U.S. Justice Department and diplomatic channels,
Bagley's return to face trial.
</TEXT>
