<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1454EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Soviet-Japan     11-01 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet-Japan,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-Level Delegation to Visit Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-level Soviet parliamentary group, the first
in four years, will visit Japan this month, a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said Wednesday.
   The delegation of the Supreme Soviet will be led by Communist
Party Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, a close adviser to
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and considered to be the architect
of his policy of glasnost.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said the group's
program includes meetings with Japanese lawmakers to discuss
international problems and Soviet-Japanese relations.
   The group will visit Japan Nov. 12-19, Gerasimov said.
   The last similar visit to Japan by Soviet legislators was four
years ago.
   Improvement of relations between the two countries has been
hindered by their dispute over ownership of the Kuril Island chain,
located between the Soviet Kamchatka Peninsula and the northern
Japanese island Hokkaido.
   The Soviet Union captured the islands at the end of World War
II, and says they historically have been Russian territory. Japan
also claims a historic right to the islands.
   The dispute has prevented them from signing a treaty ending
World War II hostilities.
</TEXT>
