<DOCNO> AP891101-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-LelandSeat Bjt   11-01 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland Seat, Bjt,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eleven Vie for Mickey Leland's Congressional Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polls and political observers say it's not a
question of whether a Democrat will replace the late Mickey Leland
as representative for Houston's 18th Congressional District, it's
which Democrat among 11 candidates.
   ``This is considered to be one of the most Democratic areas of
the state, if not the nation,'' said Sherry Johnson, chairman of
the Harris County Republican Party. ``It was drawn that way as a
guaranteed seat. In the last election, something like 70 percent
voted for Michael Dukakis.''
   A special election to fill Leland's unexpired term is Nov. 7.
   Leland was killed in a plane crash in August while checking on
famine aid in Ethiopia, part of his longtime effort to focus
attention on world hunger.
   The district, a conglomeration of downtown oil company
headquarters and slums in central and northeast Houston, was
created in 1971 for Leland's predecessor, then-state Sen. Barbara
Jordan, who became one of the most prominent black women in
American politics.
   In 1980, 41 percent of the district's residents were black and
31 percent Hispanic.
   ``I don't believe there is any question that it is a Democrat's
seat,'' said Jack Carter, chairman of the Harris County Democratic
Party. ``The question is, which Democrat?''
   Seven of the 11 candidates are Democrats. Three are Republican
and one is Libertarian. The four front-runners are Democrats,
elected officials and, like Leland, black. They are State Sen.
Craig Washington, City Councilman Anthony Hall and state Reps. Ron
Wilson and Al Edwards.
   Since a candidate must have 50 percent to win the seat outright,
political observers are predicting Washington and Hall will be
forced into a runoff.
   The Houston Chronicle reported poll results Monday showing Hall
with the support of 32 percent and Washington 24 percent of
registered voters surveyed Oct. 21-25. Wilson and Edwards trailed
with 7 percent and 6 percent.
   Undecided voters totaled 30 percent, and the other seven
candidates shared 1 percent. The newspaper said its margin of
sampling error was plus or minus 6 percentage points.
   Washington, 47, a defense lawyer, served 10 years in the Texas
House and six in the Senate. He has a reputation as a champion of
liberal causes, including abortion rights, gay rights and better
AIDS care and concerns of the poor.
   ``I think this job requires one to have the courage to stand up
and make hard decisions,'' Washington said. ``I am afraid of
politicians who have no ideas of their own, but merely regurgitate
what other politicians say. You may not always agree with me, but
you always know where I stand.''
   Hall, 45, also a lawyer, has served on the City Council the past
10 years and as a state representative from 1973-78. He credits
himself with drafting a minority and women business enterprise
ordinance for the city and negotiating the city's anti-apartheid
law. He also has helped establish anti-drug ``Just Say No'' youth
clubs.
   ``Some say it is not enough to organize `Just Say No' clubs. I
have organized 50. It's not enough, but it is something,'' Hall
said.
   Wilson, 36, has been a state representative since 1977. He was a
teen-age aide to Leland in 1973. He is a law clerk and credits
himself with strengthening the House's Liquor Regulation Committee,
which he chairs. He repeatedly has sponsored bills to create a
state lottery and allow Texans to carry concealed handguns. If
elected, he wants more federal aid for education, job training and
drug control.
   Edwards, 52, a real estate and advertising salesman, has been a
legislator for 10 years. Edwards, who likes to mention his
connections to Jesse Jackson and the civil rights marches, has
focused his campaign on charges that his lawyer opponents have
conflicts of interest because ``lawyers are paid money by drug
dealers, murderers and rapists.''
   Other Democrats in the running include lawyer Shirley Fobbs and
businessmen Timothy John Hattenbach and Lee Arthur Demas Jr.
   Republicans vying for the term are lawyer Beverly Spenser,
businessman Manse R. Sharpe Jr. and educator Byron J. Johnson. Gary
Johnson, no relation, is the Libertarian candidate and is a stock
market investor who lives in Austin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
