<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Sweden     11-01 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Sweden,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Members Tear-Gassed in Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight members of the Swedish Parliament were
engulfed by tear gas fired by Israeli troops during a visit to a
Palestinian refugee camp Wednesday, but no one was seriously hurt,
a member of the delegation said.
   Per Gahrton, a legislator from the Green Party in Sweden, said
the incident occurred in the Balata Refugee Camp near Nablus.
   The incident has been reported to the Swedish consul in
Jerusalem, he said.
   Official army sources said they had no information about the
lawmakers' visit to Balata, but they said soldiers fired tear gas
in the Balata camp after an army lookout post on the edge of the
camp was hit by stones thrown by Palestinians. The sources insisted
on anonymity.
   Gahrton said the parliamentarians and about 12 members of the
Swedish-Palestinian Friendship Society took the tour, arranged with
the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which oversees aid programs for
Palestinian refugees.
   He said the group was near a school and that about 100 girls
gathered around them, cheering and shouting welcomes.
   ``Then the tear gas began,'' Gahrton said. He said he believed
it was fired from an army checkpoint on a hill above the camp.
   One gas canister fell close to legislators, John Ahlquist, who
vomited from inhaling the fumes, he said.
   One window of the U.N. bus that brought the Parliament members
to the camp was broken while it was standing idle, and a rubber
bullet was found inside, he said. Israeli soldiers fire rubber
bullets for riot control.
   The Parliament group, which arrived Monday, is touring the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The territories have
been torn by a 22-month Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule.
</TEXT>
