<FIRST>r a AM-BrickoftheMonth     11-01 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brick of the Month,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Collection One Brick Shy of a Load</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELVIDERE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meet Wes Draper, charter member of the
Brick of the Month Club. Not that he ever meant to join, but for
the past few years, they've arrived: the Valentine Brick, the Get
Well Soon Brick, the Duck Brick.
   Santa Claus has delivered them. So has the U.S Postal Service.
They've been tucked behind Draper's screen door.
   He has enough bricks to build a small well, but until Wednesday,
he could have wished all he wanted and still not known where all
the bricks were coming from.
   He had his suspicions.
   The Drapers run with Belvidere's version of the merry
pranksters. They once piled 17 people into a car, called it a
hayride and motored around this working-class town of 15,000.
   Friends have found ``For Sale'' signs posted mysteriously in
their front yards. A relative's birthday was once marked with
``Burma Shave''-type signs along the city's streets.
   On Wednesday, Draper's friend Jerry Whitehead finally confessed
he and his wife, Joan, were behind the unsolicited subscription to
Brick of the Month Club.
   ``We always thought it might be him,'' Draper said in a
telephone interview.
   Whitehead says the whole thing is Draper's fault anyway _ and
Draper allows as how that might be so.
   ``It all started when I took a vacation to Tennessee a few years
ago. They had these bricks on sale for $2 or $3,'' Draper said.
   One of the bricks was from Loew's Grand Theater in Atlanta,
where ``Gone With the Wind'' _ one of Draper's favorites _
premiered.
   Draper bought it.
   ``Back in them days, we had a cocktail party once in a while and
I used to show it off,'' he said.
   ``It was just so stupid,'' Whitehead recalls. ``We had to do
something.''
   They did.
   A big red brick arrived at the Draper home a short time later.
   ``Dear Mr. Draper,'' said the unsigned letter accompanying it,
``It is ... a great pleasure to allow you to become an honorary
member of the Brick of the Month Club.''
   ``Since then, boy, I got a lot of bricks,'' Draper said.
   Santa Claus delivered a Christmas brick, with a Currier and
Ives-type print on one side.
   ``We asked Santa where it came from,'' said Draper's wife,
Marion. ``Santa Claus just ho-ho-ho-ed and wouldn't talk about it.''
   A ``Happy Valentines'' brick came in parts with an elaborate
blueprint for reassembly, a process requiring the placement of
arrows into holes at either end.
   He received a tiny ``bonus brick'' to hook on his key chain.
   People stopped Draper on the street to ask him about his bricks.
The town mayor gave him one. In all, there were more than two dozen
in his collection.
   He gave a speech to the local Kiwanis Club on the subject:
``Please keep in mind that brick collecting is becoming very
popular ...''
   The Whiteheads said they finally decided enough was enough and
on Wednesday revealed their secret to Draper in a newspaper article.
   ``I don't dare tell you'' how the score will be evened, Draper
said.
   ``I'll sure enough have to take him out to supper, won't I?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0131 </DOCNO>
