<FIRST>r w AM-US-Burma     11-01 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Burma,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Rejects Allgeations about Envoy in Burma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department rejected on Wednesday
accusations by Burma's official media that U.S. Ambassador Burton
Levin has interfered in Burma's internal affairs with comments
criticizing the country's human rights performance.
   Deputy spokesman Richard Boucher called the charge baseless and
said Levin's ``activities and statements, and those of his embassy
colleagues, are governed by instructions from Washington.''
   Boucher had no details on the articles critical of Levin. He
said Levin has no plans to return to Washington as the result of
the dispute.
   ``We continue to be deeply concerned by the house arrest of the
co-leaders of Burma's principal opposition party, the National
League for Democracy, as well as the mass arrests this summer of
large numbers of political opponents of the military government,''
he said.
   Boucher said the United States hopes the Burmese government will
release all political prisoners and will allow them to take part in
the national elections planned for next May.
   ``In our view, elections which exclude participation of those
who represent Burmese aspirations for democratic change _ that is,
the aspirations which the Burmese people clearly desire _ cannot be
regarded as free and fair,'' he said.
