<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PrenatalCare     11-01 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prenatal Care,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>1 in 6 U.S. Women Get Inadequate Prenatal Care</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One in six American women gets inadequate
prenatal care, according to a study released Wednesday.
   Pregnant women in the South are the most likely to receive
inadequate care, while those in the North Central region of the
country get the highest level of care, the study by the Alan
Guttmacher Institute found.
   The study estimated that 585,000 women nationally begin care in
the fifth month of pregnancy or later, or begin receiving prenatal
care early but make fewer than half of the 13 doctor visits
recommended by the American College of Obstetricians and
Gynecologists.
   A disproportionate number of women receiving this level of care,
which the institute considers inadequate, are teen-agers, unmarried
women, blacks and Hispanics, according to the report.
   More than 660,000 women, or 18 percent of women who give birth,
begin receiving prenatal care early but make only half to 80
percent of the recommended visits, the survey found.
   ``This study demonstrates how very far we have to go, as a
nation, if we are to guarantee that all women get even relatively
adequate prenatal care,'' said Jeannie Rosoff, president of the New
York-based non-profit research and education group.
   The Department of Health and Human Services in 1980 set as one
of the nation's health goals to be achieved by the end of the
decade that at least 90 percent of women would start prenatal care
within the first three months of pregnancy.
   The study concluded that prenatal services must become more
available and more accessible to decrease the number of babies born
prematurely and underweight, chief causes of infant mortality.
   The U.S. rate of infant mortality is 10.4 per 1,000, ranking the
country 19th among industrialized nations.
   The institute said more public funding would be needed to
provide more needed services, but it didn't estimate how much.
   The report estimated that 15.7 percent of pregnant women in the
United States receive what the institute considers inadequate
prenatal care. The report found 18.8 percent of women in that
category in the South, 16.5 percent in the West, 14.4 in the
Northeast and 12.3 percent in the North Central states.
   The report was based on data from the National Center for Health
Statistics and the American Hospital Association, as well as a
survey of all state health departments and some local health
departments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Flight103 4thLd-Writethru a0629 11-01 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0629,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pan Am Aims to Prove Israel, West Germany Warned US of Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 13, The papers, to attribute to court papers statement
that Mossad issued warnings.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan American World Airways is trying to prove
that Israel and West Germany warned U.S. authorities about an
impending terrorist attack on Flight 103 which was blown up last
December, according to papers filed in federal court.
   Pan Am has filed subpoenas demanding documents on any advance
warning given to the CIA, the Drug Enforcement Administration, the
FBI, the National Security Council, the National Security Agency
and the State Department.
   The airline also is demanding to question, beginning in
mid-November, anyone at the six agencies with knowledge of any
prior notice given to the U.S. government indicating that Flight
103 was targeted for attack, according to the documents.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh refused today to comment on the
subpoenas, except to say the Justice Department would give them
``due consideration'' and respond in court.
   The court papers said Pan Am and its security firm, Alert
Management Systems Inc., were taking action to prove West German
police warned U.S. officials of suspicious activities in the
baggage area at Frankfurt 90 minutes before the flight left there
Dec. 21.
   The airline said it is seeking a possible videotape of the
baggage containing the bomb being loaded in Frankfurt onto the
Boeing 727 that flew to London on the first leg of the New
York-bound flight.
   The airline, in papers filed in court in Brooklyn, N.Y., and
Washington, D.C., also said it wanted ``all documents concerning
warnings, tips, alerts, and other communications'' about possible
plans or threats of a terrorist attack on Flight 103.
   The London newspaper The Independent, which first reported the
court filings, quoted lawyers for families of Flight 103 victims as
saying Pan Am was on a ``fishing exercise'' to try to shift blame
for the disaster. The airline has been sued for more than $300
million.
   Lee Kreindler, an attorney representing the victims' families,
called the Pan Am subpoenas ``a lot of nonsense'' and a
``diversionary tactic.''
   It's ``probably an exercise by the public relations department
of Pan Am'' that ``won't have any effect'' on his case and ``won't
get anywhere,'' said Kreindler.
   The Boeing 747 that passengers boarded in London exploded over
Lockerbie, Scotland, killing all 259 people aboard and 11 on the
ground.
   The documents filed by Pan Am call on the six U.S. agencies ``to
disclose any documents relevant to surveillance by the BKA (West
Germany's FBI) of the Pan Am baggage-handling area at Frankfurt,
including video recordings made on the evening of 21 December
1988.''
   The papers demand all documents relating to what they say were
warnings from the Israeli secret service Mossad ``within the 24-36
hours before December 21, 1988, that Pan Am Flight 103 ... was the
target of a terrorist attack.'''
   The British government has said it received telephone warnings
of a bomb on a U.S. carrier in the weeks prior to Dec. 21, and U.S.
diplomats in Europe had been told to avoid Pan Am during the
Christmas season.
   Paul Hudson, an Albany lawyer who lost his 16-year-old daughter
on the plane, said his reaction to Pan Am's demand was ``oe of
shock ... one of dismay, followed by a furious reaction by most of
the relatives.''
   Hudson, chairman of a group called Families of Pan Am Flight
103, also predicted a ``tremendous outcry for accountability'' if
authorities ``knew that this flight or one very close to it was to
be bombed.''
   A CIA spokesman would not comment today on the allegations that
the Mossad warned the agency of the bombing 24 hours before it
happened. CIA spokesman Mark Mansfield said by telephone from
McLean, Va., that the CIA was among U.S. agencies subpoenaed by Pan
Am lawyers. He said he had no further comment on the case because
it is in litigation.
   The Independent's report said at least five people on the doomed
plane were U.S. government employees, either members of the CIA or
attached to it. It said the five included Matthew K. Gannon, a
political officer at the U.S. Embassy in Beirut who, it said, was
the CIA's deputy station chief in Lebanon.
   The paper said intelligence sources believe the team was on a
mission in Beirut connected to the American hostages there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ExchangeChairman     11-01 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exchange Chairman,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phelan Says He Could Support Government Stock Trading Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chairman John J. Phelan Jr. of the New York
Stock Exchange said Wednesday he could support allowing the federal
government to halt program trading when share prices drop too
rapidly.
   Phelan, who testified at a closed session of a House Commerce
subcommittee, said in earlier interviews that if left unchecked,
price volatility could destroy the stock market.
   The telecommunications and finance subcommittee, headed by Rep.
Edward Markey, D-Mass., is ready to draft legislation that would
give the Securities and Exchange Commission authority to halt
computer-programmed trading when prices move wildly.
   ``We have to sit down with the commission to see how they feel
about such emergency powers,'' Phelan told reporters after the
subcommittee session. The New York exchange could support such a
grant of power if the commission feels capable of administering it,
he said.
   Phelan pledged to work with Congress to find a solution. He will
meet Thursday with governors of the exchange amid speculation the
Big Board may take new action of its own to battle the volatility
problem.
   Phelan indicated he would like to see the Chicago markets join
with the New York exchange in any action aimed at curbing broad
swings in share prices.
   In earlier newspaper interviews, Phelan acknowledged wide
discontent among investors and brokers about how program trading of
huge blocs of stock can induce wild price swings that make many
people hesitant about buying shares.
   ``A lot of people think it is a New York Stock Exchange issue,''
he said. ``It is a national issue _ liquidity in all markets and
volatility in all markets. If it keeps up long enough, it is going
to destroy the markets as a capital-raising mechanism, much less as
a place where people can invest intelligently,'' he told The
Washington Post.
   His fears were echoed by Markey and other members of the
subcommittee.
   ``The bottom line is that we are messing with the golden goose _
capital formation,'' Markey said. ``The stock market matters. It's
not disconnected from ordinary people's lives ... It assures jobs
are there for blue-collar Americans.''
   Wednesday's hearing was scheduled after the Dow Jones Industrial
Average dropped 190 points during a wild day of computer-generated
trading on Oct. 13.
   ``Congress is ready to move'' with legislation aimed at
correcting the violatility problem, Markey said. ``There is a real
sense in our committee that something has to be done.''
   The New York exchange moved on its own last year to respond to
big swings in price. The exchange halted program trading through
its own computers any time the industrial averages moved 50 points
in one day. Traders quickly found a way around the prohibition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     11-01 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORONADO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter says he wouldn't
accept a million-dollar speaking fee like his successor, Ronald
Reagan, reportedly received during his recent trip to Japan.
   But, ``I've never been offered that much,'' Carter joked Tuesday
night before speaking to San Diego County business leaders about
Habitat for Humanity, a non-profit group that helps low-income
families build their own homes.
   Carter refused to criticize Reagan directly for reportedly
accepting $2 million in speaking fees during his trip to Japan,
including $1 million for a single speech to the Fujisankei
Communications Group last week in Tokyo.
   ``I've never criticized what presidents Nixon, Ford or Reagan do
with their post-White House years,'' he said when asked about
Reagan's fees. ``But that's not what I want out of life. We give
money, we don't take it.''
   Carter did criticize the scandal-plagued government housing
programs of the Reagan administration.
   ``It was absolutely disgusting to see a whole bunch of rich
friends of the president stealing millions of dollars from a
program that had already been robbed of 85 percent of its
resources,'' Carter said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rolling Stones, in town
for concerts Wednesday and Thursday, played cat-and-mouse with
photographers and fans.
   Mick Jagger, out for a Tuesday afternoon jog, jumped into a
trailing limousine when he spotted a TV crew.
   Jagger, wearing a gray sweatsuit and dark glasses, had popped
out of an elevator earlier at the Four Seasons Hotel, where the
rock 'n' roll band and its entourage have 10 suites on three
floors. He sprinted through the lower lobby with his entourage and
jumped into a waiting taxi. The official limo already had driven
off, apparently as a decoy.
   Hotel security guards and Stones' handlers used walkie-talkies
working on their strategy to avoid the curious and the media.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Version also on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Yankees outfielder Luis Polonia,
jailed for having sex with a 15-year-old girl, was temporarily
released by a judge Wednesday because the Dominican Republic
native's work visa had expired.
   Polonia, who had served 27 days of his 60-day sentence, also has
a contract to play winter baseball in his own courntry.
   He was ordered to return Feb. 1 to Milwaukee to serve the
balance of his sentence, said Circuit Judge Thomas Doherty.
   Doherty said that, if Polonia is not granted another employment
visa to return to the United States, he must do 90 hours of
community service in the Dominican Republic.
   Polinia, 24, pleaded no contest in August to a charge of having
sexual intercourse with a child. Besides the jail sentence, he was
fined $1,500 and ordered to contribute $10,000 to the Sinai
Samaritan Medical Center's sexual assault treatment center.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning author Alice Walker
says the violence in some of her writing is an outgrowth of her
childhood as the daughter of Georgia sharecroppers.
   ``It was a bad system where people could not get out of debt,''
Ms. Walker told about 600 people Tuesday at Temple University. ``We
lived in shacks. I was 17 before I lived in a house that didn't
leak.
   ``I was trying for myself to understand how this system of human
exploitation so killed the spirit of people ... that they were
unable to love their own. And why is it that they turned on their
own?''
   Ms. Walker also read from her latest novel, ``The Temple of My
Familiar,'' whose characters' stories span several lives over
thousands of years.
   She said the far-reaching settings from Latin America to
California, to Baltimore and Africa, show the similarity in
oppression of people throughout the world and how their struggles,
and origins, are connected.
</TEXT>
