<FIRST>r a AM-PilotReturns     11-01 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilot Returns,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot of United 232 Returns From Leave Following Iowa Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-DC-10 Crash Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capt. Al Haynes, the United Airlines pilot who
guided his disabled DC-10 to a crash landing at Sioux City, Iowa,
is back in the cockpit after a 3{-month leave.
   Haynes' wife, Darlene, and their daughter Laurie, were at
Seattle-Tacoma International Airport on Tuesday to see Haynes fly a
United DC-10 to San Francisco on the first leg of a three-day trip
across the country.
   ``It's time to get back,'' Haynes, 57, said.
   Haynes's heroic efforts during the July 19 crash of United
flight 232 helped save the lives of 184 of the 296 people aboard
the flight.
   A failed fan blade in an engine damaged the plane's hydraulic
system and robbed the cockpit crew of most of their control over
the plane.
   Haynes, with the help of an off-duty pilot aboard the flight,
used the two remaining engines to bring the plane down at the Souix
City airport.
   Tuesday's flight experienced no problems.
   One passenger, told Haynes was the pilot, said he was reassured.
   ``I'm glad to have him,'' said Dean Coonrod of Seattle. ``I know
he was a hell of a pilot.''
</TEXT>
