<FIRST>r a AM-Book-Jail     11-01 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Book-Jail,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Jailed Overnight Because of Overdue Library Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORCROSS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman jailed overnight when she failed to
appear in court to explain overdue library books said she is sure
she returned the books and was never told of the court date.
   Karen Lindsay, 48, said Tuesday she was arrested at her
apartment Friday night and held without bond until she was released
on her own recognizance Saturday.
   Ms. Lindsay said she was asleep when a Gwinnett County sheriff's
deputy arrived with the arrest warrant charging her with failure to
appear in court, which carries a maximum sentence of one year in
jail and a $1,000 fine.
   ``The police were very nice to me and acted quite embarrassed
over the whole ordeal,'' she said.
   John Shelton, director of the Lake Lanier Regional Library
system, said the library has been turning over offenders to the
courts since 1983 to face charges of failure to return library
books.
   ``I sympathize with the lady but most of my sympathy is with the
people,'' he said. ``Taxpayers should not have to pay more for
libraries because of unreturned books.''
   Ms. Lindsay pleaded innocent Monday to a charge of failure to
appear in State Court. No arraignment date had been set.
   She said she was shown a list of four books she allegedly did
not return, but she couldn't remember any of the titles and found
no unreturned library books when she moved recently.
   The library said the books were 15 months overdue, ``but would I
deserve to go to jail because of it?'' Ms. Lindsay asked.
   Ms. Lindsay said authorities knew she never received a summons
to appear in court because it had been returned to them unopened.
</TEXT>
