<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Scandal     11-01 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Scandal,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norwegian May Head Scandal-Plagued Refugee Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Norwegian Foreign Minister Thorvald
Stoltenberg will be nominated to head the scandal-plagued U.N. High
Commission for Refugees, the top U.N. spokesman said Wednesday.
   The former high commissioner, Jean-Pierre Hocke, resigned Oct.
26 over charges he misused a special education fund for refugees in
order to upgrade his air travel to first class.
   Stoltenberg, an international lawyer who also was a Norwegian
defense minister, has been named Norway's new U.N. ambassador but
he has not yet taken up the post. He declined comment on the
possible new appointment in Oslo.
   Francois Giuliani, spokesman for Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar, said the secretary-general intends to nominate the
58-year-old Norwegian.
   ``I do not deny that what you say is correct,'' he told said in
response to a question.
   The General Assembly is expected to choose a new high
commissioner this month, on the recommendation of the
secretary-general.
   ``We hope the election will be short and swift and that no other
candidates will come forward,'' said another U.N. official.
   Hocke, who defeated Stoltenberg for the three-year position in
1986, reportedly had been favored by the U.S. State Department
because he supported the restrictive immigration policies of the
United States and other Western countries.
   Stoltenberg's views on immigration and refugee issues were not
immediately known. The U.N. High Commission For Refugees handles
more than 10 million refugees worldwide, including 5 million Afghan
refugees in Iran and Pakistan, more than 1 million in southern
Africa, 1 million in the Horn of Africa and several hundred
thousand in southeast Asia and Central America.
   Stoltenberg is an international lawyer and was an unsuccessful
candidate in 1986 for the refugee position. He is backed by
Finland, Iceland, Sweden, Norway and Denmark, which are the
second-largest contributors to the refugee agency, paying $84
million while the United States pays $124 million.
   The U.S. State Department had no comment on Stoltenberg's
candidacy.
   Stoltenberg was foreign minister from March 1987 until the Gro
Harlem Bruntland Labor Party government resigned in October. From
1979 to 1981 he was defense minister in two different Labor
governments.
   He was international secretary for Norway's largest labor Union
several times between 1970 and 1983. From 1971 to 1979 he was
undersecretary in the foreign, defense and trade ministries.
   He was deputy consul in San Francisco from 1959 to 1961, later
served in Belgrade and in the Foreign Ministry in Oslo and in Lagos
in 1970.
   Hocke, who had hoped to be reappointed this month, has been
criticized for financial mismanagement and favoritism, including
the use of funds to upgrade his airine flights. Hocke, who is
Swiss, has admitted using the funds to get better airline seats but
denied misusing U.N. funds.
   He and others have said that the fund, although labeled for
``education,'' in fact was intended to help augment his U.N.
salary. A Swiss TV report said internal documents showed Hocke had
drawn $300,000 since 1987 from the education account to upgrade his
flights from business to first class. Only the U.N.
secretary-general is authorized to travel first class. The United
Nations is investigating the matter.
   He had been criticized by staff and by private refugee relief
groups for not opposing the increasingly rigid asylum policies of
the United States, East Germany and other major donors to the
commission.
   In January 1988, Hocke ordered that all 138,000 copies of the
agency's monthly magazine Refugees be burned because it contained
an article critical of West Germany's policies. He said the article
was outdated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
