<FIRST>r a AM-ElderlySlayings     11-01 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elderly Slayings,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brothers Charged with Murder, Robbery of Two Women Who Lived Alone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers were ordered held without
bond Wednesday on charges they killed two women found stabbed to
death in their ransacked homes.
   Paul Walker, 18, and Teddy Walker, 19, both of Wharton were
charged with murder, robbery and burglary. Boone County Circuit
Judge E. Lee Schlagel Jr. denied bail for the brothers and
scheduled a bond hearing Nov. 16.
   The bloody bodies of Faye Jarrell, 83, and Dorothy Daniels, 68,
were found Sunday morning. An autopsy showed that both women, who
lived alone in modest homes 500 yards apart, had been beaten and
repeatedly stabbed.
   The victims had last been seen about 10:30 p.m. Saturday, when
they left a neighbor's wake at a church in Bald Knob, a rural
community of about 100 people about 25 miles south of Madison.
   Stunned residents said they hadn't locked their doors until a
recent rash of break-ins and vandalism.
   The Walkers had been arrested on unrelated charges Tuesday and
already were in jail when they were charged with the slayings,
sheriff's Cpl. R.A. Miller said.
   ``A lot of witnesses placed them in the area,'' Miller said.
``We had collected some footprints in the immediate and surrounding
areas. ... And we collected one of the suspect's tennis shoes and
matched it with the plaster cast, and it appears to be a match.''
   Investigators believe the brothers broke into both homes, killed
the victims after robbing them, then went to a car wash to clean
off the blood, Miller said.
   ``It's convenient, but weird,'' he said.
   He said the victims' homes are missing some jewelry and cash,
but investigators have not yet placed a dollar estimate on the
missing items.
   Some of the stolen items have been recovered, as have two knives
believed to be the murder weapons, Miller said.
   Officers charged Karen Canterbury, 39, with being an accessory
to murder after the fact, a misdemeanor, for misleading
investigators with false information, Miller said. She was jailed
under $5,000 bond.
</TEXT>
