<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-AIDNominee     11-01 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-AID Nominee,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roskens, Former University of Nebraska President, Picked for AID
Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former University of Nebraska President Ronald
W. Roskens, fired by his board of regents in July, Wednesday was
picked by President Bush on Wednesday to head the Agency for
International Development.
   Bush will nominate Roskins to the post left vacant by the death
last June of AIDS Administrator M. Alan Woods, White House Press
Secretary Marlin Fitzwater announced.
   The University of Nebraska Board of Regents terminated Roskens'
contract July 31 after 12 years as president of the University of
Nebraska System. The regents have refused to say why, despite
demands for an explanation from legislators.
   The regents did say the ouster had nothing to do with any fiscal
or moral impropriety. Some university sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity, have suggested there was a personality
clash between Roskens and several regents.
   Roskens, 56, told a news conference in Lincoln, Neb., ``I would
simply tell you that I am elated.'' He declined to discuss his
dismissal from the university, saying, ``We have long since put
that behind us.''
   Roskens, if confirmed by the Senate, Roskens will run an agency
with 4,600 employees who administer $7 billion in annual U.S.
economic and foreign assistance in more than 60 countries.
   Roskens is a past chairman of the American Council on Education,
the main lobbying arm in Washington for the nation's more than
3,000 colleges and universities.
   The Iowa native was an education professor and vice president at
Kent State University in Ohio before coming to Nebraska as
chancellor of the University of Nebraska at Omaha in 1972. In 1977,
he became president of the Nebraska system, which now includes
three institutions, 40,000 students and a budget of nearly $700
million.
   Roskens said the AID post is ``very appealing in large part
because of the activities I have engaged in in the past'' in
international affairs.
   While chancellor at the Omaha campus, Roskens engineered a
contract with AID to finance an exchange program with the
University of Kabul in Afghanistan.
   Later, as system president, he oversaw campus initiatives for
AID contracts that included a $30 million project by the Omaha
campus to provide educational support for children in Afghanistan
and Afghan refugees in Pakistan.
</TEXT>
