<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     11-01 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colonel Who Led Revolt Ordered to Retire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A colonel who led a military
revolt last year against the government of former President Raul
Alfonsin was ordered Wednesday to retire.
   Col. Mohamed Ali Seineldin led the December 1988 uprising to
protest the government's decision to prosecute officers accused of
human rights abuses during the 1976-83 dictatorship.
   Rebels also demanded a more money for the military and a shakeup
of the military command.
   Seineldin has been held under military arrest since the failed
rebellion. His promotion to brigadier general was turned down by
the army's Promotions Board last week.
   Because he was passed over, he could not remain in the army and
was ordered retired, said army chief Gen. Isidro Caceres.
   The 54-year-old career soldier distinguished himself in fighting
against leftist subversives trying to overthrow Argentina's
government in the early 1970s, and against the British during the
74-day war in 1982 over the Falkland Islands.
   Seineldin and the others may appeal for reinstatement to Defense
Minister Italo Luder and Menem, who succeeded Alfonsin this year.
   On Oct. 7, Menem pardoned Seineldin and 173 other rebels whose
three insurrections threatened to destabilize the Alfonsin
government.
   Also pardoned were 39 officers accused of kidnapping, torture
and murder during the dictatorship and about 60 leftist guerrillas.
   The pardons were necessary, Menem said, to end military
grievances and achieve ``national reconciliation'' between the
armed forces and society's other important institutions.
   Tensions between the army and leftist and human rights groups
has simmered since Alfonsin took office in December 1983 over
issues such as the military budget, the human rights trials and the
army's role in domestic intelligence surveillance.
   The lack of common ground between them undermined popular
support for the Alfonsin government.
   Menem made no mention of the retirements when he addressed about
300 officers Wednesday, but said the actions of his government,
which took office on July 8, would ``close a chapter'' in Argentine
history.
   ``Today begins the reconstruction of the glorious army of the
nation,'' he said.
   Newspapers in the capital Buenos Aires reported Wednesday that
Seineldin, a former commando, might be given the quasi-military
assignment of forming an anti-terrorist, rapid deployment force
comprised of about 400 soldiers, federal police and border guards.
</TEXT>
