<SECOND>AM-People-Kennedy,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor JFK Jr. Fails Bar Exam; Will Get Two More Chances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John F. Kennedy Jr., a recently hired prosecutor
in the Manhattan district attorney's office, has failed the state
bar examination, a spokesman for the office said Wednesday.
   The spokesman, Gerald McKelvey, said a 10-year-old office policy
allows Kennedy, son of the slain president, two more chances to
take the exam and pass. If he fails the third time, he will be
asked to resign from his $30,000-a-year job, McKelvey said. The
next exam is in February.
   Meanwhile, Kennedy will continue to work as he has since August.
Under the state rules, Kennedy may handle misdemeanor cases in
Manhattan Criminal Court and certain felony matters under the
supervision of an admitted attorney.
   A graduate of New York University Law School, Kennedy, 28, was
among 69 new prosecutors hired in Manhattan last summer. He is
assigned to the special prosecutions unit which handles cases such
as consumer fraud.
   Kennedy was one of about 7,000 candidates who took the bar exam.
About 70 percent passed, according to the New York Law Journal. The
list of those who passed will be posted Thursday.
   McKelvey said that of the 63 in the district attorney's office
who took the exam, seven, including Kennedy, failed.
   McKelvey said Kennedy's cousin, Robert F. Kennedy Jr., failed
the bar exam in 1983 when he took it the first time during the 11
months he worked for Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau.
He was admitted in 1985.
   If Kennedy passes the bar, he will get a $1,000 a year raise.
</TEXT>
