<FIRST>r w AM-BowlandRejected     11-01 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bowland Rejected,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Rejects Labor Dept. Nominee</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT T. GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee
on Wednesday rejected the nomination of Debra R. Bowland to head
the Labor Department's wage and hour division, citing her work to
overturn a Louisiana wage law covering government contracts.
   ``We shouldn't put somebody in charge of a law that they don't
believe in _ period,'' said Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., one of the
nine senators to vote against the nomination. Six voted for it.
   ``This is putting the fox in charge of the chicken coop,'' said
Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., another opponent.
   Bowland had been Louisian's Secretary of Labor from 1980 to 1982
under Dave Treen, the only Republican governor in Louisiana in
modern history. She opposed the law under his administration.
Later, as a lobbyist, she represented the opposition to the
prevailing wage law, which was eventually repealed.
   ``Prevailing wage'' laws require government contractors to pay
the prevailing wage in the area of the work, and those wages
generally are defined by reference to union pay scales.
   Bowland would have been in charge of enforcing the federal
prevailing wage law, the Davis-Bacon Act.
   Bowland supporters said she has pledged to enforce federal laws
``vigorously'' and should be taken at her word. Sen. James M.
Jeffords, R-Vt., said Bowland's opppositon to the Louisiana law was
based on problems with the way it was being carried out and
regulations derived from it.
   They noted that the repeal occurred after her involvement and
under a Democratic administration.
   But Sens. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the committee,
and Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, both said it was clear from the
campaign in Louisiana that Bowland has a philosophical objection to
government involvement in wage and hour regulation.
   ``You have to ask yourself whether she is going to be committed
to the implementation of this legislation,'' said Kennedy. ``I find
it difficult to give her the benefit of the doubt.''
   Bowland, 45, has been with the Labor Department since 1985 and
heads the Women's Bureau.
   Sen. Dave Durenberger, R-Minn., abstained. His spokesman said it
was because Durenberger had serious reservations about the
nomination but thought the president should be able to pick his
nominees.
</TEXT>
