<FIRST>u i AM-Turkey     11-01 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ozal Resigns From Party, Pledges to be Non-partisan President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Turgut Ozal resigned from
the political party he founded and pledged Wednesday that he will
stay above party politics after leaving the premiership for his new
non-partisan post.
   ``I will do my duty as stipulated in the constitution,'' Ozal
told a news conference a day after his election by Parliament.
``Politics is gone.''
   Ozal was elected president Tuesday on a third ballot with the
votes of 263 Motherland deputies in a Parliament session boycotted
by all 155 opposition deputies.
   Opposition parties claimed Ozal, founder and leader of the
Motherland Party, lacked a popular mandate after the defeat of his
party in nationwide polls in March. They also questioned whether he
could rule without being influenced by his role in party politics,
as required by the constitution.
   Ozal, set to become Turkey's first civilian head of state with
an active political background since 1960, said he had resigned
from his party.
   Ozal's premiership came to an end after his election. Deputy
Premier Ali Bozer has been appointed acting premier by the outgoing
President Kenan Evren.
   Ozal said he would name a Motherland deputy to form a new
government after he takes over from Evren Nov. 9. Ozal became
premier in 1983 when his newly formed party won elections that
restored civilian rule.
   Hasan Celal Guzel, a former education minister, on Wednesday
became the first Motherland deputy to announce his candidacy for
party leadership, which will be decided in a party congress Nov.
17. Guzel said the premier and the party chairman must be the same
person in accordance with party tradition.
   Ozal said, however, he will not wait until the party congress to
appoint a premier.
   Other aspirants include Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz, Finance
Minister Ekrem Pakdemirli and Justice Minister Oltan Sungurlu.
</TEXT>
