<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 2009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearWaste     11-01 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Waste,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Propose Scaled-down Version of Temporary Nuke Waste Dump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of private experts told Congress
Wednesday the nation should build a small facility to store wastes
from nuclear power plants until a permanent dump is opened.
   The recommendation, following 18 months of study by the
three-man panel, drew immediate criticism from both supporters and
opponents of long-stalled plans for building an interim facility to
store spent uranium from the plants.
   Nuclear utilities, which support the idea of an interim storage
site, called the recommendation too limited, while
environmentalists and other opponents said it skirted the central
issue of safely managing nuclear waste in the long run.
   The panel was created by Congress in 1987 to reassess an Energy
Department plan for building a large-scale interim waste storage
site in Tennessee. It rejected key aspects of the department's
proposal but accepted the need for an interim facility.
   It also recommended building a smaller facility to hold nuclear
waste in emergencies such as a reactor accident. This would not be
intended for general waste storage.
   The review panel made no recommendations on where an interim
storage facility should be situated, but members of the Tennesee
congressional delegation were quick to say the group was wrong to
have concluded that any such facilities are needed.
   ``Its recommendations are as wrongheaded as the Department of
Energy's original plans,'' Tennessee's Democratic Sens. Albert Gore
and Jim Sasser said in a joint statement.
   The state of Tennessee sued the Energy Department to stop its
original plan to build a facility, known as the Monitored
Retreivable Storage site, near Oak Ridge, Tenn.
   Tennessee and other opponents of interim storage contend, among
other things, that other states' unwillingness to be host to a
permament waste dump would mean any temporary storage site would
risk being stuck with the waste indefinitely.
   A desert site in Nevada is under study by the Energy Department
as a proposed permanent waste dump, but the state is attempting to
stop the project. Congress has not authorized the department to
study any other permanent sites.
   In its report to Congress, the review panel recommended building
an interim waste storage facility about one-third as big as that
proposed by the Energy Department and said it should be constructed
only if enough nuclear utilities agree to put up the money. The
department plan called for all utilities to pay the cost.
   The panel said its proposed storage facility would cost $500
million to $600 million.
   The group also rejected the idea, incorporated in the 1987
Nuclear Waste Amendments Act that created the review panel, that
the start of construction of an interim facility be held up until
plans for a permanent dump were licensed.
   It said such a linkage would, because of delays in the building
the permanent dump, force some utilities to close down license
reactors because of a lack of waste storage capacity.
   The Edison Electric Institute, representing the nation's
investor-owned utilities, said Congress should reject the panel's
idea of a scaled-down storage facility and instead go back to a
more flexible version of the Energy Department's original plan.
   Public Citizen, the consumer and anti-nuclear group, said the
panel's recommendation fudged the central issue of ensuring that
all nuclear waste can be safely disposed of in the long run.
   ``They tried to give a little something to everyone and they
ended up givng nothing much to anybody,'' said Scott Saleska, a
nuclear policy analyst at Public Citizen.
</TEXT>
