<FIRST>u w AM-US-Contras     11-01 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Contras,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contrans Crossing Border Into Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Substantial numbers of anti-Sandinista rebels
have reinfiltrated Nicaragua from Honduras over the past month,
encountering government troops on search-and-destroy missions,
government sources said Wednesday.
   Congressional and administration sources said more than 1,000
Contra rebels have left their base camps in Honduras along
Nicaragua's northern border in recent weeks, bringing rebel troop
strength inside Nicaragua to about 4,000.
   At the same time, the rebels have asked the U.S. Agency for
International Development, which administers the current U.S.
humanitarian aid program for the Contras, for food packaged in
smaller, more easily portable quantities and for increased amounts
of cash in Nicaraguan currency, said an official familiar with the
aid program.
   AID has refused the requests, believing that to help the
reinfiltration effort would ``be a wrong signal,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. An Aug. 7 accord
among the five countries in the region called for gradual
demobilization of the Contras and their return to participate in
Nicaragua's electoral process.
   ``We made a conscious decision, with concurrence at the highest
levels of this building, that we not do anything to increase ...
support of increased reinfiltration,'' said a State Department
source.
   ``It appears the process is headed away from demobilization and
back toward war,'' said Rep. George Crockett, D-Mich., chairman of
the House Foreign Affairs Western Hemisphere subcommittee.
   ``It is quite clear the Contras do not have demobilization plans
in mind. Quite conversely, they appear to have mobilization
plans,'' he said.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega cited increasd Contra attacks
Wednesday as his reason for calling off a 19-month cease-fire with
the rebels.
   But some on Capitol Hill said Ortega also was responsible for
any increased skirmishing between the two sides because he
increasingly had been sending Sandinista troops into northern areas
of Nicaragua which they had traditionally not controlled.
   ``This is in part precipitated by Sandinista search-and-destroy
missions'' said Rep. Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., a member of the Foreign
Affairs and Intelligence committees. ``It's no wonder there are
conflicts.''
</TEXT>
