<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Nicaragua     11-01 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Summons Nicaraguan Envoy to Protest End of Truce</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
summoned Nicaragua's ambassador on Wednesday to lodge a protest
against President Daniel Ortega's decision to resume fighting the
Contra guerrillas.
   Nicaragua's U.N. Mission called for a meeting at U.N.
headquarters next Monday and Tuesday among representatives of the
Contras, Nicaragua, Honduras, and U.N. officials involved in trying
to disband the U.S.-backed Contras.
   Its purpose would be to ``approve the logistical and technical
matters'' involved in repatriating the Contras and integrating them
in the Nicaraguan political process, the mission said.
   Perez de Cuellar called in Ambassador Alejandro Serrano Caldera
to express dismay over cancellation of the truce.
   ``The secretary-general is extremely concerned at the breakdown
of the cease-fire in Nicaragua, which had been largely holding
since early 1988,'' said his spokesman, Francois Giuliani.
   ``It is his strong wish that maximum restraint be exercised by
all parties and that the cease-fire can be renewed so that the
peace process can once again be put on track.
   ``The momentum gained by the process in recent months must not
be lost.'' The Nicaraguan Mission's statement demanded disbanding
of the Contras by Dec. 5, as called for the peace accord signed in
August by the five Central American presidents.
   It also said Nicaragua ``reaffirms once again that, regardless
of the position assumed by the mercenary forces, the electoral
process culminating with the Feb. 25 elections will be guaranteed
along with the security of international observers in their
nationwide monitoring duties.''
   Ortega's announcement that he would resume active hostilities
jarred the joint U.N.-Organization of American States efforts to
promote peaceful settlement of guerrilla wars in the region.
   Under Central American accords signed in August in Tela,
Honduras, a joint U.N.-OAS commission is trying to help the 11,000
Contras and their 12,000 dependents camped in Honduras voluntarily
disband and resettle.
   The U.S. State Department has objected to U.N. efforts to
persuade the Contras to disarm as a violation of impartiality.
   The Security Council is about ready to approve a 625-member
peacekeeping force to patrol Nicaragua's border with Honduras to
halt raids by the Contras or Sandinista troops.
   The force would also seal the Honduran border with El Salvador
so Salvadoran leftist rebels cannot receive arms shipments from
Nicaragua or Cuba.
   Civilian U.N. poll watchers are in Nicaragua to monitor the
campaign for the national elections, and have pronounced the
process fair so far.
   Recent polls show Ortega to be trailing the U.S.-backed
presidential candidate, newspaper publisher Violeta Chamorro.
</TEXT>
