<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslav     11-01 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslav,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Presidency Refuses to Drop Charges in Kosovo Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The collective federal presidency
refused Wednesday to drop charges against Azem Vlasi, former
Communist Party chief of troubled Kosovo province, and 14 other
ethnic Albanians on trial with him.
   Police in Kosovo used tear gas to disperse about 1,000 ethnic
Albanians protesting in support of Vlasi in Pristina, the capital
and 200 more in the nearby town of Podujevo, the official news
agency Tanjug reported.
   Tanjug said the eight-member presidency _ representatives from
Yugoslavia's six republics and two provinces _ voted against the
request to drop charges.
   It did not give a breakdown of the vote, but earlier press
reports said Janez Drnovsek and Stipe Suvar, representing the
liberal republics of Slovenia and Croatia respectively, had
expressed support for stopping the trial.
   The defendants are accused of ``counterrevolutionary
activities'' for allegedly plotting Kosovo's secession from
Yugoslavia, and of inciting riots by ethnic Albanians in February.
   Serbia changed its constitution in February to give it more
control over Kosovo, an autonomous province within the republic,
prompting riots by ethnic Albanians that cost 24 lives.
   Federal police now are stationed in the southern province, an
ancient Serbian heartland that borders Albania. Serbians in Kosovo
claim they are harassed by ethnic Albanians, who make up 85 percent
of the 1.9 million people.
   The trial opened Monday in the Kosovo town of Titova Mitrovica,
but was suspended immediately by a defense demand that the
prosecutor and presiding judge be excluded on grounds of bias.
   Vlasi's lawyers also claim no court in Serbia could be
considered impartial. No date has been set for the trial to resume.
</TEXT>
