<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-01 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow, Rain Pester Motorists, Temperatures Rise in South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow pestered motorists in portions of Colorado, North Dakota
and Wyoming, and rain drenched the nation's northeast, but
temperatures rose into the 70s in Texas and much of the lower
Mississippi Valley on Wednesday.
   Up to 5 inches of snow greeted morning commuters in the Denver
area, with as much as 6 inches in Fort Collins, Colo., and 8 inches
in the northern mountains.
   Traffic was bumper to bumper along icy Colorado roads, with
numerous minor traffic accidents reported and a multi-car pileup
south of Denver. No serious injuries were reported.
   ``This is the storm that separates those prepared from those not
prepared,'' said Denver public works spokeswoman Amy Lingg.
   Denver skies cleared by afternoon. Snow also fell in
southeastern Colorado and parts of Minnesota, North Dakota and
Wyoming.
   Elsewhere, showers produced about 1.5 inches of rain in Islip,
N.Y., in a six-hour period ending at 7 a.m. EST. Providence, R.I.,
got slightly less, with showers also plaguing parts of Maine and
Massachusetts.
   Temperatures dipped into the teens in the northern Rockies and
the northern High Plains regions, with single-digit readings in
Wyoming and Montana.
   Butte and Cutbank in Montana tied as the morning cold spots in
the Lower 48 states, with lows of 2 degrees.
   The leading edge of a cold arctic air mass pushed across eastern
Oklahoma and central Texas.
   Strong northerly winds prevailed across the central and southern
high Plains. Temperatures were in the 20s and 30s in the northern
Plains and in the 60s and 70s in southern and eastern Texas and
across much of the lower Mississippi Valley. Highs rose to the 80s
across Florida.
</TEXT>
