<FIRST>r a AM-PrattMurder     11-01 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pratt Murder,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Guilty of Murdering Art Student Who'd Just Moved to New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Wrape in 5th graf is cq; mother spells name differently</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 39-year-old paroled killer was convicted
Wednesday of shooting a young woman to death in a street holdup a
week after she moved to New York from Arkansas to study art.
   The state Supreme Court jury in Brooklyn deliberated less than
four hours before finding the defendant, Frank DeChirico of
Brooklyn, guilty of murder, robbery and criminal weapons possession.
   Judith Anne Wrappe, 24, of Little Rock, Ark., was returning to
her dormitory room at the Pratt Institute on Sept. 14, 1988, when
she was shot in the chest as she struggled to hang on to her purse,
which police said contained $27.
   She had moved to Brooklyn to study art at the institute only a
week before and had been working as a part-time waitress in
Manhattan.
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' Sue Wrape, the victim's mother said from
her home in Little Rock. ``We had confidence in the system.''
   DeChirico faces 25 years-to-life in prison when he's sentenced
Nov. 27 by Justice Philip E. Lagana.
   The defense lawyer, Louis R. Rosenthal, said he would appeal the
verdict.
   Assistant District Attorney Andrew Dember said only that
``justice was done'' before hurrying out of the courthouse.
   DeChirico served 13 years in an upstate prison for manslaughter
for killing an acquaintance during a dispute in 1973. He was free
on parole when he killed Ms. Wrappe.
</TEXT>
