<FIRST>u w AM-JudgeNixon 1stLD-Writethru   11-01 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Judge Nixon, 1st LD-Writethru,a0762,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Are Urged to Oust Federal Judge in Mississippi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS graf 8: ``Nixon, in,'' to remove reference to FBI;
conviction referred only to grand jury.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   a0587 AM-Nixon
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House members on Wednesday urged the removal
of Judge Walter L. Nixon of Mississippi from the federal bench for
lying under oath as the Senate began floor action in its second
impeachment trial in two weeks.
   ``Judge Nixon has broken the law, tainted the federal judiciary
and brought disrepute on the courts,'' said Rep. Don Edwards,
D-Calif., in calling for removal of the judge, who was convicted of
perjury.
   If convicted by the Senate, Nixon would be the seventh federal
official ever removed through impeachment and the third judge to be
ousted from the bench in the last three years.
   Nixon took the Senate floor and declared that ``I have been
wrongfully convicted.'' He said witnesses against lied and
prosecutors held him to an unreasonably high standard of accuracy
in sworn statements.
   ``I had nothing to hide'' Nixon said. ``I had done nothing
wrong. I had not committed any corrupt act ... why would I lie
about something that I hadn't done?''
   The Senate began floor action in the case just 12 days after it
removed Alcee L. Hastings as a District Court judge in Miami on
charges of plotting to obtain a bribe and lying about it to a jury,
which acquitted him of that charge.
   Hastings was the first federal official ever removed on
impeachment charges of which he had been acquitted in a criminal
trial.
   Nixon, in contrast, last year began serving a perjury sentence
for telling a grand jury he never discussed a marijuana smuggling
case with a local prosecutor who was an old friend.
   Drug charges against Drew Fairchild, son of a wealthy
contractor, were made inactive after Nixon discussed the case with
Forrest County District Attorney Paul Holmes, an old friend,
according to the articles of impeachment.
   Despite serving a sentence at Eglin Air Force Base in Flrida,
Nixon has continued to collect his $89,500 judicial salary and says
he will go back on the bench and preside over court cases if the
Senate acquits him.
   The House on May 10 approved, 417-0, three articles of
impeachment.
   The articles say Nixon lied by telling the grand jury Holmes
never discussed the Fairchild case with him and by saying he never
had anything to do with the case.
   The third count says that by concealing conversations with
various figures in the case after entering into a lucarative oil
and case investment with contractor Wiley Fairchild, Nixon ``raised
substantial doubt as to his judicial integrity, undermined
confidence in the integrity of the judiciary, betrayed the trust of
the people of the United States. ...''
   After hearing arguments in the case on Wednesday, the Senate
planned to debate it in closed session on Thursday and most likely
vote on Friday.
   Conviction by a two-thirds vote of senators present and voting
on any of the three articles of impeachment would mean removal of
Nixon as a judge and halt payment of his salary.
   Taking the Senate floor, Nixon told lawmakers he had always
acted fairly in his courtroom in accord with advice from ``my good
friend, former Sen. John C. Stennis.''
   Stennis, long a fixture in the congressional establishment,
retired in 1988 after representing Mississippi in the Senate for 40
years.
   ``I have served honestly and faithfully as a federal judge for
21 years,'' Nixon said. ``I have always been mindful that I was
appointed, not annointed.''
   Defense attorney David Stewart admitted that he Nixon made
errors in his testimony, but saidd they represented honest mistakes.
   ``He didn't think of it,'' Stewart said. ``He messed up. His
testimony wasn't perfect.''
   Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., another House manager of the
case, scoffed at the notion that misstatements by Nixon in his FBI
interview and grand jury testimony were merely blunders and not
lies.
   ``Are they deceits or just a series of mistakes?'' Sensenbrenner
asked the Senate in an incredulous voice. ``Fourteen mistakes?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
