<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0688 11-01 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Brigade Headquarters, 1 Dead, 1 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with new attack, details. Picks
up 9th pvs: `Four people ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels fired two
anti-tank weapons Wednesday at the headquarters of the 1st Army
Brigade, killing one civilian and wounding another in the latest in
an escalating cycle of violence.
   The attack came one day after the bombing of a labor
federation's headquarters in which 10 people were killed and 29
wounded.
   Guerrillas aboard a red pickup truck stopped two blocks from the
entrance of the army headquarters in the city's northern sector,
witnesses and soldiers said. The rebels fired two anti-tank
weapons, both of which struck a car that pulled out from a side
street into the line of fire.
   The car's driver, identified by rescue workers as Hermogenes
Martinez, was mortally wounded by the rockets, which demolished his
car. A spokeswoman at the downtown Rosales Hospital said Martinez,
59, died in the emergency room.
   A street vendor was wounded in the attack, the rescue workers
reported.
   On Tuesday, terrorists bombed the leftist National Federation of
Salvadoran Workers hall in downtown San Salvador.
   A strike call by the workers federation, popularly known as
Fenastras, remained largely unheeded Wednesday, with public
transportation running normally, and plants, banks and shops doing
business as usual.
   Farabundo Marti National Front guerrillas blamed the rightist
government of President Alfredo Cristiani for Tuesday's bombing and
vowed to avenge the slain unionists. No one claimed responsibility.
   ``The moment for combat has arrived. The moment for setting fire
to the fascists has arrived,'' the guerrillas said in a broadcast
on their clandestine Radio Venceremos.
   Leftist leaders often refer to members of the governing
Republican Nationalist Alliance party as ``fascists.''
   ``The fascists are mistaken if they think they can terrorize the
people like this. The times when the people would run and hide are
past. ... If it is war they want, then war they will get as the
answer to these crimes,'' the broadcast said.
   The violence has threatened future talks between the guerrillas
and Cristiani's government to end the decade-long civil war.
   Four people were wounded, including an American citizen, when
another bomb went off earlier Tuesday at the office of an
organization of relatives of missing persons and political
prisoners.
   Leftist organizations blamed the military for the attacks
Tuesday, saying they were in retaliation for a guerrilla mortar
attack on the Defense Ministry compound Monday that killed one
civilian and wounded 15 others.
   Military spokesmen rejected the leftists' accusation and
promised to investigate and punish those responsible.
   The guerrilla broadcast further warned the attacks, ``committed
by the high command,'' endanger a third meeting with government
representatives, scheduled for Nov. 20 in Caracas, Venezuela, to
try negotiate a cease-fire in the war that has killed more than
70,000 people.
   ``From now on all workers are at war with (Defense Minister)
Gen. Humberto Larios, the high command and the ARENA government,''
the National Union of Salvadoran Workers, the largest labor
federation, said in a communique.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher
condemned the bombings but declined to assess blame for them. He
criticized extremists of both the left and the right for the
continuing violence.
   ``The extreme left and right in El Salvador bring neither
liberation nor order, they bring suffering, terror and death,'' he
said. ``We condemn these acts of violence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
