<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Contras     11-01 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Contras,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contra Leader Seeks U.S. Military Aid, Reports Sandinista Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Contra military commander said
Wednesday that after 21 months without U.S. military aid, his
rebels will defend themselves as best they can from attacks by
Nicaragua's Sandinista army, but ``we won't respond to Sandinista
fire because we can't.''
   The commander, Enrique Bermudez, asked the United States to
resume military aid. A communique from his general staff said
Sandinista soldiers backed by Soviet-made helicopter gunships
attacked two rebel positions in Zelaya province Wednesday.
   The communique gave no details or casualties.
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua said Wednesday he was
ending a 19-month truce because of increased Contra attacks,
including one last week that killed 18 people and another Monday
that killed four.
   Bermudez called Ortega's allegation ``a lie'' and said the
Sandinistas had political motives.
   He said the Sandinista army began large-scale mobilizations in
three provinces on Tuesday, the day before Ortega's announcement.
   ``The Sandinistas are looking for excuses not to have elections,
to impose a state of siege in Nicaragua and to impede citizens from
exercising their suffrage in the Feb. 25, 1990, elections,'' he
said in an interview with The Associated Press.
   Bermudez said Ortega left the United State with one choice:
renewing the military aid that ended in February 1988. He said
Congress ``should not leave us defenseless.''
   ``We know that the reigning political reality in the United
States does not favor sending a lot of arms to our fighters, but
this is the only option,'' Bermudez said.
   About 12,000 rebel fighters retreated to base camps in Honduras
last year after seven years of military aid ended and the
cease-fire began.
   Bermudez said 6,000 Contras have returned to Nicaragua since the
five Central American presidents agreed on Aug. 7 that the Contras
would be disbanded and relocated in exchange for moves toward
democratization in Nicaragua.
   Congressional and administration sources in Washington put the
rebel troop strength inside Nicaragua at about 4,000.
   ``These troops will only carry out evasive actions in the face
of a Sandinista army that has received $1 billion worth of arms
from the Soviet Union in the last few years,'' Bermudez said.
   ``It is a pity that our troops haven't received even a single
cartridge from the United States in almost two years. Faced with
this reality, we can't do anything except save our own lives and
defend ourselves as best we can.''
   In Managua, the capital of Nicaragua, former Contra leader
Alfredo Cesar accused the Sandinistas of ``preferring war to the
political process,'' which might hand it an electoral defeat.
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo of Managua called on the Contras,
the Sandinistas and the superpowers to demonstrate ``maturity'' and
avoid a ``bloodbath.''
   President Jose Azcona of Honduras said in a statement that
Ortega's decision jeopardizes the agreement to disband the Contras
based in Honduras.
   Costa Rica's president, Oscar Arias, condemned the move, saying
it endangers the peace process that was begun in Nicaragua.
   The San Jose newspaper Prensa Libre said Arias and Foreign
Minister Rodrigo Madrigal tried to talk Ortega out of calling off
the cease-fire.
</TEXT>
