<FIRST>r i AM-India-Violence     11-01 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Violence,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Bodies Recovered in Indian Town, Hindu-Moslem Death Toll 165</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police found 13 more bodies in the
eastern town of Bhagalpur on Wednesday, bringing the death toll to
165 in Hindu-Moslem violence that began last week in Bihar state,
the United News of India reported.
   The news agency quoted government officials in Patna, the
capital of Bihar, as saying no violence was reported in the
Bhagalpur area on Wednesday.
   Curfew was lifted for two hours during the day, but troops
continued to patrol the town and surrounding areas, UNI said.
   Bhagalpur is about 110 miles east of Patna and 635 miles
southeast of New Delhi.
   Clashes broke out in the region on Oct. 26 after Hindu
fundamentalists organized processions celebrating the building of a
temple at a disputed spot in neighboring Uttar Pradesh state. The
site, near Ayodhya, is claimed as sacred by both Hindus and Moslems.
   Moslems form about 12 percent of India's 880 million people and
Hindus make up 80 percent.
   In Srinagar, summer capital of northern Jammu-Kashmir state,
police fired on rioting Moslem mobs on Wednesday, killing
18-year-old Abdul Rahman, reported S.S. Ali, a deputy
inspector-general of police.
   Ali said in a telephone interview from Srinagar that police
fired to quell a mob that was throwing stones and forcibly closing
shops to protest the wounding and arrest of Moslem separatist
leader Abdul Hameed Sheikh on Tuesday.
   Ali said at least 25 people were injured in protests in Srinagar
and nearby Anantnag, but UNI put the number at 70.
   Sheikh, who is agitating for secession of the state from India
and its assimilation in neighboring Pakistan, was injured in a
shootout with police and later arrested.
</TEXT>
