<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Said To Be Redrafting Peace Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with proposal delivered to Arens,
TV denies report on settler deployment. CORRECTS that 138 sted 139 Palestinians
killed as collaborators. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III told
Foreign Minister Moshe Arens by telephone Wednesday that he has
revised his Middle East peace offer following objections from
Israel, an Israeli offical said.
   Israel radio said the new draft, delivered to Arens Wednesday
night by U.S. Ambassador William Brown, gave Israel assurances that
known PLO members will be banned from talks, but left the door open
to indirect PLO participation. .
   The radio said Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, Finance Minister
Shimon Peres, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Arens _ the four
top leaders _ will meet Friday to discuss the modifications.
   Israel radio also said Wednesday the army plans to begin
deploying a reserve unit of Jewish settlers in the West Bank,
breaking a ban against assigning settler units to the occupied
territory.
   The move immediately brought protests from left-wing legislators
who complained use of settler companies could increase the violence
in the 22-month-old Palestinian uprising.
   Later Wednesday, Israeli TV, quoting defense sources, said
settler reserve units would not be deployed in the West Bank,
despite the previous reports.
   An Israeli official confirmed Baker spoke to Arens on Wednesday.
The official, who spoke on condition he not be identified, refused
to provide details of the plan.
   The reported changes in Baker's proposal calling for a
preliminary meeting on Israel's election plan with a Palestinian
delegation came a week after Arens wrote the American official
asking for key changes in the U.S. proposal.
   Arens insisted that Israel have the right to veto members of a
Palestinian delegation if they are tied to the Palestine Liberation
Organization and that Israeli-Palestinian talks be limited to the
Israeli offer for elections in the occupied territories.
   In the new draft, Baker said the Palestinian delegation may
discuss the elections plan and the process of negotiations but not
the content of negotiations, reports on Israel and army radio said.
   The reports said Baker also agreed to scrap the idea of a
meeting among U.S., Israeli and Egyptian officials in Washington to
discuss the makeup of the Palestinian delegation.
   Baker declined to give Israel a veto of individual members of
the delegation but said Israel can refuse to attend the meeting if
the Palestinian delegation is not acceptable, the reports said.
   The use of the word ``acceptable'' was not a change from Baker's
earlier plan, and the reported revised draft also seemed to fall
short of Arens' request that the PLO be banned from even indirect
participation in the talks.
   Since the start of the uprising in the occupied lands in
December 1987, 607 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli
soldiers and Jewish settlers. Forty Israelis also have died in the
violence.
   In the occupied territories Wednesday, soldiers shot a masked
protester in a demonstration and masked Palestinians beat and
critically injured a 60-year-old gas station attendant on suspicion
of cooperating with Israel.
   Palestinians have killed 138 of their fellow Arabs on suspicion
of cooperating with Israel.
</TEXT>
