<FIRST>u a AM-PrisonDisturbance     11-01 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Disturbance,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Superintendent of Prison Hit by Two-day Riots Suspended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY MUTCHLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The superintendent of the state prison at
Camp Hill was suspended Wednesday pending an investigation by an
independent panel into a two-day riot that left 123 people injured
last week.
   In a three-paragraph statement, Corrections Commission David
Owens Jr. said Robert M. Freeman, superintendent of the riot-torn
prison, was suspended based on information he received on Wednesday.
   The statement said Owens would not give a reason for the
suspension ``in order to preserve Superintendent Freeman's due
process rights and to maintain the integrity of the ongoing
investigation.''
   Two hours before the suspension was announced, The Associated
Press reported that prison guards said inmates were able to go on a
second rampage at the prison because officials did not fix broken
control boxes after the first night of riots.
   Gov. Robert P. Casey appointed the three-member commission
earlier this week to look into the uprising. The commission, headed
by former federal Judge Arlin Adams, is expected to release its
report on or before Dec. 1.
   Casey spokesman Vince Carocci said the governor concurred with
the decision to suspend Freeman.
   Freeman has an unlisted phone number and could not be reached
for comment at the prison.
   Corrections spokesman Kenneth Robinson said a decision on
whether Freeman will be suspended with or without pay has not yet
been determined.
   Erskind Deramus, deputy commissioner for programs, will serve as
acting superintendent, Robinson said.
   In the Associated Press interviews, several guards said they
alerted prison officials about the control box problem.
   More than 15 correctional officers said the prison
administration ignored the problem and said officials lied about
what time they secured the prison after last Wednesday's riot. A
prison spokeswoman stressed that the prison was under control when
officials said it was, at 10 p.m.
   Robinson would not say whether the information revealed in
Wednesday's Associated Press story had any bearing on Freeman's
suspension.
   The two nights of rioting left 123 people injured and destroyed
more than a dozen buildings. Prison officials said they expect to
transfer about 1,500 inmates to state and federal prisons.
   Prison officials would not comment Wednesday on the guards'
allegations.
</TEXT>
