<HEAD>Army: Most Arabs Killed as Collaborators Not Tied to Military</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army officers said
Wednesday only one-third of the 138 Palestinians killed by fellow
Arabs on suspicion of collaborating with Israeli authorities worked
with the military.
   ``Most of the men suspected as collaborators have no connection
with us,'' Brig. Gen. Zvi Poleg, military commander of the occupied
Gaza Strip, said on Israel radio. ``It's usually family disputes or
criminal matters or unknown.''
   On a tour of a seaside prison camp in the Gaza Strip
photojournalists were told the killing of suspected collaborators
in the Gaza Strip is often carried out under explicit orders from
the Islamic fundamentalist Hamas, or Zeal, movement, which contests
with the PLO for control of the Gaza Strip.
   A military official said some top Hamas leaders were caught by
the military, but continued to work from inside the prison camp,
dispatching orders through lawyers and freed prisoners.
   ``The top people of Hamas who are currently in prison run the
kingpins who replaced them in Gaza,'' the officer said.
   The officer works in the seaside prison dubbed Ansar II by
inmates after a prison in Lebanon used to hold Palestine Liberation
Organization fighters.
   He said only a third of the Arabs killed were actually involved
with the military.
   Inside the camp, the hundreds of inmates _ the army has not
released exact figures on the inmate population _ wear blue track
suits and many seemed in high spirits. One even clandestinely
flashed a ``V'' for victory sign as he sat in front of gun-toting
guards.
   The army brought photographers inside after reports the military
was carrying out a special ``initiated action'' aimed at detaining
masked activists who patrol Gaza armed with axes, clubs and iron
bars, to enforce uprising rules and kill collaborators.
   The army showed reporters five youths who were arrested while
wearring masks and patrolling a street in the Jabaliya refugee camp.
   Army regulations order soldiers to detain any masked activist
and to fire if the masked man refuses orders to stop.
   An official said Hamas has become increasingly brutal in recent
months, with four nurses killed by activists. One nurse was killed
with an ax while at work in a hospital ward.
   At least 8,500 Palestinians are in military prisons.
