<FIRST>r a AM-HalloweenViolence 1stLd-Writethru a0790 11-01 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Halloween Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0790,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Halloween Turns Violent With Shootings and Arrests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf and 6th graf, `The older...,' to CORRECT that
second Philadelphia shooting victim was boy, sted girl; gives name.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stray gunshots wounded young trick-or-treaters in Philadelphia
and Chicago and 230 people were arrested in New York terror sprees
during Halloween violence, authorities said.
   An 8-year-old girl was shot in the chest and a 13-year-old boy
in the buttocks as they walked from house to house in a
Philadelphia neighborhood rocked by drug activity.
   The children were caught in crossfire as four men chased a
fifth, witnesses said. Police suspect the gunfire was drug-related.
   Kateisha Dublin, 8, was in fair condition Wednesday in the
intensive care unit of Children's Hospital in Philadelphia after a
bullet was removed from her chest, hospital spokeswoman Yvonne
Vaughn said.
   ``I was out there giving out candy to the kids when four guys
come running down the street,'' said a witness who was afraid to
give his name. ``One guy came down the street first and four guys
came running behind him and started shooting. It was chaos.''
   The boy, Karriem Muhamed, was released from the hospital
Wednesday.
   In Chicago, a 4-year-old boy thrilled about his first night of
trick-or-treating was shot by a shopkeeper who darted from his
store and fired at teen-agers who had been harassing him, police
said.
   Brandon Shepherd was walking home with an aunt and four young
friends when he was hit by a stray bullet. He was in good condition
Wednesday at Loyola University Medical Center in suburban Maywood,
hospital spokesman Mike Maggio said.
   Many of those arrested Tuesday in New York were teen-agers who
smashed and looted small businesses and injured dozens of people,
police said.
   The violence left officials puzzled, with some saying Halloween
in New York is growing more dangerous every year.
   ``I don't know what we can attribute it to,'' said John J.
Holmes, an assistant police chief.
   Of the 230 people arrested, 46 were charged as youthful
offenders, a charge limited to those under the age of 16. Many were
clad in Halloween costumes or masks.
   Detroit Mayor Coleman Young said the three-day, fire-setting
spree in his city known as ``Devil's Night'' produced 223 fires
this year _ six fewer than last year in a Halloween tradition that
turned from soaping windows to arson about 10 years ago.
   Police arrested 399 minors on charges of ignoring the city's
three-day 6 p.m.-to-6 a.m. curfew, and eight people on arson
charges, officials said Wednesday.
   A 3-year-old Normangee, Texas, boy was in serious but stable
condition Wednesday after he was shot in the head when a pistol
worn by a worker at his day care center as part of her Halloween
costume went off.
   Kenny Archer was airlifted to Texas Children's Hospital in
Houston after four hours of surgery at a Bryan hospital.
   Authorities said the day care worker must have thought the
.22-caliber pistol she wore with a western costume was unloaded
when she brought it to the day care center Tuesday.
   It was not clear how the gun went off, Leon County Sheriff Royce
Wilson said.
   In other Halloween incidents:
   _ A 31-year-old woman in Champaign, Ill., was burned by a
caustic liquid thrown by someone wearing a devil mask when she ran
out of Halloween candy.
   _ A ball of wet tissue touched off a Halloween night fight
between black and white teen-agers in Collinsville, Ala., that
resulted in three arrests and prompted officers to order everyone
off the streets for the rest of the night.
   _ Vandals threw gasoline bombs and rocks at police and
firefighters in Nashville, Tenn., and a school bus was attacked.
Razor blades were found in two candy bars in Knox County.
</TEXT>
