<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flood of East German Refugees Resumes After Border Reopening</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with report that number of refugees
in West German Embassy has risen to 500. Picks up 3rd pvs, `The ban...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PRA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ONDREJ HEJMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of East Germans seized
the chance to go West on Wednesday, entering the West German
Embassy hours after East Germany lifted short-lived restrictions on
travel to Czechoslovakia.
   East German refugees said the number of East Germans in the
embassy in the Czechoslovak capital had risen to more than 500 by
late Wednesday afternoon. About 80 people had been waiting there
before the East German ban on visiting Czechoslovakia was lifted at
midnight Tuesday.
   The ban went into effect after more than 15,000 East Germans
jammed the same embassy last month and East Berlin was pressured to
allow them to travel West in special trains.
   The exodus of tens of thousands of East Germans to the West
through East bloc neighbors Czechoslovakia, Hungary and Poland in
recent weeks helped to hasten the fall of East German leader Erich
Honecker.
   Since Egon Krenz succeeded Honecker as Communist Party chief
Oct. 23, authorities in East Berlin have agreed to issue travel
documents for at least 150 East Germans who have turned up at the
West German Embassy in Prague. A similar arrangement is under
operation at the West German mission in Warsaw.
   The number of East Germans flocking to the Bonn mission in
Prague seemed likely to rise with the lifting of travel
restrictions, analysts said.
   It was not immediately known how the Prague government would
react this time, after previously allowing thousands of refugees to
leave Czechoslovakia for the West via East Germany.
   The flood of new arrivals, and a continuing flow of hundreds of
East Germans going west via Hungary and Austria each day suggests
that at least some of his countrymen are skeptical about promises
of reform made by Krenz.
   Krenz rescinded the travel ban imposed under Honecker and also
hinted that a new law giving East Germans greater travel freedom to
the West would be studied.
   Austrian officials said Wednesday 402 East Germans crossed to
Austria via Hungary en route to West Germany since Tuesday,
bringing to more than 48,000 the number of East German citizens who
have crossed to the West since Budapest opened the border to them
Sept. 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
