<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-US     11-01 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-US,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salinas Says Mexican-U.S. Relations Getting Priority</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who
helped reverse decades of confrontation with the United States,
called for even better relations on Wednesday, saying they are ``of
special significance to Mexico.''
   ``Relations with such a powerful neighbor, with the most complex
common border in the world and a history burdened by acts of
extreme aggression, will never be easy,'' Salinas told a joint
session of Congress in his first state of the union speech.
   ``Nevertheless, there is no reason our relations should always
be bad or tense.''
   Relations over three previous administrations were marred by
disagreements and mutual accusations on a wide range of issues,
from alleged mistreatment of Mexican illegal aliens to U.S. trade
barriers, corruption and drug trafficking.
   Salinas said he has been making special effort to improve
relations since taking office Dec. 1 in ``a positive, respectful
atmosphere'' that ``does not stem from a change in our principles,
but from a change in circumstances.''
   ``We reject confrontation as being senseless, and submission as
being offensive to our firmest convictions. We view the future with
assurance, without ignoring a difficult past,'' he added.
   Salinas said U.S.-Mexican trade has been growing since Mexico
joined the 103-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade in
1986 and lifted many of its trade barriers.
   Mexico now is seeking to broaden its exports of iron, steel and
textiles to the United States, he said.
   He also said that increased cooperation in combating drug
trafficking has brought positive results.
   Salinas indicated, however, that Mexico will pursue its
traditional policy of non-intervention, opposing any outside
interference with Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government or in
Panama.
   ``The situation in Central America remains delicate,'' Salinas
said.
   He expressed support for a regional peace plan aimed at
negotiating an end to the war between Nicaragua's government and
the U.S.-supported rebels and to leftist guerrilla insurrections in
El Salvador and Guatemala.
   He said Mexico defends ``the rights of the Panamanian people to
self-determination.''
   But he took a swipe at Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Panama's
Defense Forces chief, saying, ``We made a distinction between
defending such principles and protecting those who have hindered
the progress of a nation.''
   Noriega was indicted on U.S. drug trafficking charges in
February 1988, and the United States has been trying to get him
ousted.
   Salinas also said Mexico is ``seeking to increase economic and
cultural relations'' with President Fidel Castro's communist regime
in Cuba, and ``in the field of finance, we agreed to respond
sensitively and responsibly to conditions in both countries.''
   He did not elaborate.
   Salinas said Mexico will press for closer relations with the
rest of Latin America and seek trade opportunities with Japan,
China and other Far East countries.
   ``One of the concerns of my administration is to extend Mexico's
presence in the Pacific Basin, the most dynamic zone of economic
growth and technological innovation,'' he said. ``We are therefore
reorienting diplomatic and consular actions in the region.''
</TEXT>
