<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-China     11-01 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-China,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expelled Committee Members Say China Punishing Hong Kong People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two legislators said the Chinese government
expelled them from a committee negotiating Hong Kong's future
constitution to punish residents for criticizing the Chinese
crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators.
   The National People's Congress Standing Committee ruled Tuesday
that Sezto Wah and Martin Lee could no longer serve on the Hong
Kong-China Basic Law Committee.
   The committee is drafting the constitution for the territory
when it reverts to Chinese rule in 1997.
   The two members of Hong Kong's Legislative Council told
reporters the Chinese action was also an attempt to make them
apologize for their criticism of Beijing's military crackdown on
the pro-democracy movement in June.
   Lee appealed to the Chinese government not to penalize people in
this British colony for their criticism and said he hoped ``the
punishment would stop'' with their expulsion.
   The two legislators are also members of a Hong Kong alliance in
support of the ``patriotic democratic movement'' in China.
   Beijing's official Xinhua News Agency reported Tuesday that the
decision to expel the two men were based on a report by Ji Pengfei,
chairman of the Basic Law Committee and head of the Hong Kong and
Macao Affairs Office in the Chinese government.
   It said the National People's Congress noted Sezto and Lee said
they would not participate in drafting law with the current Chinese
government and had called for re-examination of the 1940
Chinese-British agreement on the return of the territory to Chinese
rule in 1997.
   China has pledged to retain Hong Kong's capitalistic and legal
system for 50 years after 1997, but the crackdown on the
pro-democracy movement has raised fears about Chinese interference
in Hong Kong's affairs.
