<FIRST>r a AM-PreschoolMolest     11-01 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Preschool Molest,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests in McMartin Pre-School Molestation Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children were raped, sodomized and forced to
take part in nude sex games and satanic rituals at the McMartin
Pre-School, a prosecutor said during closing arguments Wednesday in
the longest criminal trial in U.S. history.
   Deputy District Attorney Lael Rubin urged a Superior Court jury
not to be taken in by what she called the loving ``facade''
presented by defendants Raymond Buckey and his mother, Peggy
McMartin Buckey.
   Buckey, 31, and his mother, 62, are charged with 64 counts of
child molestation and one count of conspiracy. The charges are
linked to the alleged molestations of 11 children at the
now-defunct McMartin Pre-School in suburban Manhattan Beach.
   ``It is a mistake, it is unfair and it is unconscionable to
simply discount the children's testimony because certain statements
seem unbelievable,'' Ms. Rubin said.
   ``When you assess it all, you will see loud and clear there were
some pretty awful things that went on at that preschool at the
hands of Raymond and Peggy Buckey.''
   Buckey and his mother were among seven people arrested in 1983.
Charges were dropped against the other five for lack of evidence.
   Jurors were to begin deliberations in the 2{-year trial after
receiving instructions from Judge William Pounders on Thursday.
   During his earlier closing arguments, defense attorney Danny
Davis said medical evidence presented at trial was faulty and the
children were coached in their testimony.
   He maintained that the prosecution's case was built on
``insinuations, excuses and lame rationale.''
   The trial is the longest and most expensive criminal proceeding
in U.S. history, with a price tag estimated at $15 million.
   A jury of 12 and six alternates began the trial in April 1987.
During the years, job problems and illness plagued the jury,
leaving the bare dozen panelists needed to deliberate and avoid a
mistrial.
</TEXT>
