<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     11-01 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Rampage in Sri Lanka, Burn Houses, Kill 31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of armed men rampaged through
two villages in central Sri Lanka on Wednesday, burning at least 50
houses and killing at least 31 people, officials and residents said.
   The government reported at least 35 other killings across the
Sinhalese heartland in southern and central Sri Lanka in a 24-hour
span ending Wednesday morning.
   The attack on the adjoining villages of Galanewa and
Thambuttegama, 100 miles north of Colombo, was apparently in
revenge for the landmine destruction of a police jeep on Tuesday in
which four policemen were killed, said residents in the
north-central Anuradhapura district contacted by telephone.
   The residents, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said those
killed were suspected members of the People's Liberation Front, a
radical Sinhalese group fighting to overthrow the government.
   The victims included several women, they said. All were shot in
the head and their bodies burned.
   Military officials, who cannot be identified under briefing
rules, said a senior army officer, Col. Ananda Weerasundera, was
being sent to investigate. Opposition politicians and human rights
groups have accused security forces of resorting to indiscriminate
killings of suspected radicals in the confrontation between
ultranationalist Sinhalese and the government.
   The government has denied it, but senior officials privately
admit security forces may have committed excesses.
   Military officials said at least 17 people, including four
women, were found slain near Laggala, 85 miles southeast of
Colombo. They blamed the People's Liberation Front, saying police
found notes beside the bodies reading: ``Punishment for the
traitors to the organization.''
   Government officials accused the People's Liberation Front of
killing at least 12 other people in separate attacks.
   In addition, the bodies of six radicals or supporters were found
Tuesday in the Sinhalese heartland, including two in Colombo.
Officials blamed the deaths on vigilante groups avenging attacks on
soldiers and government supporters.
   Sinhalese radicals began their bloody challenge of the
Sinhalese-dominated government's authority in 1987, saying the
government conceded too much in its efforts to make peace with
separatist guerrillas from the Tamil minority.
   Sinhalese make up 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Tamils comprise 18 percent.
   Tamils say the Sinhalese discriminate against them in jobs,
education and use of the Sinhala language.
</TEXT>
