<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 3rdLd-Writethru a0805 11-01 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0805,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Assassinated in Medellin, Congressman Slain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with congressman leading anti-drug
efforts, age of judge, attack on Mormon church. Picks up 8th graf, `The
government...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen assassinated a federal judge in
Medellin and a congressman in this capital Wednesday night in the
latest wave of violence to strike Colombia since the government
declared war on drug traffickers.
   Terrorists in two cars fatally shot Judge Mariela Espinoza, the
second justice official slain since the government began its
crackdown on traffickers 11 weeks ago.
   At about the same time, the congressman, Luis Francisco Madero,
was shot as he arrived home Wednesday night in Bogota, a national
police spokeswoman said. Madero, 66, of the opposition Conservative
Party, died minutes later at a hospital a few blocks away, the
spokeswoman said.
   Madero was considered a foe of the traffickers. He organized a
demonstration to protest trafficking in Pacho, a city 60 miles
north of Bogota, said a Conservative presidential contender, Sen.
Alvaro Leyva Duran.
   There was no claim of responsibility for Wednesday's killings,
police said, though suspicion fell on hitmen hired by the
traffickers.
   Mrs. Espinoza, a 43-year-old lawyer who had been appointed a
judge six months ago, was assassinated as she opened the garage
door of her home in western Medellin, the hub of the most powerful
drug cartel in Colombia, the radio chain Caracol said.
   Mrs. Espinoza had just arrived home and was accompanied by two
police bodyguards on motorcycles at the time of the shooting, and
one of the policemen and a passer-by were wounded, Caracol said in
a report from the city of 2 million residents about 150 miles north
of Bogota.
   The assassins fled in their cars, police said by telephone.
   Hours after the assassinations, a bomb went off in eastern
Bogota at the entrance to a Mormon church. The church sustained
minor damages but was closed at the time so no one was injured,
police said.
   The government declared a crackdown on drug traffickers after
the leading presidential candidate, Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, was
assassinated Aug. 18 by drug barons. The government reinstated an
extradition treaty with the United States and began confiscating
property belonging to the drug lords.
   Since then, drug traffickers have been blamed for scores of
shootings and bombings that have killed 36 people and injured 223.
   Traffickers responded with the violence in an effort to persuade
the government of President Virgilio Barco to end its extradition
of drug suspects.
   The administration has extradited five alleged traffickers to
the United States, where they will face trial. In Colombia, drug
lords have received relative impunity by paying off or intimidating
the nation's judges.
   In the past 10 years, 221 court employees, including 42 judges,
have been killed. On Sept. 21, Justice Minister Monica de Greiff
resigned following death threats from traffickers.
   The traffickers in an Aug. 23 message to a national radio
station vowed to kill 10 judges for every drug trafficker
extradited to the United States to face trial.
   Another federal judge, Hector Jimenez, was killed Oct. 17 in
Medellin by gunmen firing from a motorcycle.
   Judges and thousands of court employes called a three-day strike
after that killing, demanding bodyguards, bulletproof vests and
cars and metal detectors at entrances to their offices.
   Leaders of the Medellin cartel have asked for peace talks five
times the past two months.
   They offered to lay down their arms, end a terrorist bombing
campaign and abandon the drug business if the government will grant
them amnesty and stop extraditing traffickers to the United States.
   Barco has refused.
   U.S. officials say the Medellin cartel and a rival organization
in Cali are responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine sold in the
United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
