<FIRST>r a AM-LelandSlur     11-01 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland Slur,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Call for Resignation of Councilman After Racial Slur</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents, language in grafs 2, 13.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Leland Seat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of residents packed City Council
chambers to call for an incumbent councilman's resignation after he
reportedly made a racial slur about the late U.S. Rep. Mickey
Leland.
   ``Racism hurts all decent people,'' said JoAnn Gavin of a group
called the All Peoples Congress. ``Houston does not need a racist
to represent our city. ... Racism is not negotiable.''
   Councilman Jim Westmoreland joked to a newspaper reporter Oct.
18 that Houston Intercontinental Airport be renamed ``Nigger
International'' to appease council members pushing to rename the
airport as a memorial to Leland, who was killed in an August plane
crash in Ethiopia, The Houston Post reported.
   But Westmoreland, a 16-year incumbent seeking re-election to his
at-large seat next week, claims he used the term ``Negro
International.''
   Westmoreland apologized for the comment last Friday and again
Wednesday morning. He said the matter has overshadowed other
campaign issues and prompted threats against him and his family.
   ``Any anguish this has caused anyone could not match the anguish
I've suffered and my family,'' he said. ``I'm truly sorry for my
comments.''
   But few at the hearing were appeased.
   ``We tell a joke and our friends hear it,'' Skipper Lee, one of
39 residents to address the hearing, said to Westmoreland. ``You
tell a joke and the next day, it's on the streets of New York City.
You don't just speak for yourself. You speak for Houston. We look
up to you and we can't look up to a racist.''
   Westmoreland listened intently to the speakers, but said they
did not convince him to resign.
   ``The question of resignation is one I don't think we have to
make because we have a vote coming up,'' he said. ``With all the
publicity this has generated, there's no one going to the polls who
won't know what the situation has been.''
   Armed guards turned away nearly as many as those allowed inside
the packed chambers, with crowds spilling into hallways on two
floors. Most of the also criticized Mayor Kathy Whitmire and black
council members for not speaking out strongly against the slur.
   ``Kathy, I never dreamed that you _ someone who has been
outspoken for the people _ would have taken two to three weeks to
stand up for your black brothers and sisters,'' said the Rev. Jose
Angel Lopez.
   ``Minority members of this council have not stood up and spoken
out against this,'' said Nelva Polk, a sixth grade teacher.
   She said she saw repercussions of Westmoreland's statement in
her classroom Tuesday when one student called another a ``nigger.''
She said when she reprimanded the student for the language, he
responded, ``That white man on TV said it.''
   Mrs. Whitmire set a special council session for Friday to
discuss a resolution against racist remarks. On Wednesday, she told
reporters she has refrained from making any public comment on
Westmoreland because she believed the voters would decide the issue.
   ``If he worked for me, I would have asked for his resignation,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
