<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 03,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Nov. 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>President of Catholic Bishops' Conference Exercised Quiet Diplomacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peacemaker is the role Archbishop John L. May of
St. Louis envisioned for himself three years ago when he became
president of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
   No wonder. In the fall of 1986, his predecessor, Bishop James
Malone of Youngstown, Ohio, was warning of a ``growing and
dangerous disaffection'' of American Catholics from the Holy See
and the bishops were in uproar over action taken against Seattle's
liberal Archbishop Raymond Hunthausen.
   As May prepares to leave office next week, he says he wants to
be remembered for helping develop ``a very strong understanding''
between the 53 million-member Roman Catholic Church in the United
States and the Vatican.
   ``There is a real growing understanding of American culture,
American ways, American experiences,'' May said in an interview.
``That helps us greatly that we don't waste our time in this
perceived difference, perceived dissension.''
   The low-key leadership exerted by the 67-year-old May is
credited in part for the new period of good will. Hunthausen, who
was stripped of some of his powers for opening churches to
homosexual worshipers and dispensing general absolution of sin to
large groups, has regained control of his archdiocese and the
Vatican has been generous in its praise of U.S. seminaries and
religious orders.
   Archbishop Daniel E. Pilarczyk of Cincinnati, vice president of
the bishops' conference, said May is ``unflappable, always
proceeding along and getting it done.''
   The Rev. Thomas J. Reese of Woodstock Theological Center at
Georgetown University in Washington, D.C., said May's
``non-threatening'' style was particularly helpful in Vatican
relations.
   ``He's a quiet, self-effacing kind of a guy. That kind of a
personality was very useful in dealing with Rome,'' said Reese,
author of ``Archbishop: Inside the Power Structure of the American
Catholic Church.''
   May credits much of the reduced tension to a series of meetings
between U.S. church leaders and Vatican officials and Pope John
Paul II's visit to the United States in 1987.
   What particularly impressed the pope on his U.S. visit, May
said, was the growing Hispanic presence in the church and the
religious vitality displayed at an ecumenical meeting with
fundamentalists, evangelicals and other Protestant religious
leaders in Columbia, S.C.
   ``The experience there eclipsed anything he's ever had in
ecumenical meetings,'' May said. ``He couldn't believe it.''
   May began his priesthood in 1947 as an assistant pastor of a
Chicago parish. He became auxiliary bishop of the Archdiocese of
Chicago in 1967 and was appointed bishop of the Diocese of Mobile,
Ala., in 1969. He was installed as archbishop of the Archdiocese of
St. Louis in 1980.
   Along with helping improve relations with the Vatican, the
moderate May also won praise for his ability to work with liberal
and conservative camps in the bishops' conference.
   ``He was someone who didn't have kind of a platform, didn't have
his own agenda he wanted to push,'' Reese said. ``He was as much a
follower as a leader.''
   Malone said May ``works with a quiet confidence.''
   ``I think he has been able to bring during his time a sure
leadership. I think he stood at the center, with an opening to the
left,'' Malone said.
   When a statement on AIDS from the bishops' administrative board
came under fire for giving conditional approval to condom education
in public schools, May agreed to have another committee of bishops
develop a second statement. That statement, which goes before the
conference at its fall meeting next week, makes no mention of
condoms, but May insists, ``The AIDS position we took previously is
still intact and has not been withdrawn.''
   When the Rev. George A. Stallings Jr. formed a separate
congregation for black Catholics in Washington earlier this year,
May acknowledged elements of racism in the church and told the
nation's estimated 2 million black Catholics, ``We need to
recognize more black leadership; our liturgies need more of the
vibrancy, and our policies more of the insight, of African
Americans.''
   As the abortion debate has heated up, the Catholic Church has
come under renewed criticism for its teachings, but May said the
bishops had no intention of backing down on their stance that ``an
unborn child cannot be killed for any purpose.''
   ``First of all, we believe that is our right as citizens of this
country and to be teachers of the Gospel to enter into these
discussions,'' May said.
   The right to participate in public debate without imposing
morality on others ``is the American concept,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Nov. 3</NOTE>
