<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 03,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Nov. 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religious leaders attending a recent seminar on
health issues were urged to focus attention on the social problems
that keep blacks, Hispanics and other minorities from seeking
health care.
   ``In this country we find a pronounced and stubborn disparity
between the health status of minority Americans and the rest of
us,'' said Dr. James Mason, assistant secretary of the Department
of Health and Human Services. ``That disparity stands today as an
affront to American ideals.''
   Former U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop said churches must
work harder at their spiritual mission to be a compassionate buffer
between society and the sick but unwanted. Compassion for AIDS
victims tops the list, he said.
   ``The American people may not be inclined to be compassionate,''
he said. ``We have to break down barriers. Until we do that,
there's no point in calling ourselves a church.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks in America are finding their advances
toward social, political and economic equality stalled by recent
Supreme Court decisions, the Executive Council of the United Church
of Christ contends.
   The 44-member body recently said the rulings have made it harder
for blacks to redress racial discrimination in the courts. It said
the 1.6 million-member church must ``declare by official action a
renewed determination to eliminate racism within church and
society.''
   The Executive Council acts on behalf of the church's main
deliberative body between biennial General Synod meetings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Jewish Committee is giving its
highest honor to Ronald Reagan.
   The former president will receive the committee's American
Liberties Medallion for ``his exemplary leadership in support of
the state of Israel and lifetime commitment to the freedom of
Soviet Jewry.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men are far more likely than women to be
asked to lead public prayers at Southern Baptist worship services,
according to a new survey.
   Men are asked 83 percent of the time to lead public prayers,
while women are asked 15 percent of the time, according to the 334
pastors who responded to a survey sent out by the Southern Baptist
Sunday School Board.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints should take some credit for Utah having the nation's highest
adoption rate and lowest abortion rate, the head of the National
Committee for Adoption says.
   ``Not only do the Mormons place a strong emphasis on family
values, but the state of Utah has a substantial number of very
good, professional social service agencies which are operated by
the church and whose services include adoptions,'' William Pierce
said in an interview with a church publication.
   There were 52 adoptions for every thousand abortions and
out-of-wedlock births in Utah in 1986, according to a church
release. The Utah abortion rate is 122 per 1,000 births, as
compared to 423 per 1,000 births for the nation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eight seminaries of the Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America are facing a financial crisis and need a
coordinated effort to build their endowments, one seminary
president says.
   Roger W. Fjeld, president of Wartburg Theological Seminary in
Dubuque, Iowa, said four seminaries had deficits in the last school
year, and six project deficits for this school year.
   ``Those seminaries which experienced deficits in fiscal year
1988-89 used up nearly half of their reserves in order to meet
current expenses. The remaining reserves of those seminaries are
likely to be used in the current year,'' Fjeld said at a board
meeting of the church's Division for Ministry.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Nov. 3</NOTE>
