<DOCNO> AP891101-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:ImageWorld Adv05   11-01 1179</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Image World, Adv 05,1211</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Electric Boogey in the Art World</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Are neon lights windows to the soul? Can
billboards evoke the Renaissance?
   Imagine shampoo ads hanging in the Louvre, newspaper headlines
in the National Gallery, television sets at the Metropolitan Museum
of Art.
   Advertising and Art. Soup cans and the Mona Lisa. Billboards and
Michelangelo. Cable and Cubists.
   Visual images _ magazines, television, film _ have forced
artists to acknowledge the enormous volume of information
transmitted each day and incorporate it in their work.
   From Nov. 9 through Feb. 18, the Whitney Museum of American Art
will present ``Image World: Art and Media Culture,'' a wide-ranging
exhibit of art and artifacts from the past 30 years, including
posters, magazine montages and a stamp machine.
   In a world where everything, even art, is for sale, ``Image
World'' shows how commerce can be turned into art. So get ready to
appreciate the aesthetic beauty of the five-day forecast, gaze at
lovingly drawn portraits of surveillance cameras and analyze
electronic transfers of Elvis.
   ``There's no way walking through the streets of New York one can
avoid this visual culture of these popular images,'' said John G.
Hanhardt, the Whitney curator who organized the show. ``You can't
even avoid television if you don't watch it. It influences the way
people dress, what they buy, how they talk.''
   In the last 300 years, has anyone made a greater impact on art
than Volney B. Palmer? Who? Why the founder of the first
advertising agency, of course, back in 1841. What about William
Henry Fox Talbot, who that same year patented the calotype, a paper
negative capable of producing multiple copies?
   And don't forget Earnest Elmo Colkins, who in 1890 promoted the
concept of art direction in advertisements, or Walter Dill Scott,
author of the 1908 book, ``The Psychology of Advertising,'' which
urged the incorporation of emotional and motivational techniques
into the selling of products.
   Starting in the late 1950s, Nam June Paik, Andy Warhol, James
Rosenquist, Roy Lichtenstein and other artists attacked the
onslaught of product and imagery, taking recognizable objects and
placing them within the structure of the art world. That meant
glossy portraits of cigarette ads, a television set coated in
cement or a lifesize porcelain sculpture of Michael Jackson and his
chimpanzee.
   ``The show kind of tracks that response,'' said guest curator
Marvin Heiferman. ``You get a Warhol and wonder if it's critical or
celebratory. You have a picture of an electric chair or Elvis
Presley. Is he the `King' or some tragic heroic figure? There's an
enthusiasm and brashness which you didn't see before.''
   Media began creeping into art around 1912 when Braque and
Picasso used newspaper bits in their Cubist collages. A few years
later, Marcel Duchamp began appropriating actual consumer objects,
such as a paint advertisement, into his art.
   The works of Berlin Dadaists John Heartfield and Raoul Hausmann
consisted entirely of images cut from newspapers and magazines.
Surrealist Salvador Dali directed segments of Hollywood movies,
appeared in commercial advertisements and created ``Dali's Dream
House'' specially for the 1939 World's Fair.
   Also in 1939, Hollywood's most artistic and productive year ever
headlined by ``Gone With the Wind,'' an essay by art critic Clement
Greenberg, ``Avant-garde and Kitsch,'' warned that synthetic art
had become ``an integral part of our productive system in a way in
which true culture could never be,'' and that its ``enormous
profits are a source of temptation to the avant-garde itself.''
   With the proliferation of television after World War II, cereal
and toothpaste were being beamed into millions of homes every day.
Philip Morris cigarettes were smoked on ``I Love Lucy,'' quality
theater was presented by General Electric and John Cameron Swayze
was host for the ``Camel News Caravan.''
   ``Pop Art'' was the response, an attempt to inject ``truth'' in
advertising. It was created, ironically, by artists who had once
worked in the advertising world. Warhol designed shoe posters;
Rosenquist painted billboards in Times Square.
   ``I was struck by the numbness I felt by painting images like
huge noses and huge eyes,'' Rosenquist recalled.
   ``Eyes three feet wide. Noses 10 feet long. Very large imagery.
I couldn't focus on the image although I was mixing the color
accurately. I made paintings where I placed objects in the picture
plane in different scales, and where the largest and closest image
would be the most difficult to identify.''
   Movies were big when Paik was growing up in Korea, and Shirley
Temple was the most famous person in his country in 1937. He saw
television for the first time in the early 1950s and was working on
electronic music a decade later in Cologne, West Germany, when the
``idiot box'' inspired a stroke of genius.
   ``I was at an impasse, a dead end,'' the artist recalled. ``So I
thought I would rather create electronic pictures than electronic
music. There were electronic music composers but no electronic
picture composers.
   ``I bought 13 old TV sets in Germany and changed the insides of
them. Then I showed them in German galleries and got a very big
reception.''
   Technology. It's everywhere, and Pop Artists consumed it. Thanks
to the portable movie camera, one didn't have to be a Hollywood
director to make movies. Thanks to the silkscreen, a picture could
be lifted off a newspaper and duplicated on canvas.
   Anything can now be turned into art: manhole covers, toilets,
subway signs. At the ``Image World'' exhibit, even the ticket booth
can't be trusted. Dennis Adams, best known for his designs of bus
shelters, has put together a special construction.
   ``It's the idea of a ticket booth, using images of homelessness
instead,'' he said. ``There are photographic images that create the
walls of the ticket booth _ large photographic images _ and you'll
be paying through the slot in the photograph.
   ``I love those structures. They bring capitalism to its most
basic level, a small window with money being exchanged.''
   With originals by Warhol and Rosenquist now worth millions of
dollars, Adams sees his work as returning to the very idea of Pop,
making art accessible to the public, using everyday objects and
presenting them in a different way.
   ``Very simply, my work deals with the idea of taking a
functional structure that everyone recognizes and using that as a
kind of instrument for getting to another agenda,'' Adams said.
``The functional element is just a kind of decoy, a way of making a
viewer feel comfortable.''
   In an age of jumbotrons, space shuttles and photo opportunities,
the possibilities for art are limitless. Rosenquist talked of
projects involving electronic nymphs in space and particles of
nuclear ashes.
   It may all seem, literally, a million miles away from the
Sistine Chapel, but Rosenquist insists art and communication have
always been linked.
   ``You go back to the gossip of the Renaissance paintings,'' he
said. ``Later on, printing started, and hand-in-hand with art,
communication changed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
