<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-01 0787</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0825</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has reached agreement
with House leaders on a plan to raise the minimum wage gradually to
$4.25 an hour by April 1991, the first increase since 1981.
   The agreement Tuesday for a 90-cent-an-hour hike over the next
17 months also provides for an unprecedented subminimum ``training
wage'' that could be paid to teen-agers with little work
experience. It would be pegged at 85 percent of the prevailling
minimum wage.
   The House is expected to vote this week on the compromise,
designed to end a lengthy and often bitterly partisan battle.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New home sales took their steepest dive in
nearly eight years last month while the government's chief economic
forecasting gauge registered only a small increase, the government
reported.
   The Commerce Department's Index of Leading Indicators, designed
to foretell economic activity six to nine months in advance, inched
up 0.2 percent in September.
   At the same time, the department reported Tuesday that new home
sales dropped 14 percent, the sharpest decrease since a 19 percent
decline in January 1982 during the last recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wages and salaries boosted by teacher pay
raises jumped 1.6 percent from July through September, double the
increase of the previous three months, the Labor Department said.
   The government said Tuesday that the 1.6 percent increase in the
department's Employment Cost Index followed a gain of 0.8 percent
in the April-June period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. has offered to buy
Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. for about $3.13 billion, triggering
speculation about a bidding war for the maker of paper products,
lumber and plywood.
   Great Northern's stock price leaped nearly 50 percent Tuesday,
exceeding Georgia-Pacific's offering price.
   The deal would place 10 million acres of timberland, 64,000
employees and numerous pulp and paper operations in
Georgia-Pacific's hands. Georgia-Pacific had $9.5 billion in sales
last year, Great Northern $3.6 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government said it would drop its
``golden share'' power to veto any takeover of Jaguar PLC if the
luxury car maker's shareholders approved such a move, possibly
clearing the way for a bidding war.
   The decision Tuesday, which surprised Jaguar, would allow for
General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. or other potential suitors to
make proposals to Jaguar shareholders. Both GM and Ford have
ownership stakes in Jaguar.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Azoff, one of the most powerful and
highly regarded executives in the music business, says he is
forming his own label in a joint venture with Warner Bros. Records,
the leading U.S. record company.
   The as yet-unnamed recorded music and music publishing business,
to be based in Los Angeles, will open Jan. 1., Azoff said Tuesday.
Azoff spent 16 years managing the careers of rock stars, then
became head of MCA Records in 1983 and was widely credited with
resurrecting that label.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products rose 0.7
percent from September to October, leaving the monthly average also
0.7 percent above the year-earlier level, the Agriculture
Department said.
   Higher prices for hogs, milk, lettuce and tomatoes were mostly
responsible for the increase from the September average, the
department's Agricultural Statistics Board said Tuesday in its
preliminary report. Lower prices were reported for broilers,
soybeans, cattle and corn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. has abandoned index
arbitrage trading for its clients, joining an exodus of big Wall
Street firms from the controversial trading strategy being blamed
for increasing market volatility.
   Shearson, the nation' second-largest retail brokerage, said
Tuesday it had abandoned all new index arbitrage for client
accounts effective immediately. It stopped such trading for its own
account in January 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines has submitted its revised
reorganization plan to creditors after the creditors' committee
dropped plans to develop alternatives to the company's own plan.
   Joel Zweibel, a New York attorney representing the unsecured
creditors' committee, said Tuesday that creditors will vote on the
plan in a week. The plan details Eastern's proposals for repaying
its debts after it emerges from Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization that protects it from creditors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market surged higher Tuesday in a broad-based rally
analysts said was triggered by news of a $3 billion takeover offer
for Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. The Dow Jones industrial average
jumped 41.60 points to finish at 2,645.08.
   The dollar ended higher against key currencies in quiet trading.
   Bond prices finished mixed.
   Pork belly futures prices soared the permitted daily limit of 2
cents a pound; livestock futures rose; precious metals fell
sharply; stock-index futures rallied; oil futures were mixed; and
grains and soybeans were mostly lower.
</TEXT>
