<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WaterCleaner     11-01 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water Cleaner,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owners of Norelco Water Cleaner Eligible for Refunds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some owners of a popular water cleaning
machine are entitled to refunds because the appliance actually
added a harmful chemical to drinking water, the Federal Trade
Commission said.
   The agency said Tuesday that consumers who bought the Norelco
Clean Water Machine and replacement filters for them are eligible
for a full refund under a recent settlement agreement reached with
the manufacturer.
   The commission last year charged Norelco with false advertising
in its claims that the Clean Water Machine removed harmful
chemicals from drinking water because the unit actually added
methylene chloride, a potentially hazardous chemical, into water
passing through the machine.
   The commission said methylene chloride, a volatile organic
industrial solvent, was used to glue together filters for the
machines that were marketed from 1982 to 1986. As water passed
through the machines the methylene chloride leached into the water,
the agency said.
   North American Philips Corp., Norelco's parent, has agreed to
provide $2.5 million to pay customer refunds.
   Consumers must submit refund applications no later than Dec. 31,
1989. The forms and additional information are available from:
Dianne M. Nast, Esq., Kohn, Savett, Klein &amp; Graf, P.C., 1101 Market
Street, Suite 2400, Philadelphia, Pa. 19107, 215-238-1700.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891101-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ProgramTrading     11-01 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Program Trading,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Ends Index Arbitrage for Clients; Backs Higher Index Futures
Margin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. is calling for
increasing the amount of borrowed money needed to buy stock-index
futures in an effort to curb computerized program trading, which is
being blamed for market turmoil.
   Shearson, the nation's second-largest retail brokerage, called
for the reform Tuesday after joining an exodus of big Wall Street
firms by abandoning index arbitrage trading for clients.
   ``It has become increasingly clear since the afternoon of Oct.
13 that volatility is damaging the fianancial markets and the
ability of corporate America to raise capital efficiently,''
Shearson said in a statement.
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged more than 190 points in
a few hours on Oct. 13. Many market professionals blamed the
rapidity of the decline on computerized program trading strategies.
   Meanwhile Tuesday, John J. Phelan Jr., the chairman of the New
York Stock Exchange, said the exchange plans to re-examine its
rules on trading halts during wild price swings in the market.
   Phelan said the trading halts, called circuit breakers, may not
be adequate. He told The New York Times that the exchange may
consider circuit breakers that would halt trading in the futures
markets in Chicago as well as at the Big Board in New York. The
exchange's board is scheduled to meet Thursday.
   In an interview with The Washington Post, Phelan warned that the
market could be ruined if it does not check the price swings.
   ``If it keeps up long enough, it is going to destroy the markets
as a capital-raising mechanism, much less as a place where people
can invest intelligently,'' Phelan said.
   ``A lot of people think it is a a New York Stock Exchange
issue,'' he told the Post. ``It is a national issue _ liquidity in
all markets and volatility in all markets. It affects individual
investors because they get frightened to death of this volatility
that is there, and we don't blame them.''
   Six other Wall Street firms have said in the last week they
would abandon program trading for some or all of their accounts.
Shearson stopped index arbitrage trading for its own account in
January 1988.
   Shearson called for ``consistent margins'' on stocks and
stock-index futures in an attempt to reduce the rapid trading of
futures believed to spur trading in stocks.
   Federal regulations limit the amount of borrowed money used to
buy stocks to 50 percent, while investors may play stock index
futures with only a 10 percent deposit.
   Index abitrage involves sophisticated computer programs that
seek to capitalize on brief and minute differences in the prices of
stocks and stock-index futures by simultaneously buying or selling
stocks with opposite trades in the futures.
   Stock-index futures are contracts to buy or sell baskets of
stocks based on particular indexes, such as the Standard &amp; Poor's
500 index.
   Critics of program trading maintain that index arbitrage can
speed declines in stocks by flooding the market with sell orders,
encouraging waves of panic selling. The strategy was blamed for
worsening the October 1987 market crash.
   Many firms backed away from program trading after the crash but
returned gradually as the market stabilized.
   Like other firms, Sheason indicated it does not believe program
trading alone is responsible for recent rapid market movements,
saying that ``economic fundamentals will ultimately determine the
direction of stock prices over the long term.''
   But Shearson said it supported a series of changes aimed at
helping to ``minimize sudden, destructive moves in the market.''
   Shearson, a subsidiary of American Express, accounted for just
2.2 percent of all index arbitrage on the New York Stock Exchange
in September, trading a total of 11.5 million shares via computer
program strategies.
   The firm also said it supported restricting or eliminating
electronic access to the NYSE for program traders during volatile
periods and consolidating all stocks and derivative products under
a single regulatory body.
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., the largest retail brokerage, said Monday
it would halt so-called index arbitrage for clients until the stock
market calms down. Paine Webber Group Inc. took a similar step last
week.
   Kidder Peabody &amp; Co. said Monday it would execute index
arbitrage trades only for clients, not for its own account. Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co. Inc., Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. and Oppenheimer &amp; Co. made
similar announcements last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
