<FIRST>r f PM-JobTraining     11-01 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Job Training,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Criticize Administration on Job Training</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Minimum Wage, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Roberts'' in 2nd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats on a joint congressional committee
have criticized the Bush administration for scheduling further
conferences on job training rather than proposing specific
legislation.
   ``It's ridiculous that we have to re-invent the wheel like this
every year,'' Rep. James H. Scheuer of New York told Assistant
Secretary of Labor Roberts Jones.
   Scheuer said Tuesday the problem has been so well studied that
all Jones would have to do is sit down with previous administration
officials for an hour over lunch.
   Such a meeting could produce a good program, ``and you won't
have to wait until next spring,'' said Scheuer. ``Why can't you hit
the deck running?'' he asked.
   Jones was the administration's witness at a hearing of the Joint
Economic Committee, headed by Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., which
met to explore the growing gap between work skills and the needs of
employers.
   Gore chided the administration for ``a lack of precision in
connection with what needs to be done'' to make sure that workers
have the mental skills for jobs in a more complex service economy.
   Jones, the top department official for employment and training,
told the committee that the department next spring will convene ``a
national conference of employers, unions, educators and training
professionals.''
   Jones cited in his testimony the need for programs emphasizing
the the transition from school to work, including young people who
go directly from high school to jobs.
   He said the spring conference has many of the officials
mentioned by Gore and Scheuer and added: ``I don't think the
solutions come in any instant legislative package ... It's going to
happen with a fundamental change in the education system.''
   He said those changes have to originate with the setting of
educational norms at the state and local level.
   Gore and Scheuer pressed Jones to make a commitment to full
financing for the Head Start preschool training program, which the
two said has proven its effectiveness beyond a doubt.
   But Jones said it would be ``irresponsible'' to make a
commitment. ``It's got to be balanced in the context of other
programs.''
</TEXT>
