<FIRST>r f BC-Braniff-Azima     11-01 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Braniff-Azima,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman Exploring Braniff Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farhad Azima, founder of the now-defunct
Global International Airways Corp. of Kansas City, said Tuesday he
was investigating the possibility of buying troubled Braniff Inc.
   Azima said that if he was successful, the airline could operate
60 to 80 flights a day from Kansas City, its main hub, to about 30
cities.
   Braniff, based in Orlando, Fla., was operating 93 daily flights
from Kansas City International Airport when it filed for Chapter 11
Bankruptcy Court protection from its creditors in late September.
It now has 20 daily flights from the airport.
   Azima told the Kansas City Times he had discussed the prospect
of buying Braniff, or part of it, with several Kansas City
businessmen. However, Azima said, other investors would not be
essential.
   Azima's effort is separate from that of John Latshaw, a longtime
Kansas City securities executive who has discussed pooling money
from area investors to buy Braniff.
   Azima said he owns a Kansas City aircraft leasing company,
Aviation Leasing Group, that also operates in the Caribbean and
Europe. Azima also has a small airline called Buffalo Airways based
in Waco, Texas, that hauls cargo.
   He said he had retained Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. to place a
value on Braniff or at least part of it.
   Azima was president of Global International Airways, a Kansas
City company that became one of the country's biggest air cargo and
passenger charter carriers before running into financial trouble.
   Global International sought to reorganize under Chapter 11 of
the bankruptcy laws in 1983 but later was forced to liquidate.
   In 1986, the Federal Aviation Administration's records showed
that a plane owned by Azima was linked to an arms shipment to Iran.
An attorney for Global International responded at that time that
Azima had leased the plane to another company and had no knowledge
of how the plane had been used. No charges against Azima resulted.
</TEXT>
