<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-TimkenStrike     11-01 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Timken Strike,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Timken Workers Ratify Agreement, Ending Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel workers at Timken Co. ratified a
four-year contract Tuesday, ending a 5{-week strike over wages and
pensions.
   Timken spokesman Jim Mulder said the agreement gives employees
an immediate 43-cent-an-hour cost-of-living adjustment that will be
added to the average base wage of $11.83 an hour, plus an hourly
raise of 25 cents. The agreement includes a 25-cent hourly increase
in 1990, a 50-cent increase in 1991 and a cost-of-living adjustment
in 1992, Mulder said.
   Workers with more than 30 years at the company will be
guaranteed a minimum pension payment of $1,000 a month when they
retire, Mulder said. He said employees will start returning to work
Wednesday.
   Mary Walker, a spokeswoman for United Steelworkers Local 1123 in
Canton, said the estimated vote by union members at Timken plants
in Canton, Columbus and Wooster was 2,300 in favor of the contract
to 1,600 against.
   About 5,400 workers went on strike Sept. 25 over pension
benefits and pay after rejecting the company's four-year contract
proposal.
   The company makes alloy steel bars, tubes and bearings for the
automotive, railroad and construction industries.
</TEXT>
