<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ReebokBlitz Bjt   11-01 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reebok Blitz, Bjt,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reebok Plans $15 Million Ad Blitz for Pump Basketball Shoe Introduction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reebok International plans to pump $15 million
into advertising its new inflatable basketball shoe that the
sneaker maker hopes will make the company a bigger force on the
court _ as well as off it.
   Reebok executives said the eight-month ad blitz for their new
shoe, called The Pump, makes it the largest product introduction
ever in the footwear industry.
   But Reebok's main competitor, Nike Inc., said it already is
shipping similar shoes called Nike Air Pressure to retailers
without creating a splashy and expensive ad campaign.
   Nike spokeswoman Elizabeth Dolan said the Beaverton, Ore.-based
company has always had a reputation for technological innovation,
and sniffed, ``We don't have to stake the whole farm on one shoe.''
   No matter what else they are, these shoes are expensive _
Reebok's cost $170 a pair and Nike's go for $175.
   Securities analysts said Reebok may be looking for a
high-profile way to let people know it is going after people more
interested in performance than fashion. The company has had more of
a reputation as a trend innovator than as a maker of serious
athletic shoes.
   ``The actual percentage of the market that would need a shoe
like this is fairly small,'' said Elizabeth Armstrong, who follows
sneaker makers for the investment firm Prescott Ball &amp; Turben.
   She said Reebok, based in Canton, Mass., may be hoping the
attention it gets for this top-end basketball shoe will help
``sales of the shoes below it.''
   Nike is the leader in basketball shoes, selling $414 million
worth last year, according to the Nike spokeswoman.
   Frank O'Connell, president of Reebok North America, said
basketball shoes accounted for $300 million of Reebok's $1.3
billion in domestic sales last year.
   Atlanta Hawks basketball star Dominique Wilkins was on hand
Tuesday for the introduction of The Pump at a news conference on
the basketball court at Hunter College in Manhattan.
   Wilkins and NBA players Byron Scott, Danny Ainge, Dennis Johnson
and Doc Rivers, and coaches Pat Riley of the Los Angeles Lakers and
Digger Phelps of Notre Dame, appear in ads debuting later this
month in which they describe in unrehearsed and often humorous
style how the shoes work.
   ``Some people like BMW's; I like gym shoes,'' Rivers said in one
ad.
   The high-top shoes have an orange button on the tongue that can
be pressed to pump air into a specially-designed plastic bladder,
forming a readily-adjusted cushion around the ankle, heel and
instep to support the foot and protect it against the damaging
effects of jarring, sudden moves.
   Air is released by depressing a separate valve on the collar of
the shoe.
   Wilkins told the news conference the inflatable shoes give him
support and let him skip taping his ankles as he must with other
shoes before playing.
   The Nike Air Pressure shoes use a different technology to create
an air collar around the ankle of the shoe and are inflated with a
small plastic hand pump.
   Ms. Dolan said that while a separate pump may not be convenient,
Nike's tests showed an internal pump system could not withstand the
beating shoes take in tournament-style play.
   But Nike may be turning the separate pump to its advantage. It
sells the shoes and the pump in a special carrying case that could
connote status.
   Ms. Dolan said the case emphasizes that the shoes are made for
serious basketball players. ``They wear their regular shoes to the
court and change to their basketball shoes,'' she said.
</TEXT>
