<SECOND>PM-Lujan-IPAA, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0027,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Secretary Says Environment to Be Considered in Energy Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes cycle designator. Minor editing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan has
asked independent oil producers to help develop a national energy
plan and said that the oil industry must consider the environment
to move forward.
   ``Over the next few months, I want to invite you to give us your
comments and suggestions on how America can move towards a brighter
energy future,'' Lujan said Tuesday. ``I challenge you to bring
creative, innovative suggestions.''
   Lujan, speaking to the Independent Petroleum Association of
America, said the Department of the Interior is working with the
Energy Department on a national energy strategy that will include a
mix of oil, natural gas, coal, nuclear power, renewable energy and
energy conservation.
   While developing a domestic energy policy, Lujan said, the
United States and energy industry face the challenge of ``securing
a healthy and safe environmental future for our children and future
generations of America.''
   In a news conference afterward, Lujan said, ``You have to be
more environmentally sensitive if you're going to move the industry
along.''
   As for his own agency, Lujan said, the Department of the
Interior now has more of an ``environmental tilt'' than in past
administrations.
   Lujan said he doesn't believe oil imports will decrease any time
soon and are approaching 60 percent of the U.S. oil supply.
   He also said that opposition to oil well drilling on the outer
continental shelf, particularly off the Florida and California
coasts, will preclude much future exploration and development there.
   ``It's going to be very difficult for us to offer those
resources.''
   Lujan is chairing a five-agency task force expected to make
recommendations to President Bush in early 1990 on drilling on the
outer continental shelf.
</TEXT>
