<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 0813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-Jaguar 1stLd-Writethru f0017 11-01 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Jaguar, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0017,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Soar After Government Says It Won't Block Jaguar Takeover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE stock price, SUBS 7th graf, `Jaguar's shares ...'
Picks up 8th graf pv, `Trade Secretary ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaguar PLC's shares soared on London's Stock
Exchange after the government said it was prepared to waive its
right under a special Jaguar share it owns to block a takeover of
the British luxury automaker.
   The government's announcement Tuesday, which surprised Jaguar,
makes it possible for General Motors Corp. or Ford Motor Co. _ both
of which own Jaguar stakes _ or any other suitor to take proposals
to Jaguar's shareholders.
   Industry analysts in the United States said the decision by the
government of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher benefits Ford more
than GM. GM has said it would like a minority stake in Jaguar,
while Ford has said it might mount a full takeover bid.
   ``It makes the game a little more fair right now,'' said analyst
Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. in New
York. ``As of yesterday, it looked like GM was the favorite. Now,
it looks like it's anybody's game.''
   ``It suggests to me that the government is more pro-shareholder
than anything else,'' said analyst Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley
and Co. of New York. ``Once again the Thatcher philosophy of
non-intervention could prevail here.''
   Both Ford and GM could use the prestige of a Jaguar nameplate in
their model lineup and Jaguar's manufacturing and technical
facilities in England. There have been reports that GM and Jaguar
were working on a proposal for a jointly produced vehicle, but
neither company has commented on it.
   Jaguar's shares were trading at the equivalent of $13.97 in
London at midday Wednesday, up 24 cents from Tuesday's close. They
rose $1.93 in Tuesday's session.
   Trade Secretary Nicholas Ridley said in the House of Commons
that if Jaguar's shareholders voted by a 75 percent majority to
lift a 15 percent restriction on holdings in Jaguar, the government
would drop its special, or ``golden,'' share that it could use to
block any takeover.
   The golden share and the 15 percent limit had been due to expire
at the end of 1990. The restrictions were established in 1984 when
the government sold the former state-owned car maker.
   Ridley said the government's remaining role would be to assess
the impact a takeover might have on competition in the British auto
industry.
   Jaguar, which has suffered from a slump in U.S. sales, on which
it depends heavily, is looking for a partner to give it financial
and technological support, but it wants to remain independent.
   But Jaguar's shareholders are unlikely to agree to proposals
that fall short of a full bid, analysts have said.
   The luxury carmaker could fetch up to $15.80 a share, or $2.8
billion, if GM and Ford engage in a bidding war for Jaguar,
analysts have estimated.
   GM has been holding friendly talks with Jaguar in recent weeks
in an effort to reach a cooperation agreement with the company,
which is expected to be announced by mid-November.
   The agreement is expected to call for GM to take a minority
stake of perhaps 30 percent in Jaguar and run several joint
ventures, including the manufacture of a new, cheaper Jaguar.
   Ford has said it has a 13.2 percent interest in Jaguar through
market stock purchases. Ford has said that it is prepared to mount
a full bid for Jaguar once the takeover restrictions are dropped.
   Both U.S. auto makers have obtained U.S. regulatory approval to
buy up to 15 percent of Jaguar.
   Ford spokesman Rex Greenslade in Detroit said Tuesday that his
company had no comment on anything to do with Jaguar.
   GM spokesman Jack Harned read a company statement saying the
automaker would study the action by the British government. He
declined to answer any questions.
   Jaguar, which has been holding talks with numerous companies in
the past 18 months, said it hadn't been consulted in advance about
Ridley's move. ``We were surprised at the action taken,'' the
company said in a statement.
   Jaguar emphasized that its articles of association still prevent
any individual or company from owning more than 15 percent of
Jaguar without a special resolution at an extraordinary shareholder
meeting.
   An extraordinary meeting can be called by the board or by a
shareholder who has a Jaguar holding of at least 10 percent, said
Jaguar spokesman Arnold Bolton.
