<FIRST>r f BC-UnisysSuit     11-01 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Unisys Suit,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Stockholder Sues Board, Alleging Withheld Information</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Unisys Corp. stockholder has filed a class
action suit accusing the company's board of using misleading and
false information to receive a 1988 shareholders' vote supporting
the board.
   Henry L. Housman, of the Philadelphia metropolitan area, names
13 board members in Tuesday's suit, which alleges that the
company's 1988 Proxy Statement failed to disclose facts concerning
fraud in connection with government defense contracts, an internal
investigation of defense contracting units and a ``continuing
cover-up'' of wrongdoings.
   Unisys, a leading producer of electronics-based information
systems with more than 92,500 employees, designs and manufactures
main frame computers, software and systems engineering support
services for use in various technology defense projects.
   The precise number of plaintiffs are not known, but consist of
anyone who held Unysis common stock on March 22, 1988, when the
proxy statement was issued, according to the suit. There are over
158 million shares of Unisys common stock outstanding, held by over
42,000 holders of record.
   The 1988 Proxy Statement requested shareholders to approve an
indemnification agreement, which would have protected board
directors against lawsuits ``by reason of the fact that the
director is or was serving one or more capacities as a director or
officer of'' the company.
   The suit alleges that Unisys directors have artificially
inflated labor and cost data, entered into sham consulting
agreements, made illegal contributions, padded expense accounts,
inflated invoices submitted by subcontractors and permitted some
individuals to benefit personally by funneling money through hollow
``fund companies.''
   Unisys has been the subject of several federal law enforcement
and grand jury investigations, including the ongoing ``Operation
Ill Wind'' dealing with defense contractors, and, the suit alleges,
could thereby be subject to potential fines from $30 million to $60
million.
   James R. Malone, Jr., the attorney representing the
shareholders, said he knew of two similar cases against Unisys in
Eastern Pennsylvania and another in Delaware. He declined to
comment on the other cases, which are still in litigation.
   The suit seeks to have the board members removed and to have the
actions taken as a result of the proxy declared null and void, in
addition to unspecified damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
