<FIRST>u f PM-PhilipMorris 1stLd-Writethru   11-01 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philip Morris, 1st Ld-Writethru,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Plans Massive Corporate TV Ad Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Expands on original, which was sent inadvertently.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. Inc. is launching a
corporate-image advertising campaign that puts the Philip Morris
name in TV ads for the first time since the 1950s, when it quit
advertising its namesake cigarette brand on television.
   The campaign is a patriotic tribute to the 200th anniversary of
the Bill of Rights, a favorite issue of supporters of ``smokers'
rights.''
   But the TV advertising does not mention cigarettes or smoking,
the company said. Cigarette ads have been banned from television
since 1971, and Philip Morris quit advertising its Philip Morris
brand on TV in the early 1950s.
   Nonetheless, there were published reports today that some
anti-smoking activists fault the company for trying to score points
with the public by associating itself with a document that is a
cornerstone of American democracy.
   Philip Morris declined to say how much it planned to spend on
the advertising campaign. But one source familiar with the
company's plans said it could amount to $30 million a year for two
years.
   The first advertising in the campaign appeared in print and on
network television this morning.
   The ad contains a toll-free number people can call to obtain a
copy of the Bill of Rights, and Guy L. Smith IV, vice president for
corporate affairs at Philip Morris, said there were 5,000 calls in
the first hour after the commercial was on television.
   Smith said the company decided on this approach to familiarize
the public with a company that ``is a very different and much
larger company than it was just a few years ago.''
   In addition to its Philip Morris USA tobacco division, Philip
Morris also owns Miller Brewing Co. and Kraft General Foods.
   Its products include Marlboro cigarettes, Miller beer, Jell-O
desserts, Kraft cheese and salad dressings and Maxwell House coffee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
