<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   11-01 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Markets Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade with
market activity limited by the All Saints Day holiday in much of
Europe and South America.
   The corn market weakened slightly amid rumors that the Soviet
Union may delay taking delivery on some of the U.S. corn it
recently bought.
   Record-high Soviet corn purchases announced last month have
stirred concerns that the U.S. grain transportation system may be
strained in trying to deliver all the corn quickly.
   ``We're asking the transportation system to run full tilt and,
given the low water levels (for river shipping), it may be
difficult to achieve it,'' said Dale Gustafson, a grain analyst
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Some minor foreign purchases of U.S. wheat supported the wheat
market in early trading while soybeans were mostly lower due in
part to slack export demand.
   In early trading, wheat futures prices were { cent lower to 1{
cents higher with the contract for delivery in December at $3.94\ a
bushel; corn was { cent lower to } cent higher with December at
$2.37 a bushel; oats were \ cent to { cent lower with December at
$1.42\ a bushel; soybeans were \ cent to 1{ cents lower with
November at $5.57} a bushel.
   Cattle futures were lower while pork futures were mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent lower with December at
74.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .22 cent lower
with November at 83 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent lower to .18
cent higher with December at 46.52 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .42 cent lower to .10 cent higher with February at
55.70 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
