<FIRST>r f BC-Columbia-Sony     11-01 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Columbia-Sony,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Completes Tender Offer for Columbia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Guber-Peters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. said Wednesday that its $3.4 billion
tender offer for Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. had expired
as scheduled and it had been tendered or promised about 99 percent
of Columbia's shares.
   Sony and Columbia had reached an agreement Sept. 27 under which
the Japanese electronics and records company would launch a tender
offer of $27 a share for all of Columbia's stock.
   The offer expired at midnight Tuesday, and Sony said today that
it had been advised that it had either been tendered or promised
stock and warrants representing about 99.3 percent of Columbia's
outstanding shares, or 98.7 percent on a fully-diluted basis.
   Sony had said it hoped to complete the purchase of Columbia in
early November, and Sony USA spokesman Jason Farrow said Wednesday
that that was still a possibility.
   Columbia Pictures is an entertainment company which makes and
distributes movies and television programming and operates motion
picture theaters.
