<DOCNO> AP891101-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 2150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv03   11-01 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 03,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Friday, Nov. 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Time To Sell, A Time To Buy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A home-buying opportunity seems to be shaping up
for some of those people who were priced and ``rated'' out of the
market over the past couple of years.
   Median prices in most of the country have stabilized and are
likely to remain so with winter coming on, and mortgage rates have
fallen over the past month. Mortgage money is plentiful too, and
many sellers are eager.
   This latter factor is often overlooked by buyers accustomed to
feeling like beggars, but many sellers are reportedly anxious to
move their properties after enduring months of waiting, and missing
out on the August ``school'' market.
   For obvious reasons, families with school-age children often
plan their change of address before the beginning of a new school
year, making the late summer weeks among the very best for real
estate transactions.
   Partly reflecting this phenomenon, median home prices actually
declined in September from August in the four geographical regions
_ Northeast, Midwest, South and West _ measured by the National
Association of Realtors.
   The national median price for existing single-family homes in
September was $93,400, down $1,400 from August, although higher by
5.5 percent than a year earlier. Big price increases aren't
expected in most markets.
   Meanwhile, improvements in the mortgage market have made rates
more attractive compared to a year ago, or in fact to a few weeks
ago.
   HSH Associates, which monitors rates of 2,000 lenders
nationwide, reports fixed-rate, 30-year mortgages in single digits
again, and adjustable-rate mortgages far down into the 8 percent to
9 percent range.
   Its survey for the week ended Oct. 20 showed the national
average for 30-year fixed rates fell to 9.98 percent, compared with
10.03 percent a week earlier, and more than a full percentage point
lower than a year ago.
   Many of the indexes for adjustable-rate mortgages also have
fallen in recent weeks. The six-month Treasury bill fell to 7.42
percent on Oct. 20 from 7.64 percent a month earlier. The constant
maturity 3-year Treasury fell to 7.94 percent from 8.19 percent,
and the 5-year to 7.92 percent from 8.12 percent.
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. reports also show rates
declining. Its latest report, for September, listed 30-year
fixed-rate mortgages at 10.16 percent, compared with 11.19 percent
as recently as six months ago, amid indications of a further
decline in October and perhaps November too.
   HSH says its data base shows well over 550 lenders offering
30-year fixed-rate loans at under 10 percent, with many as low as
9.25 percent, a figure that even experienced mortgage people had
recently thought was a thing of the past.
   The news already has affected markets, suggesting that buyers
are extremely sensitive to rates. September sales of existing
single-family houses were at an annual rate of 3.63 million units,
4.3 percent higher than in August.
   Ira Gribin, Realtor president, believes that rate-consciousness
accounts for much of the increase. ``Many people who were forced to
put off trading up or entering the market earlier this year are
making their move now,'' he says.
   Realtor economist John Tuccillo believes that compared with
higher-priced houses, moderate-priced units tend to do well in the
fall, reflecting a market shift to smaller families whose decisions
aren't based on the school year.
   Paul Havemann, HSH vice president, thinks higher-priced units
will share in the improved market. Lower rates will spur all
buyers, he says, ``especially in higher-priced areas where sellers
are relucatant to lower their prices.''
   However, problems still remain for first-time buyers. While
price increases are not as common as they were a year ago, incomes
lag. Median prices in the Northeast and West remain close to
$145,000, while the September median in the Midwest was $71,800,
and in the South, $84,200.
   Medians can deceive, however, and discourage too, leading many
real estate people to point out that communities with high medians
might also have many sound houses priced well within the range of
first-timers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Friday, Nov. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
