<DOCNO> AP891101-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Kusumoto Adv05   11-01 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Kusumoto, Adv 05 ,0934</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minolta Man in the USA Has Been American Observer For Two Decades</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam Kusumoto, the head of Minolta Camera Co.'s
U.S. operations, says he doesn't envy his counterparts at American
corporations.
   ``I feel sorry for American CEOs. They have to be creative and
always coming out with new ideas,'' he said.
   And for an executive like him, ``a guy over 60,'' that can be
pretty stressful, said Kusumoto, president and chief executive
officer of Ramsey, N.J.-based Minolta Corp.
   American executives are under a lot of pressure, said Kusumoto.
While it's true they are highly paid, they also face high risks. If
their ideas don't work or if they make the wrong choice, ``They're
out of there,'' he said.
   Kusumoto, 61, who first came to the United States in 1954, has
been president of Minolta since 1969 _ making him one of the
longest-serving Japanese executives in America and giving him a
unique perspective on how a country left in ruins by war could turn
into one of the world's strongest economic powers.
   In 1987 he was elected secretary of the Japanese Chamber of
Commerce of New York. E.P. Dutton is publishing his autobiography,
``My Bridge to America,'' this month.
   In Washington recently to attend a White House luncheon,
Kusumoto, who now lives in Fort Lee, N.J., discussed the Japanese
way of management, the Japanese and U.S. educational systems and
Japan's image in America.
   While American corporations are run from the top down by
high-powered executives making astronomical salaries, Japanese are
run from the middle out, said Kusumoto. Middle managers, closer in
age to 35 than 65, tend to come up with the ideas and innovations.
Top management tends to keep a lower profile.
   If an idea is a success, the company shares the credit. If it
goes awry there's no finger-pointing or dismissals; everyone shares
the blame. Japanese workers see their company as a second family
and usually stay for the entire career.
   That stability, says Kusumoto, is one of the main reasons
Japanese corporations have been so successful since World War II.
   At Japanese companies, ``The difference between the top and the
bottom is not that great,'' he said.
   ``We don't have anybody making a million dollars,'' said
Kusumoto, arguing that because there isn't a vast salary gap
between executives and workers, there are fewer labor problems in
Japan.
   In fact, at most of Japan's largest companies, the top
executives' salaries are only about seven times greater than a new
employee right out of college, he said.
   To compensate for that, Japanese executives get lots of fringe
benefits: a company car _ maybe even a chauffeured limousine _ and
an unlimited expense account. In return, they have the peace of
mind that goes with stable, possibly lifetime employment.
   But that management style can run into problems when the
Japanese company operates in the United States, where success is
measured by salary and title.
   Fast-track American executives who don't get the raise or the
promotion they want move on, said Kusumoto, upsetting the harmony
that Japanese concerns strive for.
   To counter that, Minolta has come up with a simple plan: pay the
Americans more.
   Kusumoto noted that he has three Japanese vice presidents and
four American vice presidents and ``a few of the Americans make
more money than I do.''
   While none of the Japanese executives are making as much as the
Americans ``they don't care,'' said Kusumoto because they know it
is important to the company, which has earned their loyalty.
   As part of this drive to seek harmony, Kusumoto's staff, which
he takes to Japan once a year _ the Americans as well as the
Japanese _ make their decisions by consensus. In fact, there are so
many meetings, they've had to add several new conference rooms to
the New Jersey headquarters.
   ``The Japanese system, in my opinion, is better,'' Kusumoto said.
   Sam Kusumoto's given name is actually Sadahei. He was born to
Japanese parents in what is now Seoul, South Korea, where his
father was a successful Ford distributor.
   At the end of World War II the family returned to Japan, where
Kusumoto, then 18 years old, enrolled in Tokyo's Keio University,
majoring in economics. Shortly after completing his studies in
1953, Kusumoto joined Minolta.
   Within a year, he was sent to the United States as Minolta's
sole representative. He returned to company headquarters in Osaka
in 1959, rising to head the international sales division.
   Since 1969, when he was named head of Minolta's U.S. marketing
subsidiary for all its photographic and office automation products,
he has lived in this country with his family. His two daughters
went to American colleges.
   While trade deficits, import barriers and currency fluctuations
take their toll on U.S.-Japanese relations, Kusumoto thinks there
is something else ``irritating American people deep in their
heart:'' what they perceive as the ingratitude of the Japanese.
   ``One of the biggest problems in Japanese education is they
don't teach anything about (what happened) after World War II,'' he
said.
   Consequently, ``Young Japanese don't know what Americans did for
Japan after the war,'' and Americans can't understand why Japan
isn't more grateful for the assistance they rendered war-shattered
Japan.
   ``If the Japanese were more modest. If they said `Thank You
America.' Then, I think this Japan bashing would go,'' Kusumoto
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Nov. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
