<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     11-01 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
in directionless European trading Wednesday thinned by the All
Souls' Day holiday. Gold prices also declined.
   Financial markets were closed in Italy, Spain, France, and
Belgium for the holiday. In West Germany, only banks in Frankfurt
and northern Germany were open.
   Traders said they had no reason to take large positions before
Friday's release of the U.S. employment figures for October, which
are expected to confirm the U.S. economy's slower pace of growth.
   ``No one is willing to be over-adventurous ahead of Friday's
figures,'' said a corporate dealer in London.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose to 143.08 Japanese yen from 142.15 yen at
Tuesday's close. Later, in London, it rose further to 143.45 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5815 from $1.5775 late
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8377 West German marks, down from 1.8410; 1.6132 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6142; 6.2305 French francs, down from 6.2445; 2.0790
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0730; 1.1742 Canadian dollars, unchanged;
and 1,348.50 Italian lire, down from 1,349.75.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $374.25 a troy ounce from
$377.75 late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold traded at $373.40 an ounce,
down from $375.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold slipped $2.92 to close at $373.87 an
ounce.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid price of $5.18 a
troy ounce from $5.21 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
