<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0038,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Moderately Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished moderately higher Wednesday
in London, bolstered largely by continued gains on Wall Street and
technical factors affecting demand for blue-chip stocks.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 17.5
points, or 0.8 percent, higher at 2,160.1.
   The key index rose throughout most of the session after posting
a low of 2,141.7 in the first 40 minutes of trading. It ended the
day near its session high of 2,163.2, which was posted within the
last half-hour.
   Volume was a light 372.9 million shares, up from 334.5 million
on Tuesday.
   Dealers said most investor interest was focused on blue-chip
stocks. They said several key blue chips were pushed higher in
light volume due to a technical squeeze among market makers.
   The British pound's strong tone, combined with a steady opening
on Wall Street, also tempted some investors to come back to the
London market, dealers said. There was concern early in the day
that Wall Street's sharp gains on Tuesday were overdone and due for
a reversal.
   In London, the Financial Times 30-share index finished 16.7
points higher at 1,738.1. The Financial Times 500-share index rose
10.34 points to close at 1,198.81.
