<DOCNO> AP891101-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-BehindtheWheel Adv11-12   11-01 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 11-12,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 11-12, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>1990 Lincoln Town Car: Huge But Easy To Handle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't let the rounded edges on the 1990 Lincoln Town Car
disappoint you over the shrinking of true, unabashed American
luxury cars. The Town Car is still a monster.
   Indeed, this year's model is an inch longer and has a third of
an inch more wheelbase than the 1989 model. The rounded,
aerodynamic styling, borrowed from the Ford Taurus and Lincoln
Continental, just makes the new Town Car look slightly smaller.
   Once you're inside, however, you'll get the familiar
all-American picture: wide, pillow-soft seats, legroom ample for
even the Jolly Green Giant, and built-in comfort at every turn. The
carmaker boasts that the trunk, at 22 cubic feet, is the biggest in
the industry.
   The truth is, the redesigned 1990 Town Car, which had its last
major overhaul in 1979, isn't much of a departure from the previous
model, save for some smoothing of body panels and some fine-tuning
of handling features.
   For example, the test vehicle, a Cartier four-door model,
handled well despite its length of more than 18 feet, 4 inches. The
vehicle tackled winding mountain roads with remarkable ease, with
far less sway than might be expected, thanks to the addition of
rear air-spring load leveling and speed-sensitive, variable-assist
power steering.
   Inside, the ride was cushioned, as always; road bumps were
nearly imperceptible. The most I noticed were a couple of slight
jostlings on particularly rigorous roads and a bucking sensation a
couple of times.
   The 5-liter, V-8 engine, teamed with four-speed automatic
transmission with automatic overdrive, delivered good acceleration
even though it had to power more than 4,000 pounds of car (that's
about equal to the weight of two Hyundai Excel subcompacts).
   Fuel economy was rated at 17 mpg in the city and 24 mpg on the
highway, but in hard driving in the city and on the highway the
test car averaged 15.7 mpg.
   Safety items included standard driver and front-passenger
airbags, optional Traction-Lok axle ($101) that protects against
spinouts by keeping both tires rotating at the same speed even if
one loses traction on ice or sand, and optional antilock brakes.
These brakes, by the way, were excellent in panic stops, bringing
this huge car to a steady, controlled halt. But that option costs
$936.
   A less expensive option will save cold-weather drivers from
straddling the front of the car to scrape ice off the big
windshield. Ford offers Insta-Clear, a windshield that clears ice
with the touch of a dashboard button. It does this without the
windshield wires common to rear window defrosters. The only sign of
Insta-Clear is the window's pinkish tinge, from the addition of
special heat-conductive material. The cost is $253.
   Ford added other nice touches: a label and an arrow under the
dashboard fuel gauge indicating the side of the car with the gas
cap so you know how to pull up to the pumps; a button to open the
gas tank located on the dashboard rather than under or beside the
driver's seat; big handles on all four doors and on the backs of
the front seats to help entry and exit, and stereo speakers above
the front-door armrests that are so integrated into the design you
don't notice them.
   The Town Car also had the most powerful lumbar support of any
car I've tested. I was able to pressurize the system to the point I
felt I had a huge rock in the middle of my back.
   The major drawback to the Town Car is price. It starts at
$27,986 this model year, up 9.5 percent from the $25,562 starting
price in the 1989 model year, according to company spokesmen. The
upscale test car had a base price of $32,809. With options and
destination charge, it came to nearly $35,000.
   But the hefty price has not deterred more than 100,000 buyers in
recent years. More than 84,000 have been sold so far this year.
Ford Motor Co. expects the new styling to help boost sales from
121,674 in 1988 to 135,000 total in 1990.
   The new rounded look may help lure slightly younger buyers.
Spokesman Jim Trainor says previous Town Car buyers had an average
age of 59.8 years and household income of $58,800 annually.
   Seventy-four percent of buyers have been men, and 86 percent are
married, he says.
   Main competitors for the Town Car include the Cadillac Fleetwood
Brougham, which starts at $27,400, and the Cadillac Sedan DeVille,
which starts at $27,540.
   Consumer Reports magazine ranked 1982-86 model Town Cars as
average or above average in its trouble index, according to owner
reports.
   The 1987 Town Car dropped to worse than average in the trouble
index, a ranking that Trainor says baffles the company because the
magazine's list of specific trouble spots such as air conditioning,
fuel system and brakes ranked average across the board.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 11-12</NOTE>
</DOC>
