<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0305</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted in a narrow range today
after Tuesday's rally faded.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 41.60 on Tuesday,
dropped back 9.42 points to 2,635.66 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 740 up, 688 down and 508
unchanged.
   Stock prices in general got a lift Tuesday from news of a
takeover bid by Georgia-Pacific for Great Northern Nekoosa.
   Analysts said the news was taken as reassurance that merger and
acquisition activity wasn't going to disappear as a result of
recent problems involving several debt-financed buyout plans.
   Nekoosa shares, up 20[ on Tuesday, slipped back 1] to 61{ in
active trading today.
   At the same time, analysts said, worries persisted about the
numerous disappointments that showed up in corporate earnings for
the third quarter of the year.
   Those reports prompted talk of a possible significant slowdown
in the economy, and downward revisions of profit projections for
the rest of this year and early 1990.
   Georgia Gulf gained 1] to 50~. NL Industries, which holds a
stake of just under 10 percent of the company, offered to buy the
rest of the stock for $50 a share.
   Losers among the blue chips included American Express, down } at
35|; International Business Machines, down { at 99}; McDonald's,
down \ at 30}, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down { at 43}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.02 to 188.26. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.13 at 371.71.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 129.13 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
