<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   11-01 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures End Higher On Export Hopes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed
higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, ending a three-day
decline amid expectations for new export business and continued
dryness in winter wheat country.
   The markets opened lower on talk that the Soviet Union was
considering delaying the delivery of some of its recently purchased
U.S. corn, but prices turned higher at midday as rumors of pending
grain business with Far Eastern nations surfaced.
   Wheat futures got an additonal boost from reports of fairly dry
conditions in the central Plains with no rain in the weekend
forecasts.
   A report from private grain traders in Buenos Aires estimating
1989-90 Argentine planted corn acreage at the lowest level of this
century ``could be a long-term supportive factor,'' said Joel
Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   At the close of trading, wheat futures prices were 1{ cents to
3{ cents higher with the contract for delivery in December at $3.98
a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2 cents higher with December at
$2.37{ a bushel; oats were } cent to 1 cent higher with December at
$1.43{ a bushel; soybeans were \ cent to 4 cents higher with
November at $5.61} a bushel.
</TEXT>
