<FIRST>r f AM-Mortgages-Japan     11-01 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mortgages-Japan,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Investing in U.S. Mortgages Through New Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investors have pumped another $701
million into the U.S. mortgage market through two new mutual funds
that invest primarily in Fannie Mae mortgage-backed securities, it
was announced Wednesday.
   Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. is lead manager and investment adviser of
the new funds, which resemble a $575 million fund announced in June
by the Blackstone Group, Salomon Brothers Inc. and Goldman, Sachs.
The Blackstone Fund was the first tailored to attracting Japanese
money to the U.S. mortgage market.
   The funds indirectly help Americans buy homes by increasing the
pool of money available for mortgages, David O. Maxwell, chairman
and chief executive of the Federal National Mortgage Association,
or Fannie Mae, said in a statement.
   Fannie Mae buys home mortgage loans from the original issuers
and repackages some of them as mortgage-backed securities, which
are sold to the public. Investors get the flow of principal and
interest payments from the underlying loans. Fannie Mae currently
has $209 billion in mortgage-backed securities outstanding.
   Goldman, Sachs' partner in managing the offering was Japan's
Daiwa Securities Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
