<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GAFTrial     11-01 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF Trial,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Jury Hears GAF Stock Manipulation Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After two mistrials, the stock manipulation case
against GAF Corp. and a top executive opened Wednesday for a third
time.
   The new jury was not told that U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson
Lowe had declared mistrials on Jan. 10 and March 22 in the case
against the Wayne, N.J.-based chemicals and building materials
manufacturer and its vice chairman, James T. Sherwin.
   Arthur L. Liman, lead attorney for GAF, addressed the 12-member
panel in federal court in Manhattan after an hour-long opening
statement by Assistant U.S. Attorney Carl Loewenson Jr.
   Loewenson told the jury that Sherwin persuaded a Los Angeles
brokerage firm to illegally drive up Union Carbide Corp.'s stock
price in October 1986 so that GAF _ which had accumulated 10
million shares in a failed takeover bid _ could unload it at a
better price.
   Liman denied GAF was desperate to get rid of the stock. He said
GAF Chairman and Chief Executive Samuel J. Heyman was ``very
bullish, very optimistic'' about the future of Union Carbide.
   Liman said the government's case depends on the testimony of an
admitted felon, Los Angeles stockbroker Boyd L. Jefferies, who has
been testifying as part of a plea arrangement.
   Jefferies has testified twice that Sherwin induced him to
manipulate the stock and to hide the transaction.
   ``You have the power to keep Boyd Jefferies from pulling the
wool over your eyes and from perpetrating any misjustice,'' Liman
said.
   The lawyer claimed Jefferies has rehearsed his testimony at
least 25 times with government lawyers. ``The only thing they
didn't do is have him practice in front of a mirror,'' he said.
   Loewenson conceded there will be inconsistencies in the
testimony of Jefferies and his chief trader, James Melton. If their
recollections matched perfectly, he told the jury, ``you'd know
that they cooked up a story together.''
   GAF, two subsidiaries and Sherwin were indicted in July 1988 on
charges of securities fraud, wire fraud and conspiracy.
   The companies would face maximum fines totaling $12 million, or
$500,000 on each of eight counts against each of the three. Sherwin
would face 40 years in prison and a fine of up to $2 million.
   The GAF case was the first criminal trial stemming from the
insider trading scandals of the mid-1980s and were considered a
critical test of information supplied by jailed stock speculator
Ivan F. Boesky.
   Jefferies was implicated in the scandal by Boesky and pleaded
guilty to two securities fraud felonies. Earlier this year,
Jefferies was sentenced to probation and fined $250,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
