<DOCNO> AP891101-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1721EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-01 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended higher Wednesday against key
currencies in thin trading after falling overseas.
   Gold prices declined. On the Commodity Exchange in New York,
gold bullion for current delivery closed at $374.20 a troy ounce,
down 50 cents from late Tuesday. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a late bid for gold of $372.90 an ounce, down 45 cents.
   Currency dealers said technical factors within the market were
largely responsible for supporting the dollar Wednesday, although
reports of an earthquake in Japan may also have helped the dollar
at the expense of the Japanese yen.
   ``It was more related to the technical market factors and the
earthquake was a catalyst to create movement,'' said Trevor
Woodland, chief corporate trader for Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago.
   The U.S. Geological Survey reported that a major earthquake
registering 7.3 on the Richter scale struck off the northeast coast
of Japan's Honshu Island. It reportedly occurred in the same
general area as a series of earlier tremors during the past several
weeks.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose to 143.08 yen from 142.15 yen at Tuesday's
close. It traded at 143.45 yen in London, and at 143.80 yen in New
York, up from 142.87 yen Tuesday.
   Trading in Europe was quieter than usual Wednesday, with markets
in Italy, Spain, France and Belgium closed for the All Saints Day
holiday. In West Germany, only banks in Frankfurt and northern
Germany were open.
   The dollar was mixed against the British pound. Sterling rose to
$1.5815 from $1.5775 in London, but it fell to $1.5755 from $1.5805
in New York.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's quotes, included: 1.8505 West German marks, up from
1.8420; 1.6260 Swiss francs, up from 1.6160; 6.2740 French francs,
up from 6.2510; 1.1742 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1740; and
1,358.75 Italian lire, up from 1,352.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,
included: 1.8377 West German marks, down from 1.8410; 1.6132 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6142; 6.2305 French francs, down from 6.2445;
2.0790 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0730; 1.1742 Canadian dollars,
unchanged; and 1,348.50 Italian lire, down from 1,349.75.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $374.25 an ounce from
$377.75 late Tuesday. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold traded at
$373.40 an ounce, down from $375.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold slipped $2.92 to close at $373.87 an
ounce.
   Silver prices were lower. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery dipped to $5.150 a troy ounce from $5.180
Tuesday. Silver fell in London to $5.18 an ounce from $5.21.
