<FIRST>r f AM-Watkins-NaturalGas     11-01 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Watkins-Natural Gas,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Secretary Says Natural Gas Industry `On A Roll'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Natural gas has gone from being almost exotic to
an abundant, cheap source of clean fuel that plays an important
part in the nation's energy policy, Energy Secretary James D.
Watkins said Wednesday.
   ``It was wrong for us to write off natural gas in the 1970s,''
Watkins told the American Gas Association in its annual meeting.
``It would be equally wrong for us to look at natural gas, or any
fuel, as more than a component of our comprehensive energy
strategy.''
   Association members have lauded natural gas as an answer to
problems surrounding oil, mainly foreign imports and environmental
worries.
   Much attention has been paid to various programs using natural
gas, especially as a replacement for gasoline in powering vehicles
and for co-generation of electricity, areas Watkins highlighted
Wednesday in an industry he said was ``really on a roll.''
   ``Twelve years ago, in DOE's formative years, natural gas was
viewed as a scarce and dwindling resource,'' Watkins said. ``Today
we know natural gas can be a clean-burning, domestically abundant
fuel.''
   He said the department estimates that the nation has a 35-year
supply at prices of $3 per thousand cubic feet.
</TEXT>
