<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GreatNorthern Bjt   11-01 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Great Northern, Bjt,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia-Pacific Seeks Support for Great Northern Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. moved Wednesday to
muster support for its $3.13 billion takeover offer for Great
Northern Nekoosa Co., suggesting it could improve productivity and
stem the decline of Great Northern's Maine paper mills.
   Separately, Great Northern's board of directors held its
regularly scheduled meeting Wednesday at company headquarters in
Norwalk, Conn., but took no action on the tender offer, said
Stephen Hill, director of investor relations.
   Georgia-Pacific representatives fanned out across Maine to
promote the $58 a share proposal that if successful would create a
paper company owning more than 2.6 million acres.
   ``Our record of growth in the industry is a very clear record.
We are a very efficient, low-cost producer of what are very clearly
commodity products,'' said C.T. ``Kip'' Howlett Jr.,
Georgia-Pacific vice president for governmental affairs.
   Noting recent layoffs at Great Northern's mills in Millinocket
and East Millinocket, Howlett said there was ``a lot of potential
for improvement.'' Howlett didn't mention specifics but suggested
his company would introduce a more varied product mix, adding
fiberboard and structural wood paneling to the current output of
newsprint and groundwood papers.
   Great Northern stock, which soared $20.12{ on news of the buyout
offer Tuesday, dipped $1.37{ to $61.50 a share in heavy New York
Stock Exchange trading Wednesday.
   Great Northern's board of directors said Tuesday it would study
the unsolicited offer ``in due course'' before deciding on a
response.
   Workers in the Millinocket-area mills and across Great
Northern's 2.1 million acres of Maine timberlands received letters
from their employer saying it was moving ahead with business as
usual.
   The company, which has a pulp and paper mill in the Millinocket
area 80 miles north of Bangor in northern Maine, has 2,800 Maine
employees.
   Although it has stressed that it regarded the buyout offer as
friendly, Georgia Pacific has filed a U.S. District Court complaint
in Portland challenging Maine's anti-takeover law.
   Great Northern is incorporated in Maine. State law requires an
acquirer to wait five years before completing a merger unless the
deal wins prior approval from directors of the target company.
   Atlanta-based Georgia-Pacific also asked the court to throw out
several anti-takeover provisions in Great Northern's by-laws.
   In Augusta, the takeover bid dominated a State House news
briefing that followed a meeting between Gov. John R. McKernan and
leaders of the paperworkers' union.
   ``At this point, we don't know enough (about the implications)
to know what is in our best interests,'' said McKernan.
   McKernan had arranged the meeting, which was scheduled before
the takeover bid was made public, to discuss Great Northern's
tentative plan to build a new $484 million paper mill in a joint
venture with a West German papermaker.
   Edward Gorham of the Maine AFL-CIO, who attended the meeting,
said Great Northern had been reluctant to discuss whether displaced
union workers would be given the first shot at jobs in the new mill.
   He said labor leaders were waiting to see how a takeover would
affect that project, although he said ``there's not much cause for
optimism'' and that past Georgia-Pacific takeovers have led to
mills being shut down.
   McKernan said he had talked with officials from both companies
but got little information from either because ``everything is sort
of up in the air.''
   ``Great Northern has said they're continuing business as usual
until their board of directors tells them to do otherwise, which
means they will continue to move forward in their plans for the
expansion,'' he said.
   ``The people at Georgia-Pacific have said, obviously, they
haven't had a chance to look at the company in enough detail so
that if they were successful in their tender offer, that they would
be able to make any commitments.''
   McKernan said he stressed to both sides that he considered
construction of the new mill essential, regardless of who owned or
operated it.
</TEXT>
