<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market chalked up some uneven gains
Wednesday, struggling to maintain the momentum of Tuesday's rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which climbed 41.60 on
Tuesday, edged up .82 to 2,645.90.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
847 up, 644 down and 476 unchanged.
   Stock prices in general got a lift Tuesday from news of a
takeover bid by Georgia-Pacific for Great Northern Nekoosa.
   Analysts said the news was taken as reassurance that merger and
acquisition activity wasn't going to disappear as a result of
recent problems involving several debt-financed buyout plans.
   Nekoosa shares, after soaring 20[ on Tuesday, slipped back 1] to
61{ as the most active Big Board issue.
   At the same time, analysts said, worries persisted about the
numerous disappointments that showed up in corporate earnings for
the third quarter of the year.
   Those reports prompted talk of a possible significant slowdown
in the economy, and downward revisions of profit projections for
the rest of this year and early 1990.
   The next key item on the market agenda is expected to be
Friday's report from the Labor Department on the employment
situation for October.
   Advance estimates on Wall Street call for an increase in nonfarm
payroll employment of somewhere between 100,000 and 150,000, down
from 209,000 in September.
   Campbell Soup jumped 3] to 47[. Word of the resignation of
Gordon McGovern as president and chief executive stirred revived
takeover talk about the company.
   Georgia Gulf gained 1} to 51\. NL Industries, which holds a
stake of just under 10 percent of the company, offered to buy the
rest of the stock for $50 a share.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Philip Morris rose [ to 43[,
but International Business Machines dropped \ to 100; Ford Motor
fell \ to 47[; McDonald's lost [ to 30~, and American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph was down \ at 44.
   GenCorp dropped 2 to 14. The company said its fourth-quarter
earnings from continuing operations would be down significantly
from comparable levels a year ago.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 154.24 million
shares, against 176.10 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 183.77 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $9.69 billion, or 0.29
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .60 to 188.84.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose .88 to 389.42, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up .84 at 341.20.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
advanced 1.01 to 456.64. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 372.14, up 1.56.
