<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-01 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Futures Leap On Brazilian Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar futures prices exploded to 15{-month highs Wednesday on
New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange on news that Brazil, the
world's fourth-largest producer, was considering suspending sugar
exports.
   On other futures markets, coffee futures sank; pork bellies
continued to surge; copper advanced; precious metals slipped; oil
futures rallied; grains and soybeans rose; and stock-index futures
advanced.
   World sugar futures settled .45 cent to .56 cent higher in New
York with the contract for delivery in March at 14.53 cents a
pound, the highest settlement of a near-month sugar contract since
July 19, 1988.
   Brazilian authorities said they were studying the possibility of
suspending sugar exports from the country's 1989-90 sugar cane crop
but had made no decision.
   Analysts said Brazil might halt exports to divert more sugar
cane into production of alcohol for automobile fuel. Most of
Brazil's passenger cars burn alcohol.
   Earlier this year, the Brazilian Sugar and Alcohol Institute
projected production of 6.9 million metric tons of raw sugar for
the 1989-90 crop year, which began in September, with 645,000
metric tons earmarked for export.
   Last year, Brazil produced 8 million metric tons of sugar and
exported about 1.5 million.
   ``This situation is pretty severe,'' said Judith Ganes, an
analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``It remains
to be seen whether they are going to be able to meet their sugar
export commitments.''
   Coffee futures sank in New York amid fading prospects for a
return to export quotas, which were lifted in July, precipitating a
sharp drop in coffee prices.
   Green, unroasted coffee settled 1.6 cents to 2.31 cents lower
with December at 72.45 cents a pound.
   Pork-belly futures soared the permitted limit of 2 cents a pound
for the second consecutive day on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
amid expectations for new export demand.
   Hog futures rose sharply in line with the bellies while cattle
futures were mostly lower.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent to .25 cent lower with December at
74.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .15 cent lower
with November at 83.12 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to 1.08
cents higher with December at 47.65 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 2 cents higher across the board with February at 57.60
cents a pound.
   Near-month copper futures rose sharply on New York's Commodity
Exchange following news of an unexpectedly large 426-ton decline
Tuesday in the exchange's warehouse inventories.
   Copper settled 0.9 cent lower to 2.5 cents higher with December
at $1.165 a pound.
   Gold and silver futures slid lower on the Comex. Gold settled 70
cents to 90 cents lower with December at $376.90 a troy ounce;
silver was 3 cent lower across the board with December at $5.188 a
troy ounce.
   The surging heating oil market pulled energy futures higher for
the second straight day on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The rally was rooted in the American Petroleum Institute's
report late Tuesday of an unexpected 1.31 million-barrel drawdown
last week in U.S. stocks of petroleum distillates.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 13 cents to 19 cents
higher with December at $20.07 cents a barrel; heating oil was .06
cent to 1.25 cents higher with December at 60.36 cents gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .05 cent lower to .11 cent higher with
December at 52.89 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures rose on the Chicago Board of Trade,
ending a three-day decline amid expectations for new export
business and continued dryness in winter wheat country.
   Wheat futures settled 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher with December
at $3.98 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2 cents higher with
December at $2.37{ a bushel; oats were } cent to 1 cent higher with
December at $1.43{ a bushel; soybeans were \ cent to 4 cents higher
with November at $5.61} a bushel.
   Stock-index futures were mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of stocks in the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled .15 cent higher at 343.30. Each
point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
