<FIRST>u f AM-Guber-Peters     11-01 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guber-Peters,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tentative Deal Reached in Sony-Warner Battle Over Superproducers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. and Warner Communications Inc.
have reached a tentative agreement allowing Hollywood's hottest
producers, Peter Guber and Jon Peters, to jump to Sony's Columbia
Pictures, a source close to the negotiations said Wednesday.
   ``There's still a number of T's to be crossed, but it looks like
a done deal,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``It's going to cost Sony some.''
   The settlement would allow Guber and Peters, producers of such
hit films as ``Batman'' and ``Rain Man,'' to break their five-year
contract with Warner Bros. to head Columbia Pictures Entertainment.
   In a key part of the proposed settlement, Warner would receive
Columbia's 35 percent share in The Burbank Studios, the 150-acre
lot they jointly own, in exchange for the old MGM lot in Culver
City, which Warner acquired in its merger with Lorimar Telepictures
this year.
   Warner Bros. Records also would get a share of Sony's lucrative
CBS Record Club, which Sony acquired as part of its buyout of CBS
Records.
   Warner is nation's leading record company in the country,
followed by CBS. But Warner has no record club of its own and has
contracted with the CBS club and the old RCA club, now owned by
Germany's Bertelsmann Music Group, to provide records to members of
those clubs.
   Warner also would retain rights to the projects Guber and Peters
have under way or in development at Warner. Those include two
sequels to ``Batman,'' which already has grossed nearly $250
million at U.S. theaters.
   Warner, a unit of Time Warner Inc., says it already has invested
or committed $13 million in 50 projects under development by Guber
and Peters.
   Warner and Sony spokesmen declined comment.
   The loss of Guber and Peters would have scrambled Sony's
management plans for Columbia, to which it has made a $5 billion
commitment. In addition to buying Columbia for $3.4 billion, Sony
is paying $200 million for Guber-Peters Entertainment and will
assume payments on $1.5 billion in Columbia debt.
   Warner, on the other hand, stood to gain little by forcing Guber
and Peters to stay on if in doing so it only angered its star
producers.
   Both sides agreed Tuesday to postpone a court hearing Thursday
on Warner's request for an injunction barring Guber and Peters from
leaving, saying they needed time ``to allow the parties to have
further discussions.''
   The two producers contended Warner had an oral agreement to let
them out of their contract if they got the chance to run a major
studio. But Warner Bros. President Terry Semel denied that.
   ``I do not make oral agreements to terminate written agreements,
especially when they involve key talent and millions of dollars,''
Semel said in one of a series of affidavits filed in preparation
for the scheduled court hearing Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
