<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices finished mostly higher
Wednesday, led by a surge in heating oil prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, heating oil for December
delivery climbed 1.25 cents to 60.36 cents a gallon, while the
January contract rose 1.02 cents to 59.95 a gallon.
   Analysts said bullish weekly statistics from the American
Petroleum Institute and colder weather across the country
contributed to the increase.
   The latest API report showed that heating oil inventories fell
1.3 million barrels last week to 118.7 million barrels.
   Crude oil futures traded on the exchange also rose. The December
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. grade of
crude, rose 13 cents to finish at $20.07 per 42-gallon barrel.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for December delivery declined 0.05
cent to 52.89 cents a gallon, and the January contract advanced
0.11 cent to 52.71 cents.
   Analysts said crude prices gained despite an 8 million-barrel
increase in crude supplies to 344.5 million barrels, according to
API.
   ``It was a correction from last week when crude stocks fell by
about the same amount,'' said Richard Redoglio, energy broker with
Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Total gasoline supplies rose by 8,000 barrels, the API report
showed.
</TEXT>
