<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GeorgiaGulf     11-01 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Georgia Gulf,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>NL Makes $50-a-Share Offer for Georgia Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NL Industries Inc. renewed its courtship of
Georgia Gulf Corp. on Wednesday, disclosing it had made an
unsolicited $1.1 billion offer for the 90.1 percent stake in the
company it does not already own.
   Georgia Gulf said its board reviewed the NL Industries' proposal
as well as unspecified ``indications of interest from other third
parties'' about possible business combinations and would continue
to review its alternatives.
   ``No decision has been made to eliminate any alternatives from
consideration,'' Georgia Gulf said in a statement.
   It added that there can be no assurance that any transaction
will be recommended, authorized or completed.
   ``Discussions are being held with interested parties and work is
also continuing on other various transactions,'' the statement said.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Georgia Gulf stock
climbed $1.75 a share to $51.25.
   The offer NL Industries marked the first concrete proposal from
the company controlled by a Texas billionaire Harold C. Simmons,
but followed several overtures over the past few months.
   Simmons already owns about 9.9 percent of the chemical company's
25.6 million outstanding shares.
   John Garcia, an analyst with Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co. in New
York, said he viewed the offer as an attempt to drive up the price
of Georgia Gulf's stock.
   ``He saw some value and he wants to get a piece of it. He's a
moneymaker,'' Garcia said.
   NL President J. Landis Martin could not be reached for comment
Wednesday. He was out of his Houston office and did not return
messages left with his secretary.
   Simmons, through NL, has been buying and selling Georgia Gulf
stock since early summer.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission in
August, he said his then nearly 10 percent stake in Georgia Gulf
was no longer held simply for investment purposes. In September, he
reduced his stake in Georgia Gulf to below 9 percent and said he
was temporarily dropping a bid to oust the company's board of
directors. Later that month, he again increased his holdings in the
company to 9.9 percent.
   The latest offer for the Atlanta company comes about six weeks
after Georgia Gulf officials met with NL's Martin to discuss a
possible merger.
   No agreement was reached, and Georgia Gulf then asked its
financial advisers to explore the feasibility of what it called ``a
variety of alternative transactions,'' including a deal with NL.
   Georgia Gulf, a chemical company created in 1985 by
Georgia-Pacific Corp., had 1988 sales of $1.06 billion. Analysts
have said previously that a takeover would be difficult without the
consent of Georgia Gulf management, which owns a substantial
portion of the company.
</TEXT>
