<FIRST>u f AM-Telerate-DowJones     11-01 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Telerate-Dow Jones,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Extends Offer for Telerate Three More Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc. said Wednesday that it was
extending until Nov. 9 its $576 million offer for the 33 percent of
the electronic financial information company Telerate Inc. that it
does not already own.
   It was the second extension in the $18-a-share offer in the past
week.
   A special panel of Telerate directors previously rejected the
offer as inadequate and urged Dow Jones to negotiate a mutually
acceptable deal.
   The two sides have met several times, although the terms of the
offer have not been changed.
   Last Friday, Dow Jones said it was extending its tender offer
until 5 p.m. EST next Monday, and the latest action extends it
another three days. The tender offer originally was to expire this
Friday.
   In a filing Wednesday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Dow Jones said it was extending its offer because
Telerate had provided Dow Jones with a new forecast of financial
performance and Dow wants to review it.
   Peter Skinner, vice president and general counsel for Dow Jones,
said Telerate discussed the new forecast with Dow Jones at a
meeting Tuesday, and said he expects the two sides to meet again.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, Telerate rose 12{ cents a
share to $19.50.
   Dow Jones publishes The Wall Street Journal, Barron's magazine
and provides a variety of financial news services and data bases.
</TEXT>
