<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1922EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAL     11-01 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steinberg Seeks Approval to Buy More Than 15 Percent of UAL</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Saul Steinberg, who in recent months had
cut his stake in UAL Corp., filed Wednesday for federal approval to
purchase more than 15 percent of the parent of United Airlines.
   UAL announced that the filing was imminent, but refused to
comment further.
   A spokesman for New York-based Reliance Group Holdings Inc.,
which Steinberg chairs, confirmed that the company filed for
clearance with the Federal Trade Commission and the Justice
Department as required by federal antitrust law. But the spokesman
refused to comment further.
   Steinberg sold nearly 500,000 shares of UAL stock when it
rocketed to the $280-$290-per-share range following a buyout offer
by California billionaire Marvin Davis and the UAL board's
acceptance of a proposed $6.75 billion pilot-management bid.
   UAL stock plummeted more than $100 after the pilot-management
group failed to get financing for the deal. That announcement
helped to trigger an Oct. 13 stock market plunge.
   UAL stock closed $1{ higher at $177 Wednesday.
   Both Davis and the pilots have said they are exploring the
possibility of making a new bid.
   Kathie Hardin, a spokeswoman for the Air Line Pilots
Association, would not comment on the Reliance filing and refused
to say whether ALPA had been contacted by Reliance.
   Spokesmen for the International Association of Machinists, who
rebuffed Davis' latest advances, could not be reached for comment.
The Machinists refused to join the pilot-management buyout plan.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission Oct. 3,
Reliance said it had sold 499,000 shares of UAL common stock since
Sept. 5 for a total of $142.8 million. No reason for the sale was
given in the filing.
   The sale cut Steinberg's holding in UAL to 1.02 million shares,
or 4.7 percent. Previously he had held 6.99 percent of UAL's shares.
   An airline industry analyst said it was more likely that
Steinberg is looking to make a profit than maneuvering for a
takeover attempt.
   ``So far he's made a real lot of money,'' said Stephen Dexter,
of Kemper Financial Services Inc. in Chicago.
   ``Considering this fiasco we've just seen, Saul Steinberg may be
speculating that the board and (UAL Chairman) Steve Wolf are under
pressure to do something to reward shareholders,'' such as a
special dividend or a stock repurchase, Dexter said.
</TEXT>
