<DOCNO> AP891101-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 2138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Campbell-McGovern     11-01 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campbell-McGovern,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campbell Soup Announces Early Retirement of President R. Gordon McGovern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two months after announcing a worldwide
restructuring , Campbell Soup Co. said Wednesday that R. Gordon
McGovern, president and chief executive officer, plans to take an
early retirement.
   McGovern decided to step down for personal reasons, Robert J.
Vlasic, chairman of Campbell, said in a statement. McGovern had
been expected to retire in October 1991.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Campbell climbed
$3.37{ a share to $47.12{.
   But John M. McMillin, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., said he was not surprised by the resignation. ``To
put it in baseball terms _ the team wasn't winning,'' McMillin said.
   In September, Campbell reported fiscal 1989 earnings of $13
million, down sharply from the previous year because of a $343
million corporate restructuring charge. The restructuring included
the closing of manufacturing plants in New Jersey, Maryland and
Tennessee with a loss of 2,800 jobs.
   The restructuring of the nation's largest soup maker came four
months after the death of John T. Dorrance Jr., the son of the
inventor of condensed soup, who hesitated to lay off workers or
close plants.
   ``It shows the powerful changes that are taking place within
Campbell Soups'' said McMillin.
   The board had clearly been unhappy with Campbell's performance
in recent years and last November, Vlasic was tapped for the
chairman slot over McGovern.
   ``The new shareholders as well as the old were somewhat
dissatisified,'' said McMillin. ``Whether he was fired or resigned
is a question of semantics.''
   The retirement is effective Nov. 15, two days before the
company's annual shareholders meeting. Analysts say shareholders
will move quickly to find sucessor for McGovern who joined
Campbell's Pepperidge Farm subsidiary in 1956 as a management
trainee in Downington, Pa.
   ``I think the board would feel comfortable in accepting the
resignation _ paving the road for new leadership,'' said Marvin B.
Roffman, an analyst with the brokerage firm of Janney, Montgomery
Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
   Dorrance's heirs have attempted to squelch rumors that the
company may be up for sale, but analysts said the possibility
remains.
   ``I don't necessarily think a sale of the company is imminent,
but clearly the next alternative, if the new management can't get
this company up and running, might be the sale of the company,''
McMillin said.
   McGovern, who became president and CEO in 1980, has withdrawn
his name as a candidate for re-election at the meeting, the company
said. A replacement nominee will not be designated, the company
said.
   ``I leave with pride in our accomplishments and in the
management team now in place and with confidence in the company's
strategies for the future,'' the 63-year-old McGovern said in a
statement released by the company. ``The CEO succession process is
well along and I've decided for personal reasons to take early
retirement.''
   Campbell also announced the appointment Wednesday of Herbert M.
Baum, 53, and Edwin Harper, 47, as executive vice presidents. Baum
is president of Campbell U.S.A. and Harper is a senior vice
president and chief financial officer.
   Harper and Baum will assume the day-to-day operation of the
company on an interim basis, the company said. Both are also
candidates to succeed McGovern.
   Campbell spokesman James Moran said the board of directors
formed a management succession committee about a year ago in
anticipation of McGovern's retirement. He said a successor will not
be named at the shareholder's meeting.
   ``McGovern was getting up there in years,'' Moran said. ``They
had begun a search for a successor for him _ knowing he would
retire one day.''
   Under McGovern, Campbell's worldwide sales rose from $2.8
billion to $5.7 billion and net earnings climbed from $130 million
to $274 million, the company said. Campbell's sells about five
billion cans of soup a year, garnering about 65 percent of the $2.2
billion retail soup market.
</TEXT>
