<FIRST>u f AM-UpjohnRetirement     11-01 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Upjohn Retirement,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Upjohn Encouraging Early Retirements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Upjohn Co. announced an early retirement
plan Wednesday it expected would trim as many as 350 workers from
the company's U.S. payroll of 12,000 to 13,000 employees.
   Upjohn spokesman Bob LaRue said there was no estimate of how
much money the program would save the pharmaceutical company
because that depends on how many workers take the retirement offer.
   He said about 1,100 employees are eligible, and that 50 percent
to 60 percent of them would take part in the program. About half
the anticipated vacancies created by the retirement program might
be filled with new workers, LaRue said.
   No part of the company's U.S. business was exempt from the
program.
   ``Over the past two years, we have followed a strategy in which
we exercised budget constraints and implemented an effective
headcount control program,'' Upjohn Chairman Theodore Cooper said
in a statement. ``By offering attractive terms to employees who are
on the retirement threshold, we can further our strategic
objectives by accelerating our corporate restructuring.''
   Employees aged 55 or older, whose combined age and experience
with the company add up to 75, are eligible. A formula based on
seniority and other matters could boost retirement pay 10 percent
to 20 percent per employee.
   Upjohn, which employs about 21,300 people worldwide,
manufactures human and animal health products, seeds and specialty
chemicals.
</TEXT>
