<HEAD>Panama Rescinds Order Against UPI Correspondent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Press International said the government
of Panama on Wednesday rescinded its order for the news agency's
U.S.-born correspondent to leave the country.
   ``We made no concessions. We simply argued under the Panamanian
constitution freedom of the press,'' said Milt Capps, UPI's vice
president for corporate affairs. ``We will continue to report from
there,'' he said.
   After a meeting between UPI and government officials in Panama,
Capps said the company received a new order at midday Wednesday
which countermanded the previous dictum ``in all its parts.''
   Last week the Panamaniam Ministry of Government and Justice
ordered UPI to get its U.S.-born correspondent out of the country
within five days because it objected to what it called a pattern of
negative reporting of recent events by the news service.
