<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 2010EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CircuitBreakers     11-01 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Circuit Breakers,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Merc Seeks Tougher Circuit Breakers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange on Wednesday
announced plans for tougher price limits on stock-index futures
that would further restrict certain types of program trading during
a stock-market collapse.
   The biggest proposed change in the so-called ``circuit
breakers'' is a 40 percent tighter restriction in how far the price
of Standard &amp; Poor's 500 stock-index futures can fall before the
Merc halts selling for the rest of a day's session.
   The proposals, which require approval by the federal Commodity
Futures Trading Commission, also would add a fourth circuit breaker
to the three that have been in effect for more than a year.
   The Merc proposals come amid a barrage of criticism of certain
computerized, or program, trading strategies involving stock-index
futures that some experts blame for recent wild price swings in the
stock market.
   The Merc is the world's biggest market for the most popular
stock-index futures, those based on the Standard &amp; Poor's index of
500 stocks traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
   An S&amp;P 500 future is a contract to buy or sell all 500 of those
stocks at a specified price by a specified date.
   In a program trading technique called index arbitrage, traders
use computers to rapidly buy and sell huge blocks of stocks in New
York and the underlying stock-index futures in Chicago in an
attempt to profit from minute differences in prices on the two
markets.
   Chicago Merc officials said their proposed modifications stemmed
from studies of the sharp market drops on Oct. 13 and 24, when some
of the circuit breakers were triggered.
   Under the proposals:
   _S&amp;P 500 futures would be allowed to fall no more than 5 points
_ the equivalent of 40 points in the Dow Jones industrial average _
during the first 10 minutes of trading. Currently, the 5-point-drop
restriction lapses if the S&amp;P contract rebounds from that lower
level within the 10-minute period.
   _The current limit of a 12-point drop in the S&amp;P contract,
roughly equal to 100 Dow points, would remain in effect, halting
selling below that level for 30 minutes.
   _Under a new rule, if the futures market falls 20 S&amp;P points,
which is roughly equivalent to 150 Dow points, trading below that
level would be halted for one hour. If the 20-point limit is
triggered after 1:30 p.m. Central time, the restriction would
remain in effect until the end of the session at 4:15 p.m.
   _The absolute daily point-drop limit would be tightened to 30
S&amp;P points, equal to about 250 Dow points, from 50 S&amp;P points,
roughly equal to 400 Dow points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
