<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-RalstonPurina     11-01 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Ralston Purina,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ralston Purina Reports 46 Percent Drop in Quarterly Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralston Purina Co., a pet food, baker and
battery maker, reported Wednesday a 46 percent drop in earnings for
its fiscal fourth quarter due mainly to a one-time charge to close
two plants and eliminate some jobs.
   Its profit for the fiscal year, which ended Sept. 30, increased
8 percent compared with last year, while sales were up 13 percent.
   For the quarter, its profit totaled $45.2 million, or 65 cents a
share, down from $84.9 million, or $1.24 a share, for the same
period a year ago.
   Sales for the quarter were $1.76 billion, up slightly from $1.55
billion in the same quarter last year.
   The profit decline came in part because of a $31.4 million
pre-tax charge the company took to close a battery plant in
Greenville, S.C., and a bakery in Cincinnati, said Ralston
spokesman Patrick Farrell.
   He said the company also made staff cuts at its computer
operations center in St. Louis that figured into the charge.
   Even without the charges, however, its profit would have slipped
by nearly 10 percent, Farrell said.
   He said the company, the largest seller of dry dog food and
moist and dry cat food, had higher advertising and promotion costs,
sold less pet food and incurred higher costs for pet food
ingredients in the quarter.
   The company's Continental Baking subsidiary had slightly higher
profits in the quarter, but its Eveready battery business suffered
a decrease primarily because of the plant closing and economic
problems in South America.
   The company does not provide specific financial data about its
various subsidiaries.
   For the fiscal year, net earnings were $422.5 million, up from
last year's $387.8 million. Sales were $6.65 billion, compared with
$5.87 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
