<FIRST>u f BC-MinimumWage-Glance 1stLd-Writethru f0319 11-01 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Minimum Wage-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0319,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Provisions of the Minimum Wage Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS ``The Subminimum'' section to note that subminimum
may never fall below $3.35; CORRECTS $3.21 in table to $3.35. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are key provisions of the legislation to
increase the minimum wage to $4.25 an hour while creating a new
subminimum wage for certain teen-age workers. The bill becomes
effective next April 1.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THE RATE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The minimum wage, $3.35 an hour since January 1981, would
increase to $3.80 on April 1, 1990 and to $4.25 on April 1, 1991.
The Labor Department last year estimated that nearly 4 million
Americans worked at the minimum wage.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THE SUBMINIMUM</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers 16-19 may be paid 85 percent of the prevailing minimum
wage for their first three months in the work force, and for an
additional three months if receiving formal training. No one over
20 or with six months total job experience may be paid the
subminimum, and the subminimum may never fall below the current
minimum, $3.35. The subminimum expires in April 1993.
   Here is the subminimum at each new level of the minimum:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
      
</TEXT>
<NOTE> Min SubMin</NOTE>
<TEXT>
      $3.80 $3.35
    4.25  3.61
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TIP CREDIT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Employers may now pay workers who receive tips 40 percent of the
minimum wage provided the tips bring the hourly pay at least to the
minimum. That will be 45 percent on April 1 and 50 percent a year
later.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>SMALL BUSINESS EXEMPTION</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Small businesses with gross sales of $362,500 currently are
exempt from the federal minimum wage law, although all but eight
states have their own minimum wage laws and their exemptions vary.
The federal exemption would expand to $500,000.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>OTHER EXEMPTIONS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The bill continues the more than four pages of thousands of
special exemptions already in the law. Examples are some farm
workers, including tobacco leaf harvesters; casual babysitters,
newspaper delivery workers, amusement park employees, wreath
makers, employees at small radio stations in cities with a
population below 25,000 and mullusk and crustacean harvesters (for
example, clams and lobsters).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
