<FIRST>r f AM-AmocoCadiz 1stLd-Writethru f0163 11-01 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amoco Cadiz, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0163,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>$100 Million Damages Recommended in Amoco Cadiz</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Amoco comment, none
from plaintiffs. Picks up 5th graf pvs, McGarr found...'. Also moving on
general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amoco Corp. should pay about $100 million for
damages incurred when its Amoco Cadiz tanker ran aground, spilling
68 million gallons of crude oil off the coast of France in 1978, a
judge has decided.
   The final judgment, which includes interest, was recommended
Tuesday by former U.S. District Court Judge Frank McGarr, who was
appointed special master in the case after retiring from the bench
in January 1988.
   McGarr filed his recommendations with U.S. District Court Judge
Charles Norgle, who gave attorneys on both sides until Nov. 14 to
file objections. The recommendations must receive final approval by
a federal judge.
   ``We have maintained all along that the claim of damages from
this unfortunate incident were exaggerated,'' Amoco spokesman Mike
Thompson said Wednesday. ``And we intend to appeal.''
   Attorneys for the plaintiffs did not return telephone calls
Wednesday seeking comment.
   McGarr found Amoco, formerly Standard Oil of Indiana, and a
Spanish shipbuilding firm liable for damages. The second phase of
the trial, which is still not resolved, was to determine the cost
of damages.
   The French government and other plaintiffs had sought more than
$1 billion in damages. The oil spill off the Brittany coast
devastated sealife, including valuable oyster beds in the area, and
impinged on the tourism trade.
</TEXT>
