<FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 2327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-RandomHouseResignation     11-01 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Random House Resignation,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishing Company Head Retires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert L. Bernstein, chairman, president and
chief executive officer of Random House Inc., will retire from the
publishing company at the end of the year, it was announced
Wednesday.
   S.I. Newhouse Jr., chairman of Advance Publications Inc., which
owns Random House, indicated that a successor would be announced
soon, according to William T. Loverd, a spokesman for the
publishing house.
   Loverd said Bernstein would work closely with whomever is named.
   Bernstein, 66, joined Random House in 1957 and is just the
second president in the company's 64-year history, Loverd said. He
succeeded Random House's founder, Bennett Cerf, as president in
1966.
   During Bernstein's 23 years as head of the company, annual sales
increased from $40 million to $800 million this year, Loverd said.
   According to Loverd, ``after long and careful thought, Mr.
Bernstein indicated that he had decided to retire and had submitted
his resignation.''
   Newhouse accepted the resignation with regret, Loverd said.
   Bernstein was very involved in building Random House's juvenile
book department, Loverd said. Dr. Seuss was among the authors with
whom he had important relationships; others included John Hersey,
Robert A. Caro, James A. Michener, Robert Ludlum and E.L. Doctorow.
   Bernstein plans to continue his work in the international human
rights movement, Loverd said. He is the founder and chairman of the
Watch Committees (which include the Helsinki Watch, the Americas
Watch and the Asia Watch, among others) and of the Fund for Free
Expression.
   He brought to Random House the writings of some of the world's
prominent dissident figures, including Andrei Sakharov, Yelena
Bonner and Natan Scharansky, Loverd said.
   Random House is the largest general trade publisher in the
United States and one of the world's principal book publishers.
   Advance Publications also owns 26 daily newspapers, Newhouse
Broadcasting, The New Yorker, Details, Parade and Conde Nast
Publications. Conde Nast includes magazines such as Vogue, Glamour,
Vanity Fair and GQ.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
