<FIRST>u f AM-RandomHouse-Resignation 1stLd-Writethru f0345 11-01
0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Random House-Resignation, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0345,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishing Company Head Resigns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with quotes from Bernstein. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert L. Bernstein, chairman, president and
chief executive officer of Random House Inc., will step down at the
end of the year, the publishing giant announced Wednesday.
   S.I. Newhouse Jr., chairman of Advance Publications Inc., which
owns Random House, indicated that a successor would be announced
soon, according to William T. Loverd, a spokesman for Random House.
   Random House is the largest general-interest book publisher in
the United States and one of the world's principal publishers.
   Bernstein, 66, joined Random House in 1957 and is just the
second president in the company's 64-year-history, Loverd said. He
succeeded Random House's founder, Bennett Cerf, as president in
1966.
   During Bernstein's 23 years as head of the company, annual sales
volume increased to $800 million this year from $40 million, Loverd
said.
   According to Loverd, ``after long and careful thought Mr.
Bernstein indicated that he had decided to retire and had submitted
his resignation.''
   Newhouse accepted the resignation with regret, Loverd said.
   Bernstein, who three years ago declared, ``I want to be a
publisher until I'm carried out,'' said his decision to step down
``evolved out of talks with Si,'' as Newhouse is known, The New
York Times reported.
   ``There was no serious disagreement between Si and myself. It's
not as though there was some incident. It just seemed the right
thing to do,'' Bernstein said.
   Loverd said Bernstein would work closely with whomever is named
as his successor.
   Bernstein was very involved in building Random House's juvenile
department, Loverd said. Dr. Seuss was among the authors with whom
he had important relationships; others included John Hersey, Robert
A. Caro, James A. Michener, Robert Ludlum and E.L. Doctorow.
   Bernstein plans to continue his work in the international human
rights movement, Loverd said. He is the founder and chairman of the
Watch Committees (which include the Helsinki Watch, the Americas
Watch and the Asia Watch, among others) and of the Fund for Free
Expression.
   He brought to Random House some of the world's prominent
dissident figures including Andrei Sakharov, Yelena Bonner and
Natan Scharansky, Loverd said.
   Advance Publications also includes 26 daily newspapers, Newhouse
Broadcasting, The New Yorker, Details, Parade and Conde Nast
Publications. Conde Nast publishes magazines such as Vogue,
Glamour, Vanity Fair and GQ.
</TEXT>
